WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:15.240 --> 00:00:16.600
&gt;&gt; Mary Jane Deeb:
Okay, good morning.

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:18.970
Good morning, everybody.

00:00:18.970 --> 00:00:21.440
Good morning.

00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:26.010
I'm Mary Jane Deeb, chief of
the African/Middle East division

00:00:26.010 --> 00:00:28.490
which is hosting this event.

00:00:28.490 --> 00:00:32.510
And as the division has
acquired the online Omar Said

00:00:32.510 --> 00:00:36.940
autobiography that we are all
gathered here today to discuss.

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:40.260
These items are now held
by the Rare Books division

00:00:40.260 --> 00:00:44.450
where you will have a chance
to view them this afternoon.

00:00:44.450 --> 00:00:48.640
But this morning it is my honor
and privilege to introduce

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:53.480
to you Dr. Carla Hayden, the
14th Librarian of Congress

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:56.010
who will welcome
you to the library.

00:00:56.010 --> 00:00:59.870
Before coming to the library,
Dr. Hayden served as CEO

00:00:59.870 --> 00:01:04.040
of the Enoch Pratt Free Library
in Baltimore and was nominated

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:08.020
by President Obama to be a
member of the National Museum

00:01:08.020 --> 00:01:10.280
and Library Services Board.

00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:11.580
She was also president

00:01:11.580 --> 00:01:17.060
of the American Library
Association from 2003 to 2004.

00:01:17.060 --> 00:01:19.770
Prior to joining
the Pratt Library,

00:01:19.770 --> 00:01:23.220
Dr. Hayden was deputy
commissioner and chief librarian

00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:27.170
of the Chicago Public
Library from '91 to '93,

00:01:27.170 --> 00:01:30.480
and assistant professor
library and information science

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:34.510
at University of
Pittsburgh from '87 to '91.

00:01:34.510 --> 00:01:38.950
She was also library services
coordinator for the Museum

00:01:38.950 --> 00:01:44.030
of Science and Industry in
Chicago from '82 to '87.

00:01:44.030 --> 00:01:47.230
And she began her career with
the Chicago Public Library

00:01:47.230 --> 00:01:52.340
as the young adult services
coordinator from '79 to '82

00:01:52.340 --> 00:01:53.640
and as library associate

00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:57.170
and children's librarian
from '73 to '79.

00:01:57.170 --> 00:02:01.240
Dr. Hayden received a BA from
Roosevelt University and an MA

00:02:01.240 --> 00:02:04.010
and PhD from the
Graduate Library School

00:02:04.010 --> 00:02:07.160
at the University of Chicago.

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:08.990
She has received numerous --

00:02:08.990 --> 00:02:12.220
and you can go online
and see numerous awards

00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:13.920
and honorary doctorates.

00:02:13.920 --> 00:02:17.320
I would be here the whole
morning just to say it.

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:21.260
So let us welcome Dr. Hayden.

00:02:22.510 --> 00:02:28.450
[ Applause ]

00:02:28.450 --> 00:02:30.890
&gt;&gt; Dr. Carla Hayden: Thank
you, thank you, Dr. Deeb.

00:02:30.890 --> 00:02:34.480
Only my mother could do
a better job at that.

00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:39.060
And as you went through every
year I kept telling the young

00:02:39.060 --> 00:02:42.640
people, I am getting
older and older and older.

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:46.770
But good morning and Dr.
Deeb, I just want to start

00:02:46.770 --> 00:02:49.320
out by thanking you
for your perseverance

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:51.130
and what you have done.

00:02:51.130 --> 00:02:52.890
And I'm not going
to break any news,

00:02:52.890 --> 00:02:56.680
but we really appreciate
your service.

00:02:56.680 --> 00:02:57.980
So thank you.

00:02:57.980 --> 00:03:00.510
And I think we can
give her a hand.

00:03:00.510 --> 00:03:04.090
[ Applause ]

00:03:04.090 --> 00:03:05.910
So good morning and welcome.

00:03:05.910 --> 00:03:10.200
I'm delighted to
be here with you

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:14.370
as we celebrate African American
history month and the launch

00:03:14.370 --> 00:03:19.560
of the online publication
of the Omar Said Collection

00:03:19.560 --> 00:03:22.640
which was purchased in 2017.

00:03:22.640 --> 00:03:26.730
And this unique collection
consists of documents

00:03:26.730 --> 00:03:33.420
in both English and Arabic,
including an 1831 autobiography,

00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:35.930
handwritten in Arabic.

00:03:36.980 --> 00:03:41.810
Mr. Said was a west African
scholar who at the age

00:03:41.810 --> 00:03:46.110
of 37 was captured,
enslaved and brought

00:03:46.110 --> 00:03:50.100
to South Carolina in 1804.

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:52.340
And this document,
the autobiography,

00:03:52.340 --> 00:03:56.590
is the centerpiece of the
collection that includes texts

00:03:56.590 --> 00:03:59.570
which will be discussed
throughout the day

00:03:59.570 --> 00:04:05.670
by prominent scholars and
library experts who acquired,

00:04:05.670 --> 00:04:07.990
worked on the preservation,
cataloged

00:04:07.990 --> 00:04:09.480
and digitized the collection

00:04:09.480 --> 00:04:14.230
and then created what I think
is a very wonderful website

00:04:14.230 --> 00:04:17.980
that we are launching for
the whole world to see.

00:04:17.980 --> 00:04:21.920
And you can see it takes a
village to present a Library

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:24.440
of Congress collection
to the public.

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:29.120
And it requires expertise
and technological

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:33.730
and technical capacities
that showcase the expertise

00:04:33.730 --> 00:04:36.210
of the library's staff.

00:04:36.210 --> 00:04:40.120
This collection and all of the
library's collections are used

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:45.540
by scholars and researchers and
anyone and everyone who wants

00:04:45.540 --> 00:04:50.110
to come in and learn about the
items regardless of their age.

00:04:50.110 --> 00:04:53.480
And so what about
the Said collection?

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:55.880
Who apart from the
scholars and the researchers

00:04:55.880 --> 00:04:58.340
and library staff
would be interested?

00:04:58.340 --> 00:05:03.860
Well, high school students
who are here today.

00:05:03.860 --> 00:05:07.440
And we have a special
treat for you today.

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:10.500
The Richard Wright Public
Charter School for Journalism

00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:12.640
and Media Arts in
Washington DC --

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:16.510
and I told them to shout out --

00:05:16.510 --> 00:05:20.170
[ Applause ]

00:05:20.170 --> 00:05:22.430
And the Montgomery
Blaire High School

00:05:22.430 --> 00:05:25.510
in Silver Spring Maryland.

00:05:25.510 --> 00:05:28.040
[ Applause ]

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:30.190
It's like the Super Bowls again.

00:05:30.190 --> 00:05:33.910
But Super Bowl of
research and history,

00:05:33.910 --> 00:05:36.030
and that's what's so exciting.

00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:41.290
Well, both schools and
I say young scholars

00:05:41.290 --> 00:05:44.810
in both schools have been so
fascinated by the collection

00:05:44.810 --> 00:05:47.260
that they have actually
come to the library,

00:05:47.260 --> 00:05:49.550
viewed the collection,
did research,

00:05:49.550 --> 00:05:51.530
met with the specialist
and experts

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:55.090
and then interviewed
and filmed them.

00:05:55.090 --> 00:05:58.200
And like professional
journalists and camera people,

00:05:58.200 --> 00:06:01.280
they have created special
videos of the collection

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:04.210
and they will be sharing them
with you during the lunch hour.

00:06:04.210 --> 00:06:09.630
So I want you to please welcome
them and show your appreciation

00:06:09.630 --> 00:06:12.440
and tell them how proud we
are that they are carrying

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:16.330
on the tradition of being
interested in history

00:06:16.330 --> 00:06:17.900
and bringing history to life.

00:06:17.900 --> 00:06:19.700
Let's give them a hand.

00:06:19.700 --> 00:06:25.990
[ Applause ]

00:06:25.990 --> 00:06:31.440
So, we will now have Marieta
Harper to say a few words

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:35.650
in memory of Mr. Derrick
Beard who was the last owner

00:06:35.650 --> 00:06:39.850
of the collection, and who
wanted so much for it to be

00:06:39.850 --> 00:06:42.340
at the Library of Congress.

00:06:42.340 --> 00:06:46.980
Marieta is an African and
Africa area specialist.

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:51.430
And she first identified
this collection and thanks

00:06:51.430 --> 00:06:56.150
to her perseverance, the
library was able to purchase it.

00:06:56.150 --> 00:06:59.510
So please join me
in welcoming her.

00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:06.500
[ Applause ]

00:07:16.870 --> 00:07:18.600
&gt;&gt; Marieta Harper: Good morning.

00:07:18.600 --> 00:07:22.610
As you just heard, my
name is Marieta Harper

00:07:22.610 --> 00:07:27.190
and I am Africa area
specialist in the African

00:07:27.190 --> 00:07:30.420
and Middle Eastern division

00:07:30.420 --> 00:07:35.630
at this institution,
Library of Congress.

00:07:35.630 --> 00:07:40.900
In January 2002, I
met Derrick Beard,

00:07:40.900 --> 00:07:43.790
the prominent antiquarian
book dealer

00:07:43.790 --> 00:07:48.220
of African American
historical collections.

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:53.620
He was visiting our division
while we were organizing a panel

00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:55.160
on the historical roots

00:07:55.160 --> 00:08:00.900
of Muslim immigration
to the United States.

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:07.450
The symposium was entitled Islam
in America and was sponsored

00:08:07.450 --> 00:08:12.250
by the African and Middle
Eastern Division and the Office

00:08:12.250 --> 00:08:14.420
of Scholarly Programs.

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:19.090
I coordinated the first
panel of the symposium

00:08:19.090 --> 00:08:23.160
and Derrick Beard was
the first speaker.

00:08:24.170 --> 00:08:30.120
During this visit, Mr. Beard
showed me his collection

00:08:30.120 --> 00:08:38.700
of historic Arabic manuscripts
written by Omar Ibn Said,

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:43.670
along with other manuscripts
written by African Muslims

00:08:43.670 --> 00:08:48.070
from the 18th and
19th centuries.

00:08:48.070 --> 00:08:58.700
At the end of the symposium, Mr.
Beard told Dr. Mary Jane Deeb

00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:01.720
and me that he felt the Library

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:06.920
of Congress should purchase
his unique collection

00:09:06.920 --> 00:09:11.670
so the world could see

00:09:11.670 --> 00:09:18.130
and research Arabic manuscripts
written by literate Africans

00:09:18.130 --> 00:09:22.060
who were enslaved in
the early Americas.

00:09:23.370 --> 00:09:28.120
When Derrick Beard finally put
his collection of manuscripts

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:31.390
on sale, he informed me

00:09:31.390 --> 00:09:36.090
and I then initiated the
recommendation for the Library

00:09:36.090 --> 00:09:40.790
of Congress to purchase
this collection.

00:09:40.790 --> 00:09:47.140
So after much determination,
we were able to locate funds

00:09:47.140 --> 00:09:49.110
to purchase the collection.

00:09:49.110 --> 00:09:56.810
The purchase was completed
in early winter of 2017.

00:09:56.810 --> 00:10:03.170
Regretfully, months
after the sale,

00:10:03.170 --> 00:10:10.160
Derrick Beard died in July 2018.

00:10:10.160 --> 00:10:14.920
I am still shocked by his death,

00:10:14.920 --> 00:10:18.500
even though I knew he was
critically ill throughout

00:10:18.500 --> 00:10:21.390
our negotiations.

00:10:21.390 --> 00:10:26.810
Derrick Beard was a consummate
connoisseur of various arts

00:10:26.810 --> 00:10:31.170
and collectibles and
was recognized as one

00:10:31.170 --> 00:10:38.310
of the world's preeminent
experts in his field,

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:42.040
which was the art world.

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:46.090
He was a collector
of American, Islamic

00:10:46.090 --> 00:10:52.850
and other foreign decorative
arts, including photography,

00:10:52.850 --> 00:11:00.600
paintings, rare books, unique
documents and other objects

00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:04.510
of aesthetic and
historical value.

00:11:04.510 --> 00:11:10.800
The Art and Antiques Magazine
listed Mr. Beard as one

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:15.110
of the top 100 American
collectors

00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:21.710
in 1994 and again in 2005.

00:11:21.710 --> 00:11:26.020
Prior to his death, Derrick
Beard resided in Dubai,

00:11:26.020 --> 00:11:29.690
the United Arab Emirates.

00:11:29.690 --> 00:11:34.870
His 20-plus years of foreign
travels included residencies

00:11:34.870 --> 00:11:44.830
in Europe, Asia, South
America and the Caribbean.

00:11:44.830 --> 00:11:47.500
Asia, sorry.

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:49.280
Derrick Beard's broad

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:54.250
and extensive academic
background included a BS

00:11:54.250 --> 00:11:56.930
in real estate finance
from the University

00:11:56.930 --> 00:12:01.290
of Illinois Urbana-Champagne.

00:12:01.290 --> 00:12:05.640
And additional advanced
studies in interior architecture

00:12:05.640 --> 00:12:08.530
at the Art Institute of Chicago.

00:12:08.530 --> 00:12:13.080
Studies in photography
at Loyola University,

00:12:13.080 --> 00:12:15.900
studies in mechanical
engineering

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:22.570
at Tuskegee University,
studies in Islamic finance

00:12:22.570 --> 00:12:24.860
at Harvard University,

00:12:24.860 --> 00:12:29.810
and studies in earth
architecture construction

00:12:29.810 --> 00:12:32.780
and management at the
California Institute

00:12:32.780 --> 00:12:37.350
of Earth and Architecture.

00:12:38.670 --> 00:12:42.130
In acknowledging
these few aspects

00:12:42.130 --> 00:12:45.860
of Derrick Beard's
background and accomplishment,

00:12:45.860 --> 00:12:52.950
we bid farewell to one of
America's greatest collectors.

00:12:54.170 --> 00:13:04.530
May his soul rest in peace.

00:13:04.530 --> 00:13:12.410
I will now share the memorial
tribute to Derrick Tyreek Beard

00:13:12.410 --> 00:13:18.460
from the Mashid Asabar
Derrick Beard's mosque

00:13:18.460 --> 00:13:22.500
in Los Angeles, Nevada.

00:13:22.500 --> 00:13:33.730
"In the name of Allah most
gracious, most merciful,

00:13:33.730 --> 00:13:41.570
it is with deepest regret
that you are being advised

00:13:41.570 --> 00:13:46.500
of the recent death of our
dear brother Derrick Beard.

00:13:47.550 --> 00:13:53.170
Brother Derrick Beard was an
amazing giant regarding the

00:13:53.170 --> 00:14:02.640
history, culture and ethnologic
research of Islam in America

00:14:02.640 --> 00:14:07.890
and its reclamation
and preservation.

00:14:08.930 --> 00:14:13.640
Among his numerous and most
notable contributions was the

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:21.570
purchase of the original Arabic
handwritten autobiography

00:14:21.570 --> 00:14:29.680
manuscript of Omar Ibn Said
and having it translated

00:14:29.680 --> 00:14:33.360
and published in the
English language.

00:14:34.610 --> 00:14:39.340
For years, Derrick
would actually travel

00:14:39.340 --> 00:14:41.590
with the original manuscript,

00:14:41.590 --> 00:14:46.170
taking it to various
public events and activities

00:14:46.170 --> 00:14:52.340
and allowing the general
public to examine it as well

00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:56.390
as take photos with it.

00:14:56.390 --> 00:15:00.540
His involvement in the
research and acquisition

00:15:00.540 --> 00:15:06.720
of rare Islamic historical
artifacts relevant

00:15:06.720 --> 00:15:12.980
to their impact in early
America was phenomenal.

00:15:12.980 --> 00:15:19.450
Derrick was always available
and approachable by anyone.

00:15:19.450 --> 00:15:24.920
He was an African
American giant of Islam

00:15:24.920 --> 00:15:29.420
who will be dearly missed.

00:15:29.420 --> 00:15:35.140
May Allah grant him paradise."

00:15:38.150 --> 00:15:43.800
This is the Islamic funeral
prayer sent on Friday,

00:15:43.800 --> 00:15:55.320
July 27th, 2018 by Masjid
As-Sabur 711 Morgan Avenue,

00:15:55.320 --> 00:15:58.020
Las Vegas, Nevada.

00:15:58.020 --> 00:16:01.510
Thank you.

00:16:01.510 --> 00:16:08.500
[ Applause ]

