[ Inaudible ]

00:18:08.390 --> 00:18:15.170
And before joining the library
he was director of marketing

00:18:15.170 --> 00:18:17.330
and communications at
PCNG international.

00:18:17.330 --> 00:18:22.710
What I'm going to do now is I'm
going to read the biographies

00:18:22.710 --> 00:18:24.010
of each one of the speakers.

00:18:24.010 --> 00:18:25.310
[ Inaudible ]

00:18:25.310 --> 00:18:27.470
But I am doing this because this
programming is being webcast.

00:18:27.470 --> 00:18:29.420
And as people watching

00:18:29.420 --> 00:18:33.620
around the world will not have
biographies, I'm going to share

00:18:33.620 --> 00:18:38.130
with them and with you
the bios of the panel.

00:18:38.130 --> 00:18:45.200
So Dr. Sylviane Diuof is
an award-winning historian

00:18:45.200 --> 00:18:48.110
and curator of the
African diaspora.

00:18:48.110 --> 00:18:51.510
She is the holder of --

00:18:51.510 --> 00:18:57.040
[ Inaudible ]

00:18:57.040 --> 00:19:01.570
It's 15th anniversary
edition was released in 2013.

00:19:01.570 --> 00:19:07.090
Her book Dreams of Africa in
Alabama: The Slave Ship Clodilda

00:19:07.090 --> 00:19:10.690
and the Story of the Last
Africans Brought to America,

00:19:10.690 --> 00:19:14.270
published by Oxford
University Press received prizes

00:19:14.270 --> 00:19:17.120
from the American
Historical Association,

00:19:17.120 --> 00:19:19.680
the Alabama Historical
Association

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:21.060
and the first Legacy Award.

00:19:21.060 --> 00:19:26.560
Dr. Diuof is the author
of Slavery's Exiles:

00:19:26.560 --> 00:19:29.650
The Story of the American
Maroons, also published

00:19:29.650 --> 00:19:32.270
by New York University Press.

00:19:32.270 --> 00:19:35.080
She is the editor of
Fighting the Slave Trade:

00:19:35.080 --> 00:19:37.190
West African Strategies,

00:19:37.190 --> 00:19:40.090
published by Ohio
University Press.

00:19:40.090 --> 00:19:43.910
And In Motion: The African
American Migration Experience,

00:19:43.910 --> 00:19:45.210
a National Geographic Book.

00:19:45.210 --> 00:19:48.350
Dr. Diuof received
the Rosa Parks Award,

00:19:48.350 --> 00:19:49.650
the [inaudible] Achievement
Award

00:19:49.650 --> 00:19:52.500
and the Shabazz Achievement
Award.

00:19:52.500 --> 00:19:58.850
She was the inaugural
director of the Lapidus Center

00:19:58.850 --> 00:20:02.500
for the Historical Analysis
of Transatlantic Slavery.

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:05.410
And is history professor at
Brown University's Center

00:20:05.410 --> 00:20:09.170
for the Study of
Slavery and Justice.

00:20:09.170 --> 00:20:16.030
Our second speaker sitting next
to Dr. Diuof is Dr. Adam Rothman

00:20:16.030 --> 00:20:23.260
who is a professor in
the history department

00:20:23.260 --> 00:20:25.950
at Georgetown University
where he teaches undergraduate

00:20:25.950 --> 00:20:27.250
and graduate courses
on the history

00:20:27.250 --> 00:20:28.780
of slavery and Atlantic history.

00:20:28.780 --> 00:20:32.390
Rothman's first book, Slave
Country, American expansion

00:20:32.390 --> 00:20:34.380
and the origin of
the deep south,

00:20:34.380 --> 00:20:38.500
published by Harvard University
Press in 2005, traced the roots

00:20:38.500 --> 00:20:40.060
of slavery in the
early United States.

00:20:40.060 --> 00:20:44.230
His latest book, Beyond
Freedom's Reach: A Kidnapping

00:20:44.230 --> 00:20:47.680
in the Twilight of
Slavery, Harvard 2015,

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:52.540
tells the true story of three
slave children who were taken

00:20:52.540 --> 00:20:55.010
from New Orleans to
Havana during the Civil War

00:20:55.010 --> 00:20:58.040
and their mother's
quest to rescue them.

00:20:58.040 --> 00:21:00.960
It won awards from the
America Civil War Museum,

00:21:00.960 --> 00:21:03.270
Louisiana Endowment
for the Humanities

00:21:03.270 --> 00:21:06.210
and the American
Librarian Association.

00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:10.170
He has written for The
Atlantic, the Daily Beast,

00:21:10.170 --> 00:21:14.350
Al-Jazeera America and the
New York Times Disunion Blog.

00:21:14.350 --> 00:21:18.930
He has been the recipient of an
ACLS Oscar Handley Fellowship

00:21:18.930 --> 00:21:20.710
and is an Organization

00:21:20.710 --> 00:21:23.040
of American Historians
distinguished lecturer.

00:21:23.040 --> 00:21:26.110
He was a member of Georgetown
University's working group

00:21:26.110 --> 00:21:29.340
on slavery, memory
and reconciliation,

00:21:29.340 --> 00:21:30.750
and is the lead curator

00:21:30.750 --> 00:21:33.700
of the online Georgetown
slavery archive.

00:21:33.700 --> 00:21:35.490
As a distinguished
visiting scholar

00:21:35.490 --> 00:21:39.390
at the Kluge Center last fall,
he created a podcast series

00:21:39.390 --> 00:21:42.440
about the Library of
Congress manuscript material

00:21:42.440 --> 00:21:44.780
on American slavery,
including one

00:21:44.780 --> 00:21:47.530
about Omar Ibn Said's
autobiography.

00:21:47.530 --> 00:21:50.040
And he also transcribed
the letters

00:21:50.040 --> 00:21:52.360
of the documents that we have.

00:21:52.360 --> 00:21:56.850
He has earned his BA from
Yale and PhD from Columbia.

00:21:56.850 --> 00:22:01.050
And last but not least, Ala
Alryyes who is the author

00:22:01.050 --> 00:22:05.350
of the book The Translation
of Omar Ibn Said, that will be

00:22:05.350 --> 00:22:08.830
for sale by the way
at lunchtime as well.

00:22:08.830 --> 00:22:12.100
So you'll all be able to
acquire a copy if you wish.

00:22:12.100 --> 00:22:14.640
Dr. Ala Alryyes is
associate professor of English

00:22:14.640 --> 00:22:17.550
at Queens College, the City
University of New York.

00:22:17.550 --> 00:22:20.980
He was educated at MIT
and Harvard University

00:22:20.980 --> 00:22:23.510
where he received his PhD
in comparative literature.

00:22:23.510 --> 00:22:26.100
And is a recipient of
a National Endowment

00:22:26.100 --> 00:22:27.850
for the Humanities Fellowship

00:22:27.850 --> 00:22:30.980
and an American Philosophical
Society grant.

00:22:30.980 --> 00:22:34.120
He is a scholar of 18th century
British and French literature,

00:22:34.120 --> 00:22:37.140
the European Enlightenment,
slavery

00:22:37.140 --> 00:22:38.550
and the literature of empire.

00:22:38.550 --> 00:22:42.260
Professor Alryyes is a
translator as we mentioned

00:22:42.260 --> 00:22:46.100
of Omar Ibn Said's autobiography
from the original Arabic,

00:22:46.100 --> 00:22:50.950
and a contributing editor of
the Muslim American Slave:

00:22:50.950 --> 00:22:56.600
The Life of Omar Ibn
Said, and so is Dr. Diuof.

00:22:56.600 --> 00:23:01.180
He also wrote Original
Subjects: The Child, the Novel

00:23:01.180 --> 00:23:03.590
and the Nation, published
by University Press

00:23:03.590 --> 00:23:05.640
and numerous journal articles.

00:23:05.640 --> 00:23:08.630
Among other current project
Professor Alryyes is completing

00:23:08.630 --> 00:23:12.170
Between Ordinary Life and
War, a book about proximity

00:23:12.170 --> 00:23:14.420
of war and literature.

00:23:14.420 --> 00:23:19.300
In addition to the City
University of New York,

00:23:19.300 --> 00:23:21.260
Professor Alryyes
has also taught

00:23:21.260 --> 00:23:22.780
at [inaudible] University.

00:23:22.780 --> 00:23:24.850
Now you won't hear
from me anymore.

00:23:24.850 --> 00:23:29.270
And I am passing the
baton on to Dr. Flanagan.

00:23:29.270 --> 00:23:31.510
Thank you.

00:23:31.510 --> 00:23:38.090
[ Applause ]

00:23:38.090 --> 00:23:39.390
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
Thank you, Mary Jane.

00:23:39.390 --> 00:23:41.480
So I just want to
circle back to a couple

00:23:41.480 --> 00:23:43.760
of things Dr. Hayden said.

00:23:43.760 --> 00:23:46.750
One I think she referred
to us as the Super Bowl

00:23:46.750 --> 00:23:48.830
of research and history.

00:23:48.830 --> 00:23:50.130
That's interesting.

00:23:50.130 --> 00:23:51.430
I think there's probably
more people in room today

00:23:51.430 --> 00:23:54.740
than watched the second
half of the game on Sunday.

00:23:54.740 --> 00:23:58.500
More seriously, she said
that this program is part

00:23:58.500 --> 00:24:01.050
of the library's celebration
of Black History Month.

00:24:01.050 --> 00:24:05.910
And what an amazing sort of
history we have before us

00:24:05.910 --> 00:24:07.770
to discuss this morning.

00:24:07.770 --> 00:24:13.120
Some 250 years of politics
and geography and religion

00:24:13.120 --> 00:24:18.800
and literature from sort
of 18th-century west Africa

00:24:18.800 --> 00:24:23.580
to the 19th-century American
south, and from the rediscovery

00:24:23.580 --> 00:24:27.070
of the autobiography
in the 20th century

00:24:27.070 --> 00:24:29.630
to the 21st century
when here we are.

00:24:29.630 --> 00:24:32.120
The Library has acquired,
preserved

00:24:32.120 --> 00:24:36.280
and digitized the Omar
Ibn Said collection.

00:24:36.280 --> 00:24:39.000
So we have a lot
of ground to cover,

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:42.810
and so I guess the obvious place
to begin is at the beginning.

00:24:42.810 --> 00:24:46.740
And so, Sylviane, you've written
several award-winning books

00:24:46.740 --> 00:24:49.600
on the African diaspora and
slave trade, one of which,

00:24:49.600 --> 00:24:52.490
Servants of Allah:
African Muslims Enslaved

00:24:52.490 --> 00:24:55.940
in the Americas, deals
with the time and place

00:24:55.940 --> 00:24:58.030
of Omar's capture
and enslavement.

00:24:58.030 --> 00:25:00.370
That time and place seems

00:25:00.370 --> 00:25:02.480
to have been sort
of far from simple.

00:25:02.480 --> 00:25:07.300
Maybe you could give us the
background to his environment

00:25:07.300 --> 00:25:08.870
and what he would
have experienced

00:25:08.870 --> 00:25:11.080
in the first 30 years
of his life.

00:25:11.080 --> 00:25:12.650
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sylviane Diuof:
Thank you.

00:25:12.650 --> 00:25:19.100
So Omar Ibn Said was
born in Senegal in 1770.

00:25:19.100 --> 00:25:26.320
He came from northern Senegal,
the region of [inaudible]

00:25:26.320 --> 00:25:32.470
which is really kind of the
cradle of Islam in this area.

00:25:32.470 --> 00:25:42.670
And you know, for about 100
years before he was born,

00:25:42.670 --> 00:25:46.050
there had been really -- the
region really felt the impact

00:25:46.050 --> 00:25:48.430
of the transatlantic
slave trade.

00:25:48.430 --> 00:25:55.010
And that had given rise to
Islamic reformist movements.

00:25:55.010 --> 00:25:58.280
You know, there were
Muslims who were trying

00:25:58.280 --> 00:26:08.370
to protect themselves from
the transatlantic salve trade

00:26:08.370 --> 00:26:12.840
and from the despotism of
some of the local rulers.

00:26:12.840 --> 00:26:16.870
And many of them were
actually attacked, deported,

00:26:16.870 --> 00:26:22.790
were victims of the slave trade.

00:26:22.790 --> 00:26:24.870
And Islam does not allow that.

00:26:24.870 --> 00:26:30.080
Islam does not allow free
Muslims to be enslaved.

00:26:30.080 --> 00:26:37.990
So there were those movements
that started to protect Muslims,

00:26:37.990 --> 00:26:42.170
to oppose the transatlantic
slave trade,

00:26:42.170 --> 00:26:45.900
and as I mentioned,
despotism as well.

00:26:45.900 --> 00:26:51.560
And we see that not only in
Senegal but in several parts

00:26:51.560 --> 00:26:57.930
of Senegal and in
Guinea as well.

00:26:57.930 --> 00:27:06.700
Now when Omar was born in 1770,
a few years later when actually

00:27:06.700 --> 00:27:14.010
around 1776, when he
started his studies,

00:27:14.010 --> 00:27:19.900
there was a real very
important movement there.

00:27:19.900 --> 00:27:30.590
For several years before, the
British had really taken a lot

00:27:30.590 --> 00:27:35.890
of Muslims and sent
them to the Caribbean.

00:27:35.890 --> 00:27:38.670
There was also a famine.

00:27:38.670 --> 00:27:43.960
The British allied
themselves with the Moors

00:27:43.960 --> 00:27:52.380
and there were really massacres
and large taking of people.

00:27:52.380 --> 00:28:00.220
So that gave rise to a new
Islamic reformist movement,

00:28:00.220 --> 00:28:03.500
again to protect the Muslims.

00:28:03.500 --> 00:28:10.200
And their leader Sulaiman
Ball was a scholar.

00:28:10.200 --> 00:28:15.170
His view was that
it's not enough

00:28:15.170 --> 00:28:18.440
to have a Muslim
leader, a Muslim king.

00:28:18.440 --> 00:28:20.790
You have to have a scholar.

00:28:20.790 --> 00:28:27.240
And I just want to read very
quickly what he envisioned.

00:28:27.240 --> 00:28:30.070
Because I think it's
very relevant

00:28:30.070 --> 00:28:35.100
to that particular story,
but to others as well.

00:28:35.100 --> 00:28:39.900
He said, "Choose an
Imam, pious and ascetic

00:28:39.900 --> 00:28:43.140
who is not interested in
the riches of this world.

00:28:43.140 --> 00:28:48.230
And if you see that his
possessions increase, depose him

00:28:48.230 --> 00:28:50.760
and confiscate all
his belongings.

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:55.260
And if he refuses to abdicate,
fight him and exile him

00:28:55.260 --> 00:28:58.750
to make sure he does not
establish a tyranny his sons

00:28:58.750 --> 00:29:00.430
will imitate.

00:29:00.430 --> 00:29:04.690
Replace him with another among
the men of knowledge and action.

00:29:04.690 --> 00:29:09.250
Bring to power one who deserves
it, one who forbids his soldiers

00:29:09.250 --> 00:29:13.080
to kill defenseless
children and old people

00:29:13.080 --> 00:29:16.360
and to rape women,
let alone kill them."

00:29:16.360 --> 00:29:20.190
So that was the basis
of those movements.

00:29:20.190 --> 00:29:23.540
And he was killed in battle.

00:29:23.540 --> 00:29:30.340
And the first leader of a new
theocracy [inaudible] really

00:29:30.340 --> 00:29:33.920
forbade trade on the river,

00:29:33.920 --> 00:29:38.230
forbade the enslavement
of Muslims.

00:29:38.230 --> 00:29:44.780
And he was really very strongly
opposed to the slave trade,

00:29:44.780 --> 00:29:55.110
not only of Muslims but also
putting an end to the transit

00:29:55.110 --> 00:30:04.440
of people from the
east to Saint-Louis.

00:30:04.440 --> 00:30:13.550
So this is the kind of regime
that Omar Ibn Said lived under.

00:30:13.550 --> 00:30:20.500
And it was really a time
where Islamic education spread

00:30:20.500 --> 00:30:23.620
with lots of schools
being built.

00:30:23.620 --> 00:30:27.810
Omar continued his studies
he said for 25 years.

00:30:27.810 --> 00:30:32.530
He went to other parts of the
country and then he came back

00:30:32.530 --> 00:30:35.680
to Futa, probably around 1801.

00:30:35.680 --> 00:30:39.900
And that was a period
which was crucial.

00:30:44.330 --> 00:30:50.130
The leader of the [inaudible]
continued to forbid the transit

00:30:50.130 --> 00:30:57.870
of slaves, and there were of
course strong repercussions.

00:30:57.870 --> 00:31:03.990
The French who had come back
to Saint-Louis burned villages,

00:31:03.990 --> 00:31:11.180
killed people, enslaved
600 people, retaliations

00:31:11.180 --> 00:31:15.560
from [inaudible] and
so on and so forth.

00:31:15.560 --> 00:31:18.580
Until in 1807 internal

00:31:18.580 --> 00:31:21.930
and external forces
coalesced against [inaudible].

00:31:21.930 --> 00:31:26.180
And as Omar wrote, an army
came and invaded Futa.

00:31:26.180 --> 00:31:30.180
And this army actually
killed [inaudible] and that's

00:31:30.180 --> 00:31:35.660
when Omar was made a prisoner.

00:31:35.660 --> 00:31:47.110
He was worked to Saint-Louis.

00:31:47.110 --> 00:31:54.990
He was 37, very old actually for
being part of the slave trade.

00:31:54.990 --> 00:32:01.750
And in three ships
left Saint-Louis

00:32:01.750 --> 00:32:06.330
between October and
December 1807.

00:32:06.330 --> 00:32:09.050
And he was certainly
on one of those ships.

00:32:09.050 --> 00:32:17.200
Close to 400 people arrived
from Saint-Louis in Charleston.

00:32:17.200 --> 00:32:21.980
And Omar was on one
of those last ships

00:32:21.980 --> 00:32:25.240
that brought legally Africans

00:32:25.240 --> 00:32:26.810
through the transatlantic
slave trade.

00:32:26.810 --> 00:32:32.700
Because on January 1st, 1808,
the international slave trade

00:32:32.700 --> 00:32:34.380
to the United States came

00:32:34.380 --> 00:32:41.530
to a formal end even though
it continued until July 1860.

00:32:41.530 --> 00:32:45.260
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan: So given
that tumultuous background,

00:32:45.260 --> 00:32:49.890
it seems to have swung wildly
from being turbulent at times

00:32:49.890 --> 00:32:51.580
to being a safe haven
at other times.

00:32:51.580 --> 00:32:53.790
Ala, perhaps you can
talk a little bit

00:32:53.790 --> 00:32:56.610
about the intellectual milieu

00:32:56.610 --> 00:33:00.820
that he would have experienced
during those years before 1807.

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:04.410
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes:
Uniquely I think,

00:33:04.410 --> 00:33:10.530
because Omar has left this
manuscript, we are accessory

00:33:10.530 --> 00:33:18.140
to the words of a "slave" who
recounts not only his education

00:33:18.140 --> 00:33:21.610
in his country of
origin in Africa,

00:33:21.610 --> 00:33:27.170
but also who seems to cast sort
of a symbolic role for himself

00:33:27.170 --> 00:33:30.440
as resisting it in certain
ways as we will talk

00:33:30.440 --> 00:33:32.860
about later today, I think.

00:33:32.860 --> 00:33:41.630
But as Sylviane was giving a
context of the previous lives

00:33:41.630 --> 00:33:46.850
of slaves whom we
usually think of as,

00:33:46.850 --> 00:33:50.160
or the standard narrative
thinks of them as sort

00:33:50.160 --> 00:33:52.810
of a blank slate, right?

00:33:52.810 --> 00:33:56.380
When slavery and the particular
kind of slavery that developed

00:33:56.380 --> 00:34:00.560
in the US turned human
beings into chattel,

00:34:00.560 --> 00:34:04.290
people into real estate,
the standard narrative

00:34:04.290 --> 00:34:09.780
of resistance became one
of freedom versus bondage.

00:34:09.780 --> 00:34:13.000
And that narrative, as crucial
and fundamental as it is,

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:16.140
sometimes short-changes
this historicity

00:34:16.140 --> 00:34:18.730
and the historical
forces and context

00:34:18.730 --> 00:34:23.480
that set those slaves apart
or set those human beings,

00:34:23.480 --> 00:34:26.120
those people, apart
as individuals.

00:34:26.120 --> 00:34:30.140
They all had unique stories,
but these unique stories

00:34:30.140 --> 00:34:34.890
like the stories of all,
you know, frankly enslaved

00:34:34.890 --> 00:34:38.520
or poor people all over
the world are not known

00:34:38.520 --> 00:34:40.680
or have been erased from
the historical record just

00:34:40.680 --> 00:34:43.260
because of the fact that
they have left no records

00:34:43.260 --> 00:34:44.560
of their own.

00:34:44.560 --> 00:34:48.020
In the case of Omar,
however, his literacy

00:34:48.020 --> 00:34:54.390
which was a consequence of his
faith and his education in Futa

00:34:54.390 --> 00:35:01.340
in Sene-Gambia, left clues to
the mind, to the inner life

00:35:01.340 --> 00:35:06.460
as well as to the kind of
contexts in which this man

00:35:06.460 --> 00:35:09.680
when he arrived to the
US became involved in.

00:35:09.680 --> 00:35:10.980
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:

00:35:10.980 --> 00:35:15.070
And perhaps we can talk then a
little bit about the movement

00:35:15.070 --> 00:35:18.150
from Africa to the Americas
and the slave trade.

00:35:18.150 --> 00:35:21.860
And Adam, this is something
you've studies particularly

00:35:21.860 --> 00:35:23.530
on arrival in the Americas.

00:35:23.530 --> 00:35:29.880
But perhaps you can draw some
parallels for us in this regard.

00:35:29.880 --> 00:35:31.180
&gt;&gt; Dr. Aldam Rothman: Sure.

00:35:31.180 --> 00:35:32.480
Thanks very much.

00:35:32.480 --> 00:35:35.130
I just want to say before I
get into that history that most

00:35:35.130 --> 00:35:39.460
of what I know about Omar
Ibn Said actually comes

00:35:39.460 --> 00:35:40.760
from the scholarship

00:35:40.760 --> 00:35:43.290
of the people sitting
on either side of me.

00:35:43.290 --> 00:35:46.320
And I want to acknowledge that.

00:35:46.320 --> 00:35:49.550
I'm especially lucky to be here.

00:35:49.550 --> 00:35:53.440
Just picking up on
something that Ala said,

00:35:53.440 --> 00:35:57.500
I think it's very
important to understand

00:35:57.500 --> 00:36:05.240
that not only had the history
of Atlantic slavery been written

00:36:05.240 --> 00:36:11.070
and understood for a long time
in ways that generally ignore,

00:36:11.070 --> 00:36:17.460
neglect or deny the African
historicity of enslaved people

00:36:17.460 --> 00:36:20.860
and everything they
brought into that history.

00:36:20.860 --> 00:36:23.360
But the slave trade
itself depended

00:36:23.360 --> 00:36:25.210
on the denial of that history.

00:36:25.210 --> 00:36:29.410
Just to give you an example,

00:36:29.410 --> 00:36:31.690
I was with some students
this week.

00:36:31.690 --> 00:36:34.450
We're looking at a letter
from a Jesuit priest

00:36:34.450 --> 00:36:38.420
in the early 1600's who
is explaining to one

00:36:38.420 --> 00:36:40.750
of his colleagues in
Cartagena de Indias

00:36:40.750 --> 00:36:45.120
about why you shouldn't ask
captive Africans how they

00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:47.060
were enslaved.

00:36:47.060 --> 00:36:50.460
And he says, "If you ask
them, they'll tell you

00:36:50.460 --> 00:36:54.590
that they were unjustly
and illegally captured."

00:36:54.590 --> 00:36:58.400
Because if they were, then
they ought to be free.

00:36:58.400 --> 00:37:00.560
He says, "They're
self-interested

00:37:00.560 --> 00:37:01.990
so they're lying.

00:37:01.990 --> 00:37:04.430
So don't ask them."

00:37:05.660 --> 00:37:10.000
The whole operation of the slave
trade depended upon willfully

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:14.800
neglecting the origins
of enslavement.

00:37:14.800 --> 00:37:21.770
And that's one of the reasons
why a text like Omar's is

00:37:21.770 --> 00:37:25.240
so important, because
it recovers

00:37:25.240 --> 00:37:27.550
that suppressed history.

00:37:27.550 --> 00:37:30.520
Slavery is a silencer.

00:37:30.520 --> 00:37:34.660
It denies the voices of captive
Africans and enslaved peoples

00:37:34.660 --> 00:37:38.590
in the Americas, so recovering
this text is so important

00:37:38.590 --> 00:37:42.210
to getting that history back
and understanding the lies

00:37:42.210 --> 00:37:44.770
and violence that were
really at the root

00:37:44.770 --> 00:37:47.070
of the Atlantic slave trade.

00:37:47.070 --> 00:37:50.010
So that's one thing.

00:37:50.010 --> 00:37:52.250
The second thing is I
think it's so interesting

00:37:52.250 --> 00:37:57.430
as Sylviana was talking about
the politics and history

00:37:57.430 --> 00:38:03.610
of northern Senegal and these
tensions and in fact wars

00:38:03.610 --> 00:38:07.190
over slavery that ended
up with Omar Ibn Said

00:38:07.190 --> 00:38:08.880
on a slave ship in Charleston.

00:38:08.880 --> 00:38:15.600
It's interesting to think
about the intersection

00:38:15.600 --> 00:38:18.910
of this tumultuous
politics in West Africa

00:38:18.910 --> 00:38:23.490
with equally tumultuous
politics in North America.

00:38:23.490 --> 00:38:28.870
Omar Ibn Said is a kind of
nexus, a connecting point

00:38:28.870 --> 00:38:34.030
between those two histories.

00:38:34.030 --> 00:38:36.970
Sylviane mentioned that
Omar Ibn Said is one

00:38:36.970 --> 00:38:42.590
of the very last captive
Africans to be imported legally

00:38:42.590 --> 00:38:45.030
into the United States.

00:38:45.030 --> 00:38:47.030
Well, why was that?

00:38:47.030 --> 00:38:51.050
This gets us into the
whole history of the debate

00:38:51.050 --> 00:38:54.860
over slavery in the
New United States.

00:38:54.860 --> 00:39:00.440
You know, while Omar Ibn Said
is being born in West Africa,

00:39:00.440 --> 00:39:04.930
there's a revolution about to
get underway in North American

00:39:04.930 --> 00:39:07.990
in which the concept of
slavery both literally

00:39:07.990 --> 00:39:11.690
and as a metaphor is central.

00:39:11.690 --> 00:39:16.220
But so is the reality
of the slave economy

00:39:16.220 --> 00:39:19.220
which undergirds the new nation.

00:39:19.220 --> 00:39:23.000
So a whole series of
compromises is worked out to try

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:25.340
to reconcile the
rhetoric of freedom

00:39:25.340 --> 00:39:26.640
with the reality of slavery.

00:39:26.640 --> 00:39:28.050
And one of those
compromises has to do

00:39:28.050 --> 00:39:29.600
with the Atlantic slave trade.

00:39:29.600 --> 00:39:34.160
So in the Constitution
of the United States,

00:39:34.160 --> 00:39:35.970
one of the compromise clauses is

00:39:35.970 --> 00:39:40.090
that Congress cannot
prohibit the introduction

00:39:40.090 --> 00:39:42.490
of Africans for 20 years.

00:39:42.490 --> 00:39:46.590
So there's a 20-year window in
which captive Africans continued

00:39:46.590 --> 00:39:49.200
to be introduced into
the United States.

00:39:49.200 --> 00:39:56.360
That 20-year window
basically ends in 1808.

00:39:56.360 --> 00:40:01.310
And right before that window
closes, there is a kind of surge

00:40:01.310 --> 00:40:05.640
in slaving as planters
in the United States try

00:40:05.640 --> 00:40:08.570
to get one last cargo
of Africans

00:40:08.570 --> 00:40:12.020
in before that window closes.

00:40:12.020 --> 00:40:19.170
So Omar Ibn Said is caught in
this kind of trap of politics

00:40:19.170 --> 00:40:22.090
on one side of the
Atlantic and politics

00:40:22.090 --> 00:40:23.390
on the other side
of the Atlantic.

00:40:23.390 --> 00:40:25.280
And I think it's
really important

00:40:25.280 --> 00:40:30.660
to understand both sides of his
story, his story on both sides

00:40:30.660 --> 00:40:31.960
of the Atlantic together.

00:40:31.960 --> 00:40:35.230
That's the only way we
understand the particularity

00:40:35.230 --> 00:40:36.910
of his history.

00:40:36.910 --> 00:40:38.210
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes:
Just as a footnote

00:40:38.210 --> 00:40:42.210
to what Adam was saying, if
I may, Omar is born in 1770,

00:40:42.210 --> 00:40:45.350
so that's six years before the
Declaration of Independence,

00:40:45.350 --> 00:40:50.050
and he dies in 1863-64.

00:40:50.050 --> 00:40:53.220
And so that's one
year before the end

00:40:53.220 --> 00:40:54.520
of the American Civil War.

00:40:54.520 --> 00:40:58.480
So his life in a way is an
actual one might say record

00:40:58.480 --> 00:41:02.430
or demonstration of what you
were saying about context.

00:41:02.430 --> 00:41:03.730
&gt;&gt; Dr. Aldam Rothman: Yeah.

00:41:03.730 --> 00:41:08.430
His life is a microcosm
of the history of slavery

00:41:08.430 --> 00:41:12.860
in the United States from the
Revolution to the Civil War.

00:41:12.860 --> 00:41:14.640
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan: So
we've been talking about him

00:41:14.640 --> 00:41:19.460
as both an individual and sort
of a sign for large themes.

00:41:19.460 --> 00:41:27.010
Getting back to 1807, Ala, maybe
you can have a go at this one.

00:41:27.010 --> 00:41:32.250
Can you give us sort of a
sketch of who he was in 1807?

00:41:35.010 --> 00:41:36.740
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes:

00:41:36.740 --> 00:41:39.630
No one individual is
one thing for sure.

00:41:39.630 --> 00:41:46.240
And it's a difficult question,
but it's a crucial question,

00:41:46.240 --> 00:41:50.740
perhaps the most
fundamental question to ask.

00:41:50.740 --> 00:41:58.050
And we know from the
manuscript that for example,

00:41:58.050 --> 00:42:02.800
for those people who
captured him at that moment,

00:42:02.800 --> 00:42:07.210
when he escaped -- as we know,
he escaped from South Carolina,

00:42:07.210 --> 00:42:10.620
from Charleston, about two
years after he was brought

00:42:10.620 --> 00:42:15.250
in the big ship to this country.

00:42:15.250 --> 00:42:17.840
To the people he
must have seemed

00:42:17.840 --> 00:42:22.160
like this remarkable phenomenon

00:42:22.160 --> 00:42:24.530
of someone writing
Arabic letters

00:42:24.530 --> 00:42:26.650
on the walls of his jail cell.

00:42:26.650 --> 00:42:29.190
So that's one thing
that they saw in him,

00:42:29.190 --> 00:42:33.640
someone who possibly
was unusually,

00:42:33.640 --> 00:42:36.690
perhaps spectacularly
educated in a way

00:42:36.690 --> 00:42:39.700
that they expected no
African or no slave

00:42:39.700 --> 00:42:41.860
to be educated at the time.

00:42:41.860 --> 00:42:47.190
Because of course
the common belief was

00:42:47.190 --> 00:42:50.150
that Africans had no culture
or at least no literate culture

00:42:50.150 --> 00:42:54.520
of that sort or no culture
that can be of value.

00:42:54.520 --> 00:43:00.140
On the other hand, he
himself from the manuscript,

00:43:00.140 --> 00:43:04.930
we learn that he
was born in 1770.

00:43:04.930 --> 00:43:09.260
We know from the dates that
he was an old man when he --

00:43:09.260 --> 00:43:11.420
I mean, roughly, right?

00:43:11.420 --> 00:43:13.790
He was 37.

00:43:13.790 --> 00:43:17.880
He certainly was not -- I know.

00:43:17.880 --> 00:43:21.870
He was not a young,
youthful man.

00:43:21.870 --> 00:43:25.240
He refers to himself
as a weak man.

00:43:25.240 --> 00:43:27.960
He certainly saw himself as a
scholar, did not see himself

00:43:27.960 --> 00:43:32.390
as someone who is fit to work
in the fields or in plantations.

00:43:32.390 --> 00:43:35.850
You know, certainly
the plantation regime

00:43:35.850 --> 00:43:39.050
in Charleston was one
of the most difficult

00:43:39.050 --> 00:43:42.860
and backbreaking in
the United States.

00:43:42.860 --> 00:43:45.730
But he refers to his education,
he talks about the fact

00:43:45.730 --> 00:43:49.260
that he spent 25 years
seeking knowledge.

00:43:49.260 --> 00:43:51.490
He refers to three teachers,

00:43:51.490 --> 00:43:56.180
one of whom was his own
brother in Putatoro.

00:43:56.180 --> 00:44:00.740
He refers endearingly to
his father and mother.

00:44:00.740 --> 00:44:02.830
He refers to clearly both

00:44:02.830 --> 00:44:04.740
of his parents were married
before they had a number

00:44:04.740 --> 00:44:07.400
of children, and he
had a big family.

00:44:07.400 --> 00:44:12.980
So he refers to all sorts
of details of that sort,

00:44:12.980 --> 00:44:16.060
and the manuscript itself
also reveals details

00:44:16.060 --> 00:44:19.910
about his escape, about the
number of days he was held

00:44:19.910 --> 00:44:21.630
in jail in Fayetteville,

00:44:21.630 --> 00:44:24.650
North Carolina once he
escapes from the south.

00:44:24.650 --> 00:44:29.700
All of these various
details sketch Omar

00:44:29.700 --> 00:44:33.160
as a multiple person,
like all of us.

00:44:33.160 --> 00:44:35.040
I mean, he was an African.

00:44:35.040 --> 00:44:39.030
He was one might say certainly
an insipient American.

00:44:39.030 --> 00:44:41.760
The moment he was captured,

00:44:41.760 --> 00:44:44.850
he was an extraordinary
individual who could write.

00:44:44.850 --> 00:44:49.060
And so that question I
think should not be boiled

00:44:49.060 --> 00:44:50.980
down to one answer,
but we should look

00:44:50.980 --> 00:44:56.320
at the historical record first
and foremost the autobiography

00:44:56.320 --> 00:44:58.140
to open up that question.

00:44:58.140 --> 00:45:01.600
And that question is also
intertwined I would say

00:45:01.600 --> 00:45:05.230
with a kind of one might
say informants or people

00:45:05.230 --> 00:45:10.450
in the United States,
and we have a clue as to

00:45:10.450 --> 00:45:13.810
who these people were from the
title page of the manuscript

00:45:13.810 --> 00:45:15.150
that was written in English.

00:45:15.150 --> 00:45:17.010
We know a lot about them.

00:45:17.010 --> 00:45:19.580
These were well-known
people, scholars

00:45:19.580 --> 00:45:24.960
and these are all white
individuals, including a man

00:45:24.960 --> 00:45:26.790
by the name of Theodore Dwight,

00:45:26.790 --> 00:45:29.160
whose uncle was a
former president

00:45:29.160 --> 00:45:31.320
of Yale College, Timothy Dwight.

00:45:31.320 --> 00:45:36.330
And I'm sure Adam will maybe
later say a little bit more

00:45:36.330 --> 00:45:38.420
about Theodore Dwight.

00:45:38.420 --> 00:45:40.740
There were others,
Isaac Byrd who was one

00:45:40.740 --> 00:45:43.040
of the early translators
of the manuscript,

00:45:43.040 --> 00:45:44.950
and who himself was a
missionary actually,

00:45:44.950 --> 00:45:46.850
ended up going to
the Middle East.

00:45:46.850 --> 00:45:48.490
He was in Lebanon, working

00:45:48.490 --> 00:45:50.520
on producing a new
Protestant Bible.

00:45:50.520 --> 00:45:53.810
We have a lot of information
about that circuit of people

00:45:53.810 --> 00:45:57.880
who solicited Omar to
write his autobiography.

00:45:57.880 --> 00:46:01.360
And certainly the question
of who Omar is, is a question

00:46:01.360 --> 00:46:03.520
about his interiority.

00:46:03.520 --> 00:46:06.490
It's also a question about
his culture back in Africa.

00:46:06.490 --> 00:46:10.690
But it's also a question
about his future collaboration

00:46:10.690 --> 00:46:14.070
and really incorporation
into the circuit of people

00:46:14.070 --> 00:46:19.250
who had definite goals about
one might say the future

00:46:19.250 --> 00:46:22.750
of enslaved people in
the Americas, right?

00:46:22.750 --> 00:46:26.790
Including the fact that many
of them were not comfortable --

00:46:26.790 --> 00:46:28.130
this particular circuit
of people,

00:46:28.130 --> 00:46:31.140
they were not comfortable
with slavery as such.

00:46:31.140 --> 00:46:37.100
They saw in Omar's culture,
his education and his literacy,

00:46:37.100 --> 00:46:42.380
manifest proofs that
Africans were cultured

00:46:42.380 --> 00:46:46.650
and they should not be
subject to this regime.

00:46:46.650 --> 00:46:52.050
But they also were not happy or
not comfortable with the idea

00:46:52.050 --> 00:46:55.370
of freeing those slaves
and then having them stay

00:46:55.370 --> 00:46:56.670
in the United States.

00:46:56.670 --> 00:46:57.970
There's a particular group

00:46:57.970 --> 00:47:02.390
of people called the American
Colonization Society whose plans

00:47:02.390 --> 00:47:06.410
were to [inaudible] as
many slaves as they can

00:47:06.410 --> 00:47:09.350
through convincing slave
owners to release them

00:47:09.350 --> 00:47:11.510
and then have them
immigrate to Africa,

00:47:11.510 --> 00:47:14.860
to Liberia or other places.

00:47:14.860 --> 00:47:19.410
And so Omar has a multiple
identity and he's really --

00:47:19.410 --> 00:47:23.880
as we were saying
before, he has a biography

00:47:23.880 --> 00:47:26.170
but also a historical moment.

00:47:26.170 --> 00:47:27.470
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
Sylviane,

00:47:27.470 --> 00:47:29.450
there's many ways
of looking at Omar.

00:47:29.450 --> 00:47:31.900
There's a tendency to
see him as exceptional.

00:47:31.900 --> 00:47:34.440
Is that the case?

00:47:34.440 --> 00:47:37.210
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sylviane Diuof: Yes,
and he actually was not.

00:47:37.210 --> 00:47:43.990
I mean, we have to understand
that the estimate is about 10%

00:47:43.990 --> 00:47:46.800
of the 12.5 million
Africans who were deported

00:47:46.800 --> 00:47:52.110
through the transatlantic
slave trade, 10% were Muslims.

00:47:52.110 --> 00:47:56.090
So we are talking about
more than a million people,

00:47:56.090 --> 00:47:59.800
more than a million Muslims
arrived in the Americas

00:47:59.800 --> 00:48:02.190
and really in every country.

00:48:02.190 --> 00:48:07.780
I mean, I used English, French,
Portuguese and Spanish sources

00:48:07.780 --> 00:48:11.070
and I found them
in 20 countries.

00:48:11.070 --> 00:48:15.660
And I didn't use Dutch
because I don't know Dutch.

00:48:15.660 --> 00:48:18.080
And what I found, you know,

00:48:18.080 --> 00:48:21.480
again it's not just
what is there.

00:48:21.480 --> 00:48:24.680
There's many others.

00:48:24.680 --> 00:48:28.730
And you know, we're talking
about people who had been --

00:48:28.730 --> 00:48:31.710
not all of them, but
many of them had been

00:48:31.710 --> 00:48:37.060
to Koranic schools, could
read and write like Omar.

00:48:37.060 --> 00:48:40.540
Of course, you know, when
you were taken at 10,

00:48:40.540 --> 00:48:43.750
you have a little knowledge.

00:48:43.750 --> 00:48:47.520
When you arrived at 20
or 25, you had more.

00:48:47.520 --> 00:48:52.820
Some had been teachers,
scholars, judges.

00:48:52.820 --> 00:48:56.420
So we have really a
large number of people

00:48:56.420 --> 00:49:05.670
who like Omar were literate,
who like Omar left documents.

00:49:05.670 --> 00:49:09.690
And there are a lot.

00:49:09.690 --> 00:49:11.120
I mean, a lot.

00:49:11.120 --> 00:49:13.990
It's maybe not exaggerated.

00:49:13.990 --> 00:49:18.390
But in Brazil, for example,
there are a lot of documents

00:49:18.390 --> 00:49:22.530
that have been preserved
in Arabic as well

00:49:22.530 --> 00:49:27.540
as in languages written
in Arabic script.

00:49:27.540 --> 00:49:34.620
And we have that even
in the United States.

00:49:34.620 --> 00:49:38.220
You know, there's a 13-page
manuscript that was written

00:49:38.220 --> 00:49:45.100
by a Muslim on the island of
Georgia that still exists.

00:49:45.100 --> 00:49:53.840
We have facsimiles of other
writings that Muslims left.

00:49:53.840 --> 00:49:58.340
And in Jamaica, in Trinidad.

00:49:58.340 --> 00:50:05.270
And that goes from chapters
of the Koran to full Koran.

00:50:05.270 --> 00:50:14.560
One man here in the United
States known as Job ben Solomon

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:18.630
from Senegal wrote three
copies of the Koran

00:50:18.630 --> 00:50:22.300
that of course he knew by rote.

00:50:22.300 --> 00:50:27.880
And one copy of the Koran that
he wrote was sold at auction

00:50:27.880 --> 00:50:37.210
in London, I think
it was in 2011.

00:50:37.210 --> 00:50:45.060
So a number of manuscripts
still exist.

00:50:45.060 --> 00:50:50.240
And sometimes it's letters,
it's religious writings.

00:50:50.240 --> 00:50:55.100
It's also plans for revolt.

00:50:55.100 --> 00:51:00.750
Let's not forget that in 1807
when Omar Ibn Said arrived

00:51:00.750 --> 00:51:05.470
in the United States, that
was the start also of a series

00:51:05.470 --> 00:51:13.500
of conspiracies and revolts
by Muslims in [inaudible].

00:51:13.500 --> 00:51:16.200
And those Muslims arrived

00:51:16.200 --> 00:51:22.160
because of another
Islamic reformist movement

00:51:22.160 --> 00:51:27.220
in Nigeria that started in 1804.

00:51:27.220 --> 00:51:34.030
And there was also one
autobiography that was written

00:51:34.030 --> 00:51:37.160
by a Muslim in Jamaica.

00:51:37.160 --> 00:51:43.490
And it's much longer
than Omar's.

00:51:43.490 --> 00:51:47.910
It's much, much,
much more detailed.

00:51:47.910 --> 00:51:52.710
Now the difference though is
that Abuba Asidic who wrote it,

00:51:52.710 --> 00:51:55.950
and I think he wrote
three versions of it,

00:51:55.950 --> 00:51:59.440
wrote it when he
was freed in 1834.

00:51:59.440 --> 00:52:04.340
He wrote one version in
1834 and one in 1835.

00:52:04.340 --> 00:52:06.640
He was free.

00:52:06.640 --> 00:52:09.270
He actually went back to Mali.

00:52:09.270 --> 00:52:14.450
He was born in Timbuktu.

00:52:14.450 --> 00:52:18.400
And the other thing that
is different from Omar,

00:52:18.400 --> 00:52:21.480
that particular original
manuscript doesn't

00:52:21.480 --> 00:52:23.150
exist anymore.

00:52:23.150 --> 00:52:27.000
So it had been translated
and the idea is probably

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:31.080
that he actually took those
versions that he wrote with him

00:52:31.080 --> 00:52:33.120
when he went back home.

00:52:33.120 --> 00:52:40.460
So Omar's manuscript
as far as we know,

00:52:40.460 --> 00:52:44.660
and maybe something would be
discovered, we don't know.

00:52:44.660 --> 00:52:48.050
But Omar's manuscript
is unique in the sense

00:52:48.050 --> 00:52:55.480
that it's the only autobiography
of a person who was enslaved

00:52:55.480 --> 00:53:01.930
and wrote his biography
when he was still enslaved.

00:53:01.930 --> 00:53:03.410
&gt;&gt; Dr. Aldam Rothman:
Can I just add one thing?

00:53:03.410 --> 00:53:07.260
I think Sylviane is
absolutely right to place Omar

00:53:07.260 --> 00:53:11.330
and his autobiography
in a larger context

00:53:11.330 --> 00:53:15.030
of enslaved Muslim
Africans in the Americas.

00:53:15.030 --> 00:53:18.490
So it's part of a
broader picture,

00:53:18.490 --> 00:53:21.870
but there's always this
tension between the degree

00:53:21.870 --> 00:53:24.350
to which somebody like
Omar Said is representative

00:53:24.350 --> 00:53:26.900
of something larger
and the extent

00:53:26.900 --> 00:53:31.950
to which he really is unique
sort of in his own experience.

00:53:31.950 --> 00:53:37.680
So when I read the
translation of his autobiography

00:53:37.680 --> 00:53:41.170
and the way he writes about
arriving in Charleston,

00:53:41.170 --> 00:53:44.360
the overwhelming
sense that I get is

00:53:44.360 --> 00:53:49.260
that he is alone
and traumatized.

00:53:49.260 --> 00:53:54.010
That there is a shock of arrival

00:53:54.010 --> 00:53:58.340
in this new very strange
and very harsh place.

00:53:58.340 --> 00:54:01.780
He writes in the autobiography
of being sold into the hands

00:54:01.780 --> 00:54:05.580
of Christians and arriving
in a Christian country.

00:54:05.580 --> 00:54:08.190
But then his first
owner, his first enslaver

00:54:08.190 --> 00:54:13.810
in Charleston he describes
as a wicked infidel,

00:54:13.810 --> 00:54:16.860
which is strong language.

00:54:16.860 --> 00:54:19.680
And he suffers.

00:54:19.680 --> 00:54:23.890
He's a scholar but he's
made to do hard labor.

00:54:23.890 --> 00:54:26.610
He's literate but he
doesn't speak the language

00:54:26.610 --> 00:54:29.170
of the society that
he's found himself in.

00:54:29.170 --> 00:54:35.230
And it's hard, but instead
of having his spirit broken,

00:54:35.230 --> 00:54:37.370
which could have been
one of the effects

00:54:37.370 --> 00:54:44.160
of this extraordinary odyssey
that he's been on, he resists.

00:54:44.160 --> 00:54:45.910
He runs away.

00:54:45.910 --> 00:54:48.920
You know, he takes matters into
his own hands and he runs away

00:54:48.920 --> 00:54:52.590
and he wanders for
what seems to be weeks.

00:54:52.590 --> 00:54:55.530
And somehow he gets from
Charleston, South Carolina

00:54:55.530 --> 00:54:59.030
to I think it is
Fayetteville, North Carolina.

00:54:59.030 --> 00:55:01.110
How does he do that?

00:55:01.110 --> 00:55:07.200
And then he ends up you
know, and maybe it's a church

00:55:07.200 --> 00:55:10.350
where he's arrested
and gets sent to jail.

00:55:10.350 --> 00:55:14.860
He spends time in jail and
he's writing Arabic characters

00:55:14.860 --> 00:55:16.160
on the wall of his jail cell.

00:55:16.160 --> 00:55:22.190
I mean, you could not write a
novel that's more remarkable

00:55:22.190 --> 00:55:23.890
than the true story of this man

00:55:23.890 --> 00:55:28.190
when he arrives in
South Carolina.

00:55:28.190 --> 00:55:32.420
So he is part of this broader
movement, but he is also

00:55:32.420 --> 00:55:37.050
so alone when he arrives
in the United States.

00:55:37.050 --> 00:55:39.020
And I find that to be
one of the most poignant

00:55:39.020 --> 00:55:42.830
and powerful aspects
of his story.

00:55:42.830 --> 00:55:47.420
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan: And he
really is ripped from his world

00:55:47.420 --> 00:55:49.370
and placed in a very
different world.

00:55:49.370 --> 00:55:51.800
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes: May
I just follow up on that?

00:55:51.800 --> 00:55:53.100
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan: Please.

00:55:53.100 --> 00:55:54.400
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes:
It's no accident

00:55:54.400 --> 00:55:57.200
that Omar was [inaudible]
a life, right?

00:55:57.200 --> 00:56:00.690
He refers to it a [inaudible],
an honorific title that he gives

00:56:00.690 --> 00:56:05.980
to a clergyman who I
think later I traced

00:56:05.980 --> 00:56:08.090
down to a man called Eli Hunter,

00:56:08.090 --> 00:56:10.260
a member of the American
Colonization Society.

00:56:10.260 --> 00:56:12.180
I am pretty sure about that.

00:56:12.180 --> 00:56:16.460
So this [inaudible]
asked him to write a life

00:56:16.460 --> 00:56:20.420
which Omar actually ended up --
in the manuscript it refers to,

00:56:20.420 --> 00:56:24.060
"You asked me to write hayati,"
which is the Arabic word

00:56:24.060 --> 00:56:29.110
for a life, immediately
translating it.

00:56:29.110 --> 00:56:35.040
Now the fascinating thing about
it is that the Arabic genre

00:56:35.040 --> 00:56:40.040
of the life is not called that,
but is referred to as sira.

00:56:40.040 --> 00:56:42.230
And so there is something
remarkable about the fact

00:56:42.230 --> 00:56:45.180
that he's asked to
write an autobiography

00:56:45.180 --> 00:56:48.700
for the simple reason that
this particular genre has

00:56:48.700 --> 00:56:53.290
by now become in the west
the kind of genre that speaks

00:56:53.290 --> 00:56:57.400
to the authenticity of
someone's experiences as well

00:56:57.400 --> 00:56:59.690
as the development
of a person, right?

00:56:59.690 --> 00:57:03.180
That is you turn
yourself into a person,

00:57:03.180 --> 00:57:06.310
you sort of demonstrate your
personhood and consciousness

00:57:06.310 --> 00:57:09.950
by writing about it, by
writing an autobiography.

00:57:09.950 --> 00:57:13.380
And autobiographies remain
of course huge bestsellers

00:57:13.380 --> 00:57:14.990
in the US today, right?

00:57:14.990 --> 00:57:17.110
They're seen as in
a way a reflection,

00:57:17.110 --> 00:57:19.160
a mirror of the person.

00:57:19.160 --> 00:57:24.290
And so in a way, Omar's
1832 manuscript is unique

00:57:24.290 --> 00:57:29.130
because in it we encounter
someone who not only fulfills

00:57:29.130 --> 00:57:33.130
that premise or that
aspect of the genre.

00:57:33.130 --> 00:57:39.650
But he actually opens it by
talking about his previous life,

00:57:39.650 --> 00:57:44.850
by talking about his teachers,
by talking about his education

00:57:44.850 --> 00:57:49.030
by actually drawing on the other
Arabic tradition of writing,

00:57:49.030 --> 00:57:51.790
which is the Arabic
tradition of the sira, right?

00:57:51.790 --> 00:57:53.750
Where you actually don't
begin by talking necessarily

00:57:53.750 --> 00:57:57.730
about yourself and about your
education and about your culture

00:57:57.730 --> 00:57:59.200
and about your teachers.

00:57:59.200 --> 00:58:03.240
And therefore Omar is able
to bring together these two,

00:58:03.240 --> 00:58:08.200
concatenate as it were
these two literary genres

00:58:08.200 --> 00:58:09.500
in his narrative.

00:58:09.500 --> 00:58:12.110
And that really sets him apart.

00:58:12.110 --> 00:58:13.410
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
And in your book,

00:58:13.410 --> 00:58:17.150
A Muslim American Slave,
the Life of Omar Ibn Said,

00:58:17.150 --> 00:58:19.410
you characterize a three-step
process of translating,

00:58:19.410 --> 00:58:21.620
deciphering and contextualizing.

00:58:21.620 --> 00:58:24.330
And I'm wondering if you
can tell us a little bit

00:58:24.330 --> 00:58:29.010
about the insights that
come from that approach.

00:58:29.010 --> 00:58:30.310
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes: Sure.

00:58:30.310 --> 00:58:37.380
So the work that later became
this book really was done

00:58:37.380 --> 00:58:38.680
in two stages.

00:58:38.680 --> 00:58:42.530
One was an encounter with the
manuscript itself with the life

00:58:42.530 --> 00:58:45.740
and autobiography and
translating it and trying

00:58:45.740 --> 00:58:48.770
to in translating it, to
interpret it and to think

00:58:48.770 --> 00:58:52.340
about both the inner life
of this man, his suffering

00:58:52.340 --> 00:58:56.200
as Adam was saying, the
fact that at one point he

00:58:56.200 --> 00:58:59.630
for example responds
to an overseer,

00:58:59.630 --> 00:59:02.090
clearly someone who's
sent by his southern owner

00:59:02.090 --> 00:59:03.980
to recapture him
and take him back

00:59:03.980 --> 00:59:07.800
or to buy him whatever
again, he responds by --

00:59:07.800 --> 00:59:11.100
I mean, he's responding in 1831.

00:59:11.100 --> 00:59:12.400
He's writing in 1831.

00:59:12.400 --> 00:59:15.610
Remember, there is a
24-year differential or so

00:59:15.610 --> 00:59:17.620
between the moment of
the escape and the moment

00:59:17.620 --> 00:59:19.420
of the writing of
the manuscript.

00:59:19.420 --> 00:59:22.210
And he's so traumatized
by that moment

00:59:22.210 --> 00:59:25.760
that he actually records it as
having responded to that man

00:59:25.760 --> 00:59:27.810
by writing seven no's in Arabic.

00:59:27.810 --> 00:59:30.160
The word for no is
lah in Arabic.

00:59:30.160 --> 00:59:34.720
And he writes seven no's,
right, not one but seven.

00:59:34.720 --> 00:59:37.960
And that is really a moment
where you could see just

00:59:37.960 --> 00:59:41.600
by looking at the space of the
page, you could gain something

00:59:41.600 --> 00:59:45.340
into one might say really
the mind of someone.

00:59:45.340 --> 00:59:49.810
So there is that aspect of the
suffering of the human being

00:59:49.810 --> 00:59:54.560
that can be given by
the work of translation.

00:59:54.560 --> 00:59:59.320
There is also the fact that
there is the political agency

00:59:59.320 --> 01:00:03.260
or the act of resistance itself
that the manuscript reveals

01:00:03.260 --> 01:00:07.580
where Omar rhetorically
casts certain kind

01:00:07.580 --> 01:00:10.550
of symbolic role for himself.

01:00:10.550 --> 01:00:14.910
The text, as my introduction to
the book shows, is full of sort

01:00:14.910 --> 01:00:16.910
of double hidden utterances

01:00:16.910 --> 01:00:20.760
in which he often will use
koranic suras to cast sort

01:00:20.760 --> 01:00:25.140
of a role for himself or to
deliver a message that is hidden

01:00:25.140 --> 01:00:27.760
to all except for those who
can really decipher what he

01:00:27.760 --> 01:00:29.680
is writing.

01:00:29.680 --> 01:00:32.160
So that's one aspect or
one big part of the work.

01:00:32.160 --> 01:00:36.720
The other aspect that I refer
to as recovering the context

01:00:36.720 --> 01:00:41.140
of it is something that I have
already spoken about briefly,

01:00:41.140 --> 01:00:46.430
and that's kind of -- thinking
about the circuit of people

01:00:46.430 --> 01:00:50.790
who are mentioned, a few of
them are actually mentioned

01:00:50.790 --> 01:00:52.920
on the manuscript
on the title page.

01:00:52.920 --> 01:00:57.200
And these are white men
who obviously are related

01:00:57.200 --> 01:01:01.370
to that [inaudible] who asked
him to write his manuscript.

01:01:01.370 --> 01:01:04.410
And you know, you need to
ask yourself the question,

01:01:04.410 --> 01:01:09.770
in a country where --
what's the percentage?

01:01:09.770 --> 01:01:12.930
0.0001% of people spoke Arabic.

01:01:12.930 --> 01:01:16.860
I mean, obviously I'm even
increasing that percentage.

01:01:16.860 --> 01:01:19.380
I haven't computed it,
but a minute number

01:01:19.380 --> 01:01:20.680
of people spoke Arabic.

01:01:20.680 --> 01:01:21.980
Why ask this man
who speaks Arabic

01:01:21.980 --> 01:01:25.940
to write a manuscript in Arabic?

01:01:25.940 --> 01:01:27.260
Who could read it?

01:01:27.260 --> 01:01:29.460
Who could really be
interested in it?

01:01:29.460 --> 01:01:34.550
And that opens really
or has opened a window

01:01:34.550 --> 01:01:39.120
into the interest of a number
of missionary scholars,

01:01:39.120 --> 01:01:43.130
ethnographers and so on who
saw in Omar an opportunity

01:01:43.130 --> 01:01:47.420
to do something or to kind
of prove or make a point

01:01:47.420 --> 01:01:51.540
or create an anti-slavery
argument that was

01:01:51.540 --> 01:01:55.230
at that point becoming
a third way shall we say

01:01:55.230 --> 01:01:58.430
in the anti-slavery rhetoric.

01:01:58.430 --> 01:02:00.490
Between the northern
abolitionists

01:02:00.490 --> 01:02:02.980
and the southern slave
plantation owners,

01:02:02.980 --> 01:02:04.660
there was a middle
way as they called it.

01:02:04.660 --> 01:02:08.990
And that middle way was
colonization, namely convincing

01:02:08.990 --> 01:02:14.210
as many salve owners to
release slaves or buying them

01:02:14.210 --> 01:02:15.510
and then sending
them to Liberia.

01:02:15.510 --> 01:02:19.100
And those particular people
were not universally it seems

01:02:19.100 --> 01:02:21.180
interested in all slaves.

01:02:21.180 --> 01:02:25.130
They were particularly drawn
to men of culture and education

01:02:25.130 --> 01:02:28.530
like Omar was and as
Sylviane was talking

01:02:28.530 --> 01:02:35.360
about other people whom they
saw as deserving of manumission

01:02:35.360 --> 01:02:37.840
because of their
culture and literacy.

01:02:38.860 --> 01:02:41.410
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan: Now
part of the record assumes

01:02:41.410 --> 01:02:44.620
that he converted
to Christianity,

01:02:44.620 --> 01:02:46.650
but the autobiography
itself starts

01:02:46.650 --> 01:02:52.400
with a long quotation
chapter from the Koran.

01:02:52.400 --> 01:02:53.700
What's in play there?

01:02:53.700 --> 01:02:55.310
Can you tell us a
little bit about that?

01:02:55.310 --> 01:02:58.010
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sylviane Diuof: It's
one of the things that a number

01:02:58.010 --> 01:03:03.300
of Muslims did, you know,
that pseudo-conversion.

01:03:03.300 --> 01:03:06.440
In some countries
they were forced.

01:03:06.440 --> 01:03:12.950
And they externally if you
will conformed to that.

01:03:12.950 --> 01:03:16.230
And then you know, they
actually remained Muslims.

01:03:16.230 --> 01:03:20.080
And we have several
examples of that in Brazil,

01:03:20.080 --> 01:03:22.930
in Jamaica, in Trinidad.

01:03:22.930 --> 01:03:30.720
And when you read these
particular autobiographies,

01:03:30.720 --> 01:03:39.520
you see how opaque if you
will it is, how contradictory.

01:03:39.520 --> 01:03:46.080
And if he had been truly
converted as a Christian,

01:03:46.080 --> 01:03:51.520
there wouldn't have been
I think this need to kind

01:03:51.520 --> 01:03:55.110
of say one thing from
one side of his mouth

01:03:55.110 --> 01:03:59.910
and another from the other.

01:03:59.910 --> 01:04:02.650
It's confusing and
Ala, of course,

01:04:02.650 --> 01:04:08.710
you're very well
placed to dig into that.

01:04:08.710 --> 01:04:14.100
But again, if he had
been a true Christian,

01:04:14.100 --> 01:04:18.150
there wouldn't have been
the need to be that opaque,

01:04:18.150 --> 01:04:23.060
that complicated, that unclear.

01:04:23.060 --> 01:04:25.920
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
And Adam,

01:04:25.920 --> 01:04:29.960
the autobiography
was written in 1831.

01:04:29.960 --> 01:04:32.580
And I'll switch us
here in other ways.

01:04:32.580 --> 01:04:36.720
Can you speak to the context
of that particular year

01:04:36.720 --> 01:04:40.460
and the years surrounding it and
whether there's a coincidence

01:04:40.460 --> 01:04:43.430
in play or they're connected.

01:04:43.430 --> 01:04:45.640
&gt;&gt; Dr. Aldam Rothman: 1831
was an auspicious year

01:04:45.640 --> 01:04:51.150
in American slavery, the year
of Nat Turner's insurrection

01:04:51.150 --> 01:04:56.830
and the publication of Nat
Turner's alleged confessions.

01:04:56.830 --> 01:04:58.200
It's really interesting I think

01:04:58.200 --> 01:05:07.120
to compare these two
biographies, the one ostensibly

01:05:07.120 --> 01:05:11.970
of Turner written by a white
lawyer who had interviewed him

01:05:11.970 --> 01:05:18.360
in jail which represents
Turner as a kind of prophet

01:05:18.360 --> 01:05:21.290
or religious fanatic,
depending on your perspective.

01:05:21.290 --> 01:05:23.470
So that's one thing
that's happening in 1831.

01:05:23.470 --> 01:05:25.350
And on one hand Turner's
insurrection

01:05:25.350 --> 01:05:29.410
of course causes widespread
panic across the south

01:05:29.410 --> 01:05:35.310
about the possibility of slave
insurrection and provokes a kind

01:05:35.310 --> 01:05:39.150
of backlash, a crackdown
against slaves and free people

01:05:39.150 --> 01:05:40.890
of color across the south.

01:05:40.890 --> 01:05:43.750
So you have that going on.

01:05:43.750 --> 01:05:48.460
At the same time you have
Omar Ibn Said writing his own

01:05:48.460 --> 01:05:52.190
autobiography which represents
a totally different kind

01:05:52.190 --> 01:05:58.240
of textual presence or
representation of the life

01:05:58.240 --> 01:06:00.990
of an enslaved person.

01:06:00.990 --> 01:06:03.580
And I think there's
no direct connection

01:06:03.580 --> 01:06:11.090
between those two events, but
I do think that by the time

01:06:11.090 --> 01:06:13.720
that Omar writes
this autobiography,

01:06:13.720 --> 01:06:17.530
he's already become a
kind of minor celebrity.

01:06:17.530 --> 01:06:23.380
Especially in the colonization
circles that Ala mentioned.

01:06:23.380 --> 01:06:27.650
So the colonizationists
do represent this kind

01:06:27.650 --> 01:06:29.490
of middle ground or third way

01:06:29.490 --> 01:06:33.190
between abolitionism
and pro-slavery.

01:06:33.190 --> 01:06:36.130
And they're trying to cultivate
a different way of thinking

01:06:36.130 --> 01:06:40.530
about slavery and its demise and
also a different relationship

01:06:40.530 --> 01:06:43.530
between the United
States and Africa.

01:06:43.530 --> 01:06:46.450
So there's a kind of broad pivot
between Africa as a reservoir

01:06:46.450 --> 01:06:49.650
of labor through
the slave trade.

01:06:49.650 --> 01:06:52.330
And in the 19th century,
Africa as kind of an object

01:06:52.330 --> 01:06:54.230
of salvation and civilization.

01:06:54.230 --> 01:06:57.170
This is what the
missionaries are up to.

01:06:57.170 --> 01:07:01.760
And they see Omar Ibn Said as
this cultured, literate African

01:07:01.760 --> 01:07:06.200
who in their minds had
converted to Christianity.

01:07:06.200 --> 01:07:10.470
And they see in him a
model for all of Africa.

01:07:10.470 --> 01:07:11.770
And I think that's one

01:07:11.770 --> 01:07:15.390
of the reasons why they
illicit this autobiography

01:07:15.390 --> 01:07:18.160
and he's described in
various colonization --

01:07:18.160 --> 01:07:21.630
there are articles about him
in colonizationist publications

01:07:21.630 --> 01:07:24.540
where he really represents
this possibility

01:07:24.540 --> 01:07:27.930
of civilizing Africa.

01:07:27.930 --> 01:07:32.620
So I think to put Omar
Ibn Said's autobiography

01:07:32.620 --> 01:07:36.450
in conversation with
Turner's confessions is

01:07:36.450 --> 01:07:44.930
to show a wide range of both
the positions of enslaved people

01:07:44.930 --> 01:07:49.440
in America in the early
1830's, but also the variety

01:07:49.440 --> 01:07:54.150
of white responses to
the problem of slavery.

01:07:54.150 --> 01:07:55.610
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan: And
we should encourage everybody,

01:07:55.610 --> 01:07:58.710
if they're going to read
one autobiography this year,

01:07:58.710 --> 01:08:00.310
it should be his, right?

01:08:00.310 --> 01:08:04.500
Because it's actually quite
short as well, which is handy.

01:08:04.500 --> 01:08:09.710
So do we know details
of his life between 1831

01:08:09.710 --> 01:08:12.070
and his death in 1863?

01:08:12.070 --> 01:08:21.450
Perhaps we could sort of
sketch that out briefly?

01:08:21.450 --> 01:08:24.970
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sylviane Diuof: Well,
after he was bought by Owen

01:08:24.970 --> 01:08:32.580
who was a brother of the
governor of North Carolina,

01:08:32.580 --> 01:08:40.200
he was said to have been put
to kind of light work regime,

01:08:40.200 --> 01:08:43.950
gardening and that
kind of things.

01:08:43.950 --> 01:08:48.930
The thing also is that
there's no good slavery.

01:08:48.930 --> 01:08:54.630
And the fact also is
that he died enslaved.

01:08:54.630 --> 01:08:56.980
And there was no
good reason for that.

01:08:56.980 --> 01:08:58.530
I mean, no good reason.

01:08:58.530 --> 01:09:05.440
He could have been freed, he
could have stayed where he was

01:09:05.440 --> 01:09:10.470
and continued working
or drawing an income.

01:09:10.470 --> 01:09:12.310
He died enslaved.

01:09:12.310 --> 01:09:24.190
So you know, even though by
some measure his enslavement was

01:09:24.190 --> 01:09:29.260
lighter if you will in the
sense that he was not punished,

01:09:29.260 --> 01:09:36.080
he did not have this horrible
workload, he was not abused --

01:09:36.080 --> 01:09:37.810
and that's what he says.

01:09:37.810 --> 01:09:39.110
But at the same time,

01:09:39.110 --> 01:09:46.160
in his autobiography he
denounces slavery in the way

01:09:46.160 --> 01:09:52.480
that he says that you know,
"I eat what they eat."

01:09:52.480 --> 01:09:58.320
I mean, it's not
his exact words,

01:09:58.320 --> 01:10:03.000
but "I have clothes,
I am not naked.

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:06.320
I'm not abused."

01:10:06.320 --> 01:10:09.040
Meaning that the
others are, right?

01:10:09.040 --> 01:10:17.700
And so in that way he is
also denouncing slavery,

01:10:17.700 --> 01:10:22.400
even as he contrasts
the normal lot

01:10:22.400 --> 01:10:27.040
of enslaved people to his own.

01:10:27.040 --> 01:10:29.110
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes:
So regarding his life,

01:10:29.110 --> 01:10:35.670
there are fascinating contexts
that you find when you dig

01:10:35.670 --> 01:10:39.650
into the research and when
you look at known facts

01:10:39.650 --> 01:10:42.390
and context at an angle.

01:10:42.390 --> 01:10:45.460
So for example, one

01:10:45.460 --> 01:10:50.940
of my favorite 19th-century
African American texts is David

01:10:50.940 --> 01:10:56.060
Walker's 1829 Appeal for the
Colored Citizens of the World

01:10:56.060 --> 01:10:58.850
which he modelled on the
US Constitution, right,

01:10:58.850 --> 01:11:00.150
with a preamble and everything.

01:11:00.150 --> 01:11:02.790
It is a really remarkable
document inasmuch

01:11:02.790 --> 01:11:07.350
as he creates a document
that is modeled

01:11:07.350 --> 01:11:12.530
on the supposedly
universal Constitution.

01:11:12.530 --> 01:11:17.850
But it speaks to
black experience.

01:11:17.850 --> 01:11:19.150
And the appeal

01:11:19.150 --> 01:11:24.090
by the [inaudible] made him
really a hated man in the south.

01:11:24.090 --> 01:11:27.080
They were like Turner of course

01:11:27.080 --> 01:11:29.900
after the rebellion
two years later.

01:11:29.900 --> 01:11:38.190
And I found a letter which
was written to precisely Owen,

01:11:38.190 --> 01:11:42.620
John Owen who was then the
governor of South Carolina,

01:11:42.620 --> 01:11:46.360
the brother of the man in
whose house Omar resided

01:11:46.360 --> 01:11:47.820
for so many years.

01:11:47.820 --> 01:11:52.780
And that letter alerts
the governor to the fact

01:11:52.780 --> 01:11:58.780
that there have been attempts
to translate or to actually read

01:11:58.780 --> 01:12:01.510
that book to the
illiterate slaves, right?

01:12:01.510 --> 01:12:05.640
To the illiterate slaves
around where you live.

01:12:05.640 --> 01:12:07.730
And so be on the
lookout for that.

01:12:07.730 --> 01:12:10.590
And certainly Omar who never
learned English could not have

01:12:10.590 --> 01:12:14.030
read the appeal in English,
but he could have listened

01:12:14.030 --> 01:12:15.640
to someone reading it, right?

01:12:15.640 --> 01:12:18.810
Clearly that letter makes the
case that there are people going

01:12:18.810 --> 01:12:25.010
around reading that appeal
as Walker himself said

01:12:25.010 --> 01:12:29.020
when he offered the pamphlet
for no cost to people

01:12:29.020 --> 01:12:31.780
who would read it to your
brethren who were illiterate,

01:12:31.780 --> 01:12:33.560
right, could not read
it for themselves.

01:12:33.560 --> 01:12:35.460
So there are these
fascinating intersections

01:12:35.460 --> 01:12:40.600
that remind us again of, as
Adam was saying, the historicity

01:12:40.600 --> 01:12:45.590
of Omar not only
in Africa which is

01:12:45.590 --> 01:12:47.820
to be emphasized
but also in America.

01:12:47.820 --> 01:12:54.180
That history speaks
broadly and it's wider

01:12:54.180 --> 01:13:03.720
and full context are his
words placed in the context

01:13:03.720 --> 01:13:07.190
of his intentions as well
as in the other texts

01:13:07.190 --> 01:13:08.890
that were circulating
at that time

01:13:08.890 --> 01:13:11.200
and the other political
acts that were being played.

01:13:11.200 --> 01:13:18.580
The full history of that
reprehensible institution.

01:13:18.580 --> 01:13:20.830
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan: As you
said, that full history has sort

01:13:20.830 --> 01:13:24.190
of a deep fascination but
also a deep sadness running

01:13:24.190 --> 01:13:26.510
through the whole thing.

01:13:26.510 --> 01:13:30.640
Omar dies in 1863 and Adam,

01:13:30.640 --> 01:13:32.800
I believe you discovered
his obituary.

01:13:32.800 --> 01:13:37.410
Is that correct, while
you were researching?

01:13:37.410 --> 01:13:38.710
&gt;&gt; Dr. Aldam Rothman: Yeah.

01:13:38.710 --> 01:13:43.860
Just to add to this connotation
about Omar's life after 1831,

01:13:43.860 --> 01:13:46.550
I do think bits and pieces
of this have come up already.

01:13:46.550 --> 01:13:48.590
But I think it's
important to understand

01:13:48.590 --> 01:13:54.630
that 1831 autobiography is not
the only thing that Omar wrote

01:13:54.630 --> 01:13:57.420
and that still exists
in the archives.

01:13:57.420 --> 01:14:00.660
There's actually quite
an extensive set of --

01:14:00.660 --> 01:14:04.550
he left a paper trail, is what
I'm saying here, in Arabic.

01:14:04.550 --> 01:14:06.950
That extends to the 1850's.

01:14:06.950 --> 01:14:12.380
So his story archivally
speaking is even richer

01:14:12.380 --> 01:14:15.290
than just his extraordinary
1831 autobiography.

01:14:15.290 --> 01:14:17.210
It's one of the things
that makes him so,

01:14:17.210 --> 01:14:19.990
so deeply fascinating.

01:14:19.990 --> 01:14:21.990
But I do think that
the main fact is

01:14:21.990 --> 01:14:24.210
that he remains enslaved.

01:14:24.210 --> 01:14:29.710
Unlike so many other African
Americans who made their way --

01:14:29.710 --> 01:14:31.850
not so many, but some
other African Americans

01:14:31.850 --> 01:14:33.440
who made their way
from slavery to freedom

01:14:33.440 --> 01:14:35.070
and then wrote their stories,

01:14:35.070 --> 01:14:37.270
like Frederick Douglass
for instance.

01:14:37.270 --> 01:14:42.160
Omar is unusual because he
never made it to freedom.

01:14:42.160 --> 01:14:46.260
Yet we have this
archival record of him

01:14:46.260 --> 01:14:48.900
as a person held in bondage.

01:14:48.900 --> 01:14:50.290
And just the point -- I mean,

01:14:50.290 --> 01:14:53.730
he lived a long life,
a really long life.

01:14:53.730 --> 01:14:55.440
More than 90 years.

01:14:55.440 --> 01:14:59.690
But just not quite long enough
to make it back to freedom.

01:14:59.690 --> 01:15:02.180
I mean, if he lasts
just two more years,

01:15:02.180 --> 01:15:06.290
he sees emancipation
in North Carolina.

01:15:06.290 --> 01:15:11.080
And then how would the
story be different?

01:15:11.080 --> 01:15:13.320
If he had lived just those
two more years and been able

01:15:13.320 --> 01:15:18.330
to tell us stories of a free
person, what would he have said?

01:15:18.330 --> 01:15:24.590
That's to me one of the things
that's so sad about this.

01:15:24.590 --> 01:15:32.170
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan: Ala,
did you want to add to that?

01:15:32.170 --> 01:15:33.470
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes: Maybe later.

01:15:33.470 --> 01:15:34.770
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
You each have --

01:15:34.770 --> 01:15:36.410
I mentioned the obituary.

01:15:36.410 --> 01:15:41.410
You each have sort of a
close connection to Omar

01:15:41.410 --> 01:15:44.540
and to the collection
or the autobiography

01:15:44.540 --> 01:15:48.250
or the more extensive
collection.

01:15:48.250 --> 01:15:52.320
Perhaps we can touch
on those intersections,

01:15:52.320 --> 01:15:53.740
each of you in turn.

01:15:53.740 --> 01:15:56.700
Ala, perhaps you can start
in terms of what drew you

01:15:56.700 --> 01:16:00.760
to translating the
autobiography,

01:16:00.760 --> 01:16:03.990
which had been done,
what, two or three times

01:16:03.990 --> 01:16:06.360
and it's been sort of
lost and rediscovered.

01:16:06.360 --> 01:16:10.600
What drew you to it?

01:16:10.600 --> 01:16:13.580
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes: At
first it began at that time

01:16:13.580 --> 01:16:22.650
to resurrect the words, thinking
about the words of someone

01:16:22.650 --> 01:16:27.460
who is so distinctive and
in many ways unique to think

01:16:27.460 --> 01:16:31.320
about what his words
mean to us today,

01:16:31.320 --> 01:16:35.020
to think about the
fuller debate on slavery

01:16:35.020 --> 01:16:36.960
that those words can entail.

01:16:36.960 --> 01:16:41.630
And that as I said before
kind of morphed into --

01:16:41.630 --> 01:16:45.720
connected with the story of
the bigger historical work.

01:16:45.720 --> 01:16:47.820
So there was -- I
mean, I'm a professor

01:16:47.820 --> 01:16:49.840
of comparative literature
in English

01:16:49.840 --> 01:16:55.790
and I spend my days
thinking about the way

01:16:55.790 --> 01:17:03.490
in which you interpret words
and sentences put together.

01:17:03.490 --> 01:17:08.780
And there is a fascinating
sentence by W. E. B. Dubois

01:17:08.780 --> 01:17:13.980
that as I recall it,
"The expression in words

01:17:13.980 --> 01:17:18.870
of the tragic experience
of the negro race is

01:17:18.870 --> 01:17:20.440
to be found in various places."

01:17:20.440 --> 01:17:23.290
And it was fascinating
that in addition

01:17:23.290 --> 01:17:28.710
to the well-known places
of the Negro Spirituals

01:17:28.710 --> 01:17:30.200
or the Slave Narratives,

01:17:30.200 --> 01:17:33.190
wills in which certainly
slaves were left

01:17:33.190 --> 01:17:34.820
as property from someone.

01:17:34.820 --> 01:17:36.790
I mean, that kind of expression

01:17:36.790 --> 01:17:40.260
of how they were treated
or seen as slaves.

01:17:40.260 --> 01:17:48.150
But their own expressions we see
in this autobiography by someone

01:17:48.150 --> 01:17:52.360
that in a way reorients
I think the debates

01:17:52.360 --> 01:17:55.530
about slave narratives
themselves.

01:17:55.530 --> 01:18:01.110
So in a way I was drawn to
it first through the words

01:18:01.110 --> 01:18:04.290
of the man, then trying
to think about his agency.

01:18:04.290 --> 01:18:10.840
The fact that he was -- that
the opacity of his narrative

01:18:10.840 --> 01:18:16.110
when he opens it for
example by a particular surah

01:18:16.110 --> 01:18:20.160
from the Koran, that seemed
to me to be included as kind

01:18:20.160 --> 01:18:22.150
of a message, a hidden message

01:18:22.150 --> 01:18:25.170
that his owners had
no right over him.

01:18:25.170 --> 01:18:29.650
That the possession and power
are all in the hands of God.

01:18:29.650 --> 01:18:34.170
This seemed to kind of
go against the narrative

01:18:34.170 --> 01:18:39.550
of his conversion, right,
or his slavery itself.

01:18:39.550 --> 01:18:44.030
And to go back to your
question about earlier moments

01:18:44.030 --> 01:18:46.630
of translation, I mean
what is different is

01:18:46.630 --> 01:18:50.620
that certainly before the
overarching assumption

01:18:50.620 --> 01:18:54.010
about this man and
this narrative was

01:18:54.010 --> 01:19:01.130
that he is essentially a
convert to Christianity, right?

01:19:01.130 --> 01:19:08.010
His culture vindicates
the missionary converting,

01:19:08.010 --> 01:19:12.240
evangelizing aspect
of the people

01:19:12.240 --> 01:19:14.490
who were circulating his work.

01:19:14.490 --> 01:19:19.920
And not necessarily or not at
all that it proves the universal

01:19:19.920 --> 01:19:22.670
or near-universal
obviously education

01:19:22.670 --> 01:19:24.800
of people back in Africa, right?

01:19:24.800 --> 01:19:28.730
So in a way I began my
translation and I began thinking

01:19:28.730 --> 01:19:31.660
about his words and interpreting
them with different assumptions

01:19:31.660 --> 01:19:34.560
which I think make a difference.

01:19:34.560 --> 01:19:35.860
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
Thank you.

01:19:35.860 --> 01:19:38.060
And Adam, in your most recent
book, Beyond Freedom's Reach:

01:19:38.060 --> 01:19:41.230
A Kidnapping in the
Twilight of Slavery --

01:19:41.230 --> 01:19:44.230
and this is while you were a
visiting Kluge scholar here

01:19:44.230 --> 01:19:46.950
at the Library of Congress
carrying out research

01:19:46.950 --> 01:19:51.070
on African American voices
from slavery to freedom during

01:19:51.070 --> 01:19:54.550
which time you graciously helped
us out with some translations

01:19:54.550 --> 01:19:58.150
in the collections of Omar.

01:19:58.150 --> 01:20:02.170
Can you tell us a little
bit more about that?

01:20:02.170 --> 01:20:03.470
If you can give a plug

01:20:03.470 --> 01:20:06.350
to Chronicling America,
that would be okay.

01:20:06.350 --> 01:20:08.940
&gt;&gt; Dr. Aldam Rothman: Yeah,
like I said at the beginning,

01:20:08.940 --> 01:20:11.770
I'm really a latecomer
to Omar Ibn Said compared

01:20:11.770 --> 01:20:15.340
to the other scholars
sitting up here.

01:20:15.340 --> 01:20:17.280
But I just happened to be sort

01:20:17.280 --> 01:20:19.490
of in the right place
at the right time.

01:20:19.490 --> 01:20:23.690
I was here at the library Kluge
Center last semester working

01:20:23.690 --> 01:20:26.450
on a project of trying
to find material

01:20:26.450 --> 01:20:31.940
in the Manuscript Collections
written by African Americans,

01:20:31.940 --> 01:20:35.060
especially enslaved African
Americans in the 19th century.

01:20:35.060 --> 01:20:37.320
I mean, the Manuscript
Collections are vast.

01:20:37.320 --> 01:20:39.350
Millions of pages of material.

01:20:39.350 --> 01:20:45.550
But only here and there do you
find anything actually written

01:20:45.550 --> 01:20:48.110
by a person who was enslaved.

01:20:48.110 --> 01:20:50.560
And I wanted to highlight
that material.

01:20:50.560 --> 01:20:55.840
So of course, the news that the
Omar Ibn Said autobiography had

01:20:55.840 --> 01:20:59.130
come into the library and that
the library was doing a whole

01:20:59.130 --> 01:21:00.640
project around it was
incredibly exciting.

01:21:00.640 --> 01:21:05.900
And then I was doing a series
of podcasts about the material

01:21:05.900 --> 01:21:08.260
that I found in the manuscript
division, so we decided

01:21:08.260 --> 01:21:11.240
to do one on Omar Ibn Said.

01:21:11.240 --> 01:21:13.650
So that should be
coming out pretty soon.

01:21:13.650 --> 01:21:16.520
Sylviane is on it and
Mary Jane as well.

01:21:16.520 --> 01:21:19.050
And for those of you
who like podcasts,

01:21:19.050 --> 01:21:20.520
be on the lookout for that.

01:21:20.520 --> 01:21:27.110
But that's also part of a
broader I think goal which is

01:21:27.110 --> 01:21:33.390
to find new ways of telling
stories about history.

01:21:33.390 --> 01:21:37.530
Finding new ways to bring
manuscript materials

01:21:37.530 --> 01:21:39.870
and archival materials to light.

01:21:39.870 --> 01:21:42.950
You know, as scholars we sort
of seem to have a special

01:21:42.950 --> 01:21:44.790
and privileged access
to these materials.

01:21:44.790 --> 01:21:47.440
But something like Omar Ibn
Said's autobiography really

01:21:47.440 --> 01:21:49.370
ought to be accessible
to everyone.

01:21:49.370 --> 01:21:50.950
It's that important.

01:21:50.950 --> 01:21:59.550
And part of that is
digitizing these materials.

01:21:59.550 --> 01:22:02.900
Part of it is translating

01:22:02.900 --> 01:22:05.970
and transcribing the
original documents.

01:22:05.970 --> 01:22:07.730
So my role was really
just to take some

01:22:07.730 --> 01:22:10.170
of the English language
documents in the collection,

01:22:10.170 --> 01:22:17.210
which are really remarkable,
and just transcribe them.

01:22:17.210 --> 01:22:21.120
Now many of you in this audience
look like you're of a generation

01:22:21.120 --> 01:22:24.030
that probably knows
how to read cursive.

01:22:24.030 --> 01:22:26.040
[ Laughter ]

01:22:26.040 --> 01:22:27.540
But some of you may not.

01:22:27.540 --> 01:22:30.380
Reading cursive is
actually a dying art.

01:22:30.380 --> 01:22:34.030
And it's not just reading
cursive, but going through some

01:22:34.030 --> 01:22:35.520
of these 19th century
manuscripts,

01:22:35.520 --> 01:22:38.330
the handwriting is
actually difficult to read.

01:22:38.330 --> 01:22:40.560
I happen to have decades now

01:22:40.560 --> 01:22:42.770
of experience reading
19th century handwriting,

01:22:42.770 --> 01:22:45.160
so I thought, let's put
those skills to good use.

01:22:45.160 --> 01:22:47.010
I transcribed some
of these materials

01:22:47.010 --> 01:22:48.980
to make them more accessible

01:22:48.980 --> 01:22:53.070
in the overall digital
platform of the project.

01:22:53.070 --> 01:22:57.580
But actually transcribing
19th-century

01:22:57.580 --> 01:23:00.460
and archival materials,

01:23:00.460 --> 01:23:03.810
it's much like how Ala
described translating materials

01:23:03.810 --> 01:23:05.500
from Arabic from English.

01:23:05.500 --> 01:23:08.110
You just get a closer bond

01:23:08.110 --> 01:23:12.210
to the language and
to the artifacts.

01:23:12.210 --> 01:23:14.240
It just stays with you better.

01:23:14.240 --> 01:23:15.840
You sit with it.

01:23:15.840 --> 01:23:17.930
You just ruminate about it.

01:23:17.930 --> 01:23:19.750
And so doing these
transcriptions led me

01:23:19.750 --> 01:23:21.310
to do some of my own research.

01:23:21.310 --> 01:23:23.290
I started noodling
around on the Library

01:23:23.290 --> 01:23:25.160
of Congress's Chronicling
America website

01:23:25.160 --> 01:23:30.710
which is an incredible database
of historical newspapers.

01:23:30.710 --> 01:23:37.880
And doing that led me to this
1863 obituary of Omar Ibn Said

01:23:37.880 --> 01:23:40.230
in a North Carolina newspaper.

01:23:40.230 --> 01:23:43.300
So how many enslaved people
got their obituary written

01:23:43.300 --> 01:23:45.580
in a newspaper in
the 19th century?

01:23:45.580 --> 01:23:51.250
That's just a testament of
the kind of celebrity of Omar.

01:23:51.250 --> 01:23:53.970
But that was my connection
to this project,

01:23:53.970 --> 01:23:57.900
and it was really -- I'll tell
you all a tremendous thrill

01:23:57.900 --> 01:24:00.230
to get to the library and
have an opportunity to work

01:24:00.230 --> 01:24:02.770
on something as important,
significant

01:24:02.770 --> 01:24:05.440
and tremendous as this.

01:24:05.440 --> 01:24:06.740
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
Terrific.

01:24:06.740 --> 01:24:09.620
And Sylviane, your engagement
with Omar might be the longest,

01:24:09.620 --> 01:24:12.360
certainly over 20 years or so.

01:24:12.360 --> 01:24:13.660
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sylviane Diuof: Yes.

01:24:13.660 --> 01:24:15.080
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
And you've intersected

01:24:15.080 --> 01:24:17.680
with the collection and the
Library of Congress on a couple

01:24:17.680 --> 01:24:20.820
of occasions over those
couple of decades.

01:24:20.820 --> 01:24:24.300
Could you tell us about that and
what it all means to you today?

01:24:24.300 --> 01:24:26.000
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sylviane Diuof: Yeah.

01:24:26.000 --> 01:24:31.900
My encounter with Omar
probably started when I decided

01:24:31.900 --> 01:24:37.330
to write this book on Muslims
enslaved in the Americas.

01:24:37.330 --> 01:24:41.850
And I don't remember
exactly when I got this idea.

01:24:41.850 --> 01:24:44.280
I think it was probably
'93, '94.

01:24:44.280 --> 01:24:47.700
So I encountered Omar then.

01:24:47.700 --> 01:24:53.910
But at kind of two encounters,
if you will, with him.

01:24:53.910 --> 01:25:05.970
I mentioned earlier that he was
taken a prisoner of war in 1807

01:25:05.970 --> 01:25:11.830
and during this entire
[inaudible] coalition.

01:25:11.830 --> 01:25:19.390
And I mean, to me there's
a family connection there.

01:25:19.390 --> 01:25:27.210
Sulaiman Ball whose text I read
earlier, and [inaudible] as well

01:25:27.210 --> 01:25:35.060
as many of the Islamist
reformists studied

01:25:35.060 --> 01:25:41.100
at [inaudible] in Senegal
which is a very renowned school

01:25:41.100 --> 01:25:47.790
which was founded by my
ancestor Hami Amachfal in 1603.

01:25:47.790 --> 01:25:51.870
So I had this particular
connection.

01:25:51.870 --> 01:25:56.710
Then while I was writing,
I was almost finished.

01:25:56.710 --> 01:26:04.560
When I was writing Servants
of Allah, I learned in '96

01:26:04.560 --> 01:26:08.860
that there was this
auction in New York

01:26:08.860 --> 01:26:13.380
of the manuscript plus others.

01:26:13.380 --> 01:26:19.110
So I went there not exactly
to buy it, even though I tried

01:26:19.110 --> 01:26:24.760
to interest somebody who had
more money that I did to buy it.

01:26:24.760 --> 01:26:35.270
So I got there and I was
looking at the document.

01:26:35.270 --> 01:26:43.100
And you know, this young
man came and very affable

01:26:43.100 --> 01:26:49.310
and sociable, and it's only
that he wanted to buy it

01:26:49.310 --> 01:26:53.700
and introduce himself,
Derrick Beard, Muslim.

01:26:53.700 --> 01:26:57.160
And you know, we
started to talk.

01:26:57.160 --> 01:27:04.350
And you know, the price was
not that expensive at all.

01:27:04.350 --> 01:27:09.450
And I thought, "Well,
he's there all alone.

01:27:09.450 --> 01:27:15.620
I'm sure a lot of other people
are interested as well."

01:27:15.620 --> 01:27:21.200
And I was kind of
appalled by the fact

01:27:21.200 --> 01:27:26.560
that nobody bid for
that collection.

01:27:26.560 --> 01:27:28.650
He was the only one.

01:27:28.650 --> 01:27:31.400
And I was happy for him,
but I thought, "Okay,

01:27:31.400 --> 01:27:38.910
there's no museum, there's no
archive, library, university,

01:27:38.910 --> 01:27:43.370
collectors who are
interested in this unique" --

01:27:43.370 --> 01:27:45.230
because it was not
only the manuscript.

01:27:45.230 --> 01:27:47.890
It was other things as well.

01:27:47.890 --> 01:27:52.460
And I thought, "Okay,
nobody is interested?"

01:27:52.460 --> 01:28:00.690
And I was surprised and I
was disappointed as well.

01:28:00.690 --> 01:28:05.300
You know, fortunately
the interest came after.

01:28:05.300 --> 01:28:10.620
But at least the good
thing about the fact

01:28:10.620 --> 01:28:16.600
that Derrick bought it is
that he really exposed it

01:28:16.600 --> 01:28:23.480
in the sense that he was
always willing to lend it

01:28:23.480 --> 01:28:27.760
to scholars and others.

01:28:27.760 --> 01:28:34.090
To have it read,
translated, written about.

01:28:34.090 --> 01:28:39.330
He did something that was
in my view very moving.

01:28:39.330 --> 01:28:44.750
As I mentioned, he
bought it in 1996.

01:28:44.750 --> 01:28:52.540
In 1998, he took it to
Senegal in order to share it

01:28:52.540 --> 01:28:57.430
with the people of Senegal, with
the scholars and others there.

01:28:57.430 --> 01:29:03.910
And Omar never made it back,
but his manuscript did.

01:29:03.910 --> 01:29:08.050
And I thought that was you know,

01:29:08.050 --> 01:29:14.440
moving and that's
who Derrick was.

01:29:14.440 --> 01:29:15.740
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
Thank you.

01:29:15.740 --> 01:29:20.300
I will be opening it up
to questions in a minute.

01:29:20.300 --> 01:29:23.210
Any sort of final
thoughts before we open it

01:29:23.210 --> 01:29:25.200
up to questions, Ala?

01:29:25.200 --> 01:29:28.330
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes: Since
there is a large number

01:29:28.330 --> 01:29:34.980
of young people here, I think
one important thing to say,

01:29:34.980 --> 01:29:40.410
one important advice is learn
foreign languages, right?

01:29:40.410 --> 01:29:48.200
That method of multiculturism
in the US, as positive as it is,

01:29:48.200 --> 01:29:52.100
short-changes the
fact that people come

01:29:52.100 --> 01:29:54.790
with their own culture
to this country,

01:29:54.790 --> 01:29:57.900
and those cultures are
encoded in their own languages.

01:29:57.900 --> 01:29:59.970
And often the only
access you'll have

01:29:59.970 --> 01:30:01.930
to other people's cultures is

01:30:01.930 --> 01:30:03.950
if you take the time
to learn languages.

01:30:03.950 --> 01:30:06.760
Not everything comes in English.

01:30:10.290 --> 01:30:11.790
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
So before I open it

01:30:11.790 --> 01:30:14.520
up to questions, please
join me in saying thank you

01:30:14.520 --> 01:30:16.510
to our terrific panel.

01:30:16.510 --> 01:30:25.350
