01:30:26.870 --> 01:30:28.170
Yes, sir?

01:30:28.170 --> 01:30:30.900
&gt;&gt; Hi, Ishmael Royer from the
Religious Freedom Institute.

01:30:30.900 --> 01:30:32.200
Thank you.

01:30:32.200 --> 01:30:36.110
This is a fascinating and
overlooked topic, all of you.

01:30:36.110 --> 01:30:39.760
And I was wondering
if anyone who wanted

01:30:39.760 --> 01:30:42.210
to could say something
about what this collection

01:30:42.210 --> 01:30:44.870
or more broadly what
the collection

01:30:44.870 --> 01:30:50.820
of materials that's available
from Muslim slaves says

01:30:50.820 --> 01:30:55.960
about the ability to
practice Islam as slaves.

01:30:55.960 --> 01:31:00.770
We know that there was
originally under slavery,

01:31:00.770 --> 01:31:02.770
slaves were not permitted
even to be Christians.

01:31:02.770 --> 01:31:07.220
So what did the slave
owners and so on,

01:31:07.220 --> 01:31:10.360
how did they handle their
slaves that were Muslims?

01:31:10.360 --> 01:31:13.550
What did they do to either
allow or oppress that?

01:31:13.550 --> 01:31:16.660
&gt;&gt; Dr. Sylviane Diuof:
I can address that.

01:31:16.660 --> 01:31:20.450
You know, there were
two different kinds

01:31:20.450 --> 01:31:22.720
of things, of attitude.

01:31:22.720 --> 01:31:31.060
You had really -- I mean, as
Muslims were known in the sense

01:31:31.060 --> 01:31:33.630
that people knew that they were.

01:31:33.630 --> 01:31:40.370
And that's why you have all
these testimonies of journalists

01:31:40.370 --> 01:31:44.490
and travelers and
slaveholders, et cetera.

01:31:44.490 --> 01:31:47.750
Mentioning my so and so is.

01:31:47.750 --> 01:31:49.940
So it was known.

01:31:49.940 --> 01:31:51.560
So you had this attitude,

01:31:51.560 --> 01:31:54.900
especially in Catholic
countries,

01:31:54.900 --> 01:31:57.690
where they had to convert.

01:31:57.690 --> 01:32:04.800
So the idea was you know,
you have to be Christian.

01:32:04.800 --> 01:32:09.410
And so you have all
these crypto-Muslims.

01:32:09.410 --> 01:32:15.740
You know, in an overt manner,
say that they are Christian

01:32:15.740 --> 01:32:21.650
or go through the motions
and actually remain Muslims.

01:32:21.650 --> 01:32:27.370
Then you also have people
who know that the people

01:32:27.370 --> 01:32:32.180
who are enslaved
can read and write.

01:32:32.180 --> 01:32:40.970
And it was mentioned by a
number of American scholars

01:32:40.970 --> 01:32:47.930
at the time, that that created
jealousy in slaveholders

01:32:47.930 --> 01:32:52.820
because they themselves
were illiterate.

01:32:52.820 --> 01:32:56.380
So that was kind of an
impediment also to learn more

01:32:56.380 --> 01:32:59.620
about the people
they had enslaved.

01:32:59.620 --> 01:33:03.410
You also had in the
United States this idea

01:33:03.410 --> 01:33:08.650
that the Muslims were not
Africans, that they were Arabs

01:33:08.650 --> 01:33:15.600
who had been taken
kind of by mistake.

01:33:15.600 --> 01:33:20.820
And that those Muslims,
those Arabs,

01:33:20.820 --> 01:33:26.590
despised the rest
of the Africans.

01:33:26.590 --> 01:33:31.090
And you know, so there were
sometimes these attempts

01:33:31.090 --> 01:33:35.540
at putting people one
against the other.

01:33:35.540 --> 01:33:38.330
So you had kind of
a multiplicity

01:33:38.330 --> 01:33:43.780
of attitudes concerning them.

01:33:43.780 --> 01:33:51.400
But we also find for example
in the islands of Georgia,

01:33:51.400 --> 01:33:56.190
people who had been enslaved and
had been freed were interviewed

01:33:56.190 --> 01:34:00.620
in the 1930's and who
described their parents

01:34:00.620 --> 01:34:04.480
and their grandparents
praying several times a day,

01:34:04.480 --> 01:34:09.550
having prayer beads,
having turbans.

01:34:09.550 --> 01:34:14.100
So we know that they continued

01:34:14.100 --> 01:34:17.900
on the plantations
to actually pray.

01:34:17.900 --> 01:34:24.610
So you know, again we have
all those different attitudes.

01:34:24.610 --> 01:34:28.780
The thing is that
Islam did not --

01:34:28.780 --> 01:34:31.090
I mean, Islam as brought

01:34:31.090 --> 01:34:35.030
by the West Africans did
not really continue even

01:34:35.030 --> 01:34:39.120
in countries like Brazil

01:34:39.120 --> 01:34:44.030
where you had really
established communities.

01:34:44.030 --> 01:34:45.330
So that's what I --

01:34:45.330 --> 01:34:49.230
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
Thank you for the question.

01:34:49.230 --> 01:34:50.830
Any other questions?

01:34:50.830 --> 01:34:52.130
Here.

01:34:52.130 --> 01:34:54.700
&gt;&gt; This side, please.

01:34:54.700 --> 01:34:56.440
Just a couple questions.

01:34:56.440 --> 01:35:01.880
One is, what do you know about
Omar Ibn Said's descendants

01:35:01.880 --> 01:35:03.180
and relatives in Senegal?

01:35:03.180 --> 01:35:04.540
And for that matter,
what do you know

01:35:04.540 --> 01:35:07.440
about his family
in North Carolina?

01:35:07.440 --> 01:35:09.890
Does he have descendants
that we know about?

01:35:09.890 --> 01:35:15.440
And two, what do you know about
the provenance of the documents

01:35:15.440 --> 01:35:20.380
from Omar Ibn Said
to Derrick Beard?

01:35:20.380 --> 01:35:22.860
How did Derrick Beard
acquire the documents?

01:35:22.860 --> 01:35:24.210
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes: The
provenance of the sale?

01:35:24.210 --> 01:35:26.440
How it came to Mr. Beard?

01:35:26.440 --> 01:35:28.280
&gt;&gt; How it came to
Mr. Beard, yeah.

01:35:28.280 --> 01:35:32.850
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes: There is
a well-documented provenance

01:35:32.850 --> 01:35:36.860
because the title page as I was
mentioning, which is written

01:35:36.860 --> 01:35:40.300
in English, describes
exactly the way --

01:35:40.300 --> 01:35:45.840
it says written by Omar and
then given by another slave

01:35:45.840 --> 01:35:50.460
and then translated ultimately
by a man called Theodore Dwight.

01:35:50.460 --> 01:35:54.470
Dwight was a member of the
American Ethnological Society.

01:35:54.470 --> 01:35:59.510
And he sends the
manuscript to another man,

01:35:59.510 --> 01:36:01.880
Isaac Byrd who then
has another --

01:36:01.880 --> 01:36:04.550
there's a letter actually in
the Theodore Dwight collection

01:36:04.550 --> 01:36:07.810
that has been acquired by the
Library of Congress as well

01:36:07.810 --> 01:36:09.890
within that rich collection,

01:36:09.890 --> 01:36:13.820
in which you see Isaac Byrd
responding to Theodore Dwight.

01:36:13.820 --> 01:36:17.260
There is a conversation
between them about a number

01:36:17.260 --> 01:36:18.610
of manuscripts that
have been sent

01:36:18.610 --> 01:36:20.580
to Isaac Byrd for translating.

01:36:20.580 --> 01:36:25.120
Isaac Byrd in later life
goes to Hartford, Connecticut

01:36:25.120 --> 01:36:27.060
and opens a school,
right, a private school.

01:36:27.060 --> 01:36:28.920
I mean, he has been a
linguist in the Middle East

01:36:28.920 --> 01:36:33.020
for many years and he ends his
life as a principle in Hartford.

01:36:33.020 --> 01:36:35.400
But he is well-known and that
manuscript gets sent to him.

01:36:35.400 --> 01:36:40.590
And he has it, and then it ends
up with I think the secretary

01:36:40.590 --> 01:36:44.260
of the American Numismatic
Society or something.

01:36:44.260 --> 01:36:45.560
We know that as well.

01:36:45.560 --> 01:36:48.470
And then the manuscript I think
ends up in his family kind

01:36:48.470 --> 01:36:50.310
of hidden in an attic.

01:36:50.310 --> 01:36:56.310
And then finally it comes out
and ends up at the gallery

01:36:56.310 --> 01:36:58.920
at that auction that
Slyviane has introduced.

01:36:58.920 --> 01:37:02.060
So there's actually a
well-known record of it,

01:37:02.060 --> 01:37:03.880
quite a remarkable one.

01:37:03.880 --> 01:37:07.880
As to your first
question, Omar never married

01:37:07.880 --> 01:37:09.960
or sired children in the US.

01:37:09.960 --> 01:37:13.240
I mean, he remained
a lonely man,

01:37:13.240 --> 01:37:15.100
a lonely presence
for whatever reason.

01:37:15.100 --> 01:37:16.790
I mean, maybe he
didn't want his children

01:37:16.790 --> 01:37:18.140
to be sold into slavery, right?

01:37:18.140 --> 01:37:21.970
I mean, maybe he saw what
happened in Charleston

01:37:21.970 --> 01:37:26.530
where he spent two years and saw
the way families were treated,

01:37:26.530 --> 01:37:30.520
that they were not
respected as families at all.

01:37:30.520 --> 01:37:35.460
And so in a sense, I think
that he never had children.

01:37:35.460 --> 01:37:37.450
He never had a progeny
in the US.

01:37:37.450 --> 01:37:39.260
&gt;&gt; Dr. Aldam Rothman: I
just want to add one thing

01:37:39.260 --> 01:37:42.900
to the question of the
provenance of the autobiography.

01:37:42.900 --> 01:37:47.090
One of the moments where the
autobiography reappears is

01:37:47.090 --> 01:37:49.290
in the early 20th century

01:37:49.290 --> 01:37:52.640
when a scholar named J. Franklin
Jameson somehow gets his hand

01:37:52.640 --> 01:37:56.180
on it and actually
translates it and publishes it

01:37:56.180 --> 01:37:57.840
in the American Historical
Review.

01:37:57.840 --> 01:38:01.690
Which is the leading journal
for American historians.

01:38:01.690 --> 01:38:04.860
So this is a document that's
been discussed by historians

01:38:04.860 --> 01:38:07.940
for 100 years and then has a
much longer history than that.

01:38:07.940 --> 01:38:11.310
But Jameson, the man who
translated and published this,

01:38:11.310 --> 01:38:14.380
then went on to become the chief
of the Manuscripts Division here

01:38:14.380 --> 01:38:15.790
at the Library of Congress.

01:38:15.790 --> 01:38:17.630
So there is a long Library

01:38:17.630 --> 01:38:21.770
of Congress connection
to this document.

01:38:21.770 --> 01:38:23.380
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan: So
we have a question over here.

01:38:23.380 --> 01:38:24.880
&gt;&gt; Yes. I'm Angela Pashane.

01:38:24.880 --> 01:38:28.000
I'm a PhD student at
Howard University.

01:38:28.000 --> 01:38:30.360
Thank you so much for
your contributions.

01:38:30.360 --> 01:38:34.000
It's just beyond beyond.

01:38:34.000 --> 01:38:35.300
Two questions.

01:38:35.300 --> 01:38:39.900
One, will the manuscript ever be
