01:38:42.010 --> 01:38:46.460
to have a course with the book?

01:38:46.460 --> 01:38:52.890
And two, I'm thinking about
the writings of Charles Meals

01:38:52.890 --> 01:38:55.240
in The Racial Contract.

01:38:55.240 --> 01:39:00.020
And I'm wondering how you
posit the importance of both

01:39:00.020 --> 01:39:02.420
of those writings together.

01:39:02.420 --> 01:39:04.020
And I know they're
completely different.

01:39:04.020 --> 01:39:06.680
I know they're from
completely different eras.

01:39:06.680 --> 01:39:10.110
But if you're familiar
with The Racial Contract

01:39:10.110 --> 01:39:17.290
and the importance of that piece
as compared to Omar Ibn Said.

01:39:21.040 --> 01:39:24.150
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes: So I'll
speak to the first question

01:39:24.150 --> 01:39:27.520
which is the manuscript is
now available on the website

01:39:27.520 --> 01:39:28.820
of the Library of
Congress itself

01:39:28.820 --> 01:39:31.820
of course in its full glory.

01:39:31.820 --> 01:39:34.170
But it's also available
in translation in my book.

01:39:34.170 --> 01:39:37.790
I hate to -- since you
were asking that question,

01:39:37.790 --> 01:39:41.340
I can take this occasion to
disavow plugging my book, right?

01:39:41.340 --> 01:39:42.640
&gt;&gt; Dr. Aldam Rothman:
I'll plug it for you.

01:39:42.640 --> 01:39:43.940
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan: Yeah.

01:39:43.940 --> 01:39:49.260
Is this the book that's for
sale outside at the break?

01:39:49.260 --> 01:39:51.620
Is that the book
we're talking about?

01:39:51.620 --> 01:39:55.350
&gt;&gt; Dr. Ala Alryyes:
Did I say that?

01:39:55.350 --> 01:39:57.630
But yes, available online.

01:39:57.630 --> 01:40:01.120
We also have facsimile
editions for on-site research.

01:40:01.120 --> 01:40:03.860
So that's one of
the exciting things

01:40:03.860 --> 01:40:05.770
about this theme throughout.

01:40:05.770 --> 01:40:10.080
It's been available, studied on
and off for quite a long time.

01:40:10.080 --> 01:40:13.650
And now it's readily available
to schools everywhere,

01:40:13.650 --> 01:40:17.840
high schools to colleges,
to book clubs, to churches.

01:40:17.840 --> 01:40:20.130
You just go on, as long
as you have a computer

01:40:20.130 --> 01:40:22.860
and an internet connection,
it's there for you.

01:40:22.860 --> 01:40:26.770
So that's a very exciting
aspect of all of this.

01:40:26.770 --> 01:40:28.070
Did we answer this?

01:40:28.070 --> 01:40:31.170
Was there a second
part to the question?

01:40:32.510 --> 01:40:37.010
[ Inaudible ]

01:40:37.010 --> 01:40:38.310
&gt;&gt; Dr. Aldam Rothman:

01:40:38.310 --> 01:40:40.760
So I actually cannot
answer that question.

01:40:40.760 --> 01:40:42.060
&gt;&gt; That's fine.

01:40:42.060 --> 01:40:43.500
&gt;&gt; Dr. Aldam Rothman:
But I do think

01:40:43.500 --> 01:40:45.920
that it is an exciting
opportunity

01:40:45.920 --> 01:40:51.270
to have this source available
to enter into all sorts

01:40:51.270 --> 01:40:56.660
of scholarly conversations
about race and slavery

01:40:56.660 --> 01:40:59.810
in American history,
about archival power,

01:40:59.810 --> 01:41:02.680
about religion and power.

01:41:02.680 --> 01:41:06.970
There are so many conversations
that this particular document

01:41:06.970 --> 01:41:09.450
and set of documents speaks to.

01:41:09.450 --> 01:41:11.680
And that's one of the
reasons why it's so exciting

01:41:11.680 --> 01:41:13.610
to have this material so readily

01:41:13.610 --> 01:41:16.920
and generally available
up on the website.

01:41:16.920 --> 01:41:19.520
So scholars can talk about
it, students can talk

01:41:19.520 --> 01:41:21.820
about it on every level.

01:41:21.820 --> 01:41:23.370
Just to give you one example,

01:41:23.370 --> 01:41:26.140
I'm teaching an Atlantic
history class this semester

01:41:26.140 --> 01:41:27.440
at Georgetown.

01:41:27.440 --> 01:41:32.340
And every week students have
to post an artifact to a map

01:41:32.340 --> 01:41:34.300
about Atlantic history.

01:41:34.300 --> 01:41:39.890
And then completely unprovoked
by me, two weeks ago one

01:41:39.890 --> 01:41:43.320
of the students used the
Omar Ibn Said autobiography

01:41:43.320 --> 01:41:44.620
for the map.

01:41:44.620 --> 01:41:47.720
Like the day after I
think it came online.

01:41:47.720 --> 01:41:51.710
So it's out there, it's
being used and it can enter

01:41:51.710 --> 01:41:55.260
into every conversation that
we can have about these issues.

01:41:55.260 --> 01:41:56.560
&gt;&gt; Dr. Eugene Flanagan:
Terrific.

01:41:56.560 --> 01:41:58.860
I believe we have a
question over here.

01:42:00.250 --> 01:42:01.550
&gt;&gt; [Inaudible] I
am a [inaudible].

01:42:01.550 --> 01:42:03.720
I am from the Muslim Institute.

01:42:03.720 --> 01:42:07.790
I am in the process of
