01:48:19.980 --> 01:48:22.090
There in Fayetteville,
North Carolina

01:48:22.090 --> 01:48:25.830
when Omar Ibn Said came
there and went to the jail,

01:48:25.830 --> 01:48:28.300
he wrote the Arabic on the wall.

01:48:28.300 --> 01:48:31.340
We have the church there, the
First Presbyterian Church.

01:48:31.340 --> 01:48:35.280
Where in the history of the
First Presbyterian Church,

01:48:35.280 --> 01:48:38.410
they have Omar annotated,
but they refer

01:48:38.410 --> 01:48:40.470
to him as Uncle Moran.

01:48:40.470 --> 01:48:43.720
And as to the question
that was earlier discussed,

01:48:43.720 --> 01:48:46.690
whether he accepted
Christianity or not,

01:48:46.690 --> 01:48:49.970
we find that he did not
convert to Christianity.

01:48:49.970 --> 01:48:53.970
As one of the scholars said,
based on the circumstances

01:48:53.970 --> 01:48:57.080
and the situation
he found himself in,

01:48:57.080 --> 01:49:00.260
he did many things
in order to adapt.

01:49:00.260 --> 01:49:03.150
The same way that from our
ancestors when they went

01:49:03.150 --> 01:49:05.730
down by the river,
maybe they sung a song,

01:49:05.730 --> 01:49:08.850
it was coded language
in order to adapt.

01:49:08.850 --> 01:49:10.510
Now I just want to
mention one thing.

01:49:10.510 --> 01:49:15.430
The young lady was asking
a question about if any

01:49:15.430 --> 01:49:17.820
of the predecessors converted

01:49:17.820 --> 01:49:20.940
or accepted Al Islam
or became Muslims.

01:49:20.940 --> 01:49:22.870
You know, the late
Dr. Sierra Lincoln

01:49:22.870 --> 01:49:25.570
who was a theologian there
at the Duke University,

01:49:25.570 --> 01:49:28.910
he said there is something in
the African American make up,

01:49:28.910 --> 01:49:32.120
he called it the
Islamic genetic memory.

01:49:32.120 --> 01:49:37.870
The Islamic genetic memory, that
somewhere in some place and time

01:49:37.870 --> 01:49:40.750
in our families, that gene

01:49:40.750 --> 01:49:44.620
or that genetic memory
is going to awaken in us.

01:49:44.620 --> 01:49:47.650
Now in my family, I'm the
only one that accepted.

01:49:47.650 --> 01:49:52.990
I heard the call and I
accepted Al Islam in 1973.

01:49:52.990 --> 01:49:57.140
Now we also have built two
edifices in Fayetteville,

01:49:57.140 --> 01:50:01.670
North Carolina honoring our
great ancestor Omar Ibn Said.

01:50:01.670 --> 01:50:04.490
We built two masjids
or houses of worship.

01:50:04.490 --> 01:50:08.390
This gentleman here, under his
leadership we built the first

01:50:08.390 --> 01:50:11.930
one as indigenous
Muslims in North Carolina.

01:50:11.930 --> 01:50:14.380
We structured Omar Ibn Said.

01:50:14.380 --> 01:50:17.150
Then when the highway
department came through

01:50:17.150 --> 01:50:22.060
and declared imminent domain,
well, we took that money

01:50:22.060 --> 01:50:24.370
and we built another masjid.

01:50:24.370 --> 01:50:27.610
Plus we have a marker
in North Carolina

01:50:27.610 --> 01:50:30.980
that recognized Omar
Ibn Said that was issued

01:50:30.980 --> 01:50:33.210
by the state of North Carolina.

01:50:33.210 --> 01:50:34.960
And these are very
important things

01:50:34.960 --> 01:50:38.340
because Omar Ibn
Said is all of us.

01:50:38.340 --> 01:50:41.570
Everyone sitting in this
room is Omar Ibn Said.

01:50:41.570 --> 01:50:44.460
What I like about your
presentation is first you talked

01:50:44.460 --> 01:50:46.660
about him as a human being.

01:50:46.660 --> 01:50:47.960
He was a human being.

01:50:47.960 --> 01:50:49.800
You talked about his identity.

01:50:49.800 --> 01:50:54.020
Then you also emphasized his
intellectual enlightenment.

01:50:54.020 --> 01:50:58.680
If you don't know, Omar
was very influential

01:50:58.680 --> 01:51:02.160
in bringing public
education to North Carolina

01:51:02.160 --> 01:51:03.610
through his legislation.

01:51:03.610 --> 01:51:07.050
And we thank you very much
for allowing us to be here

01:51:07.050 --> 01:51:09.810
at this great, great
program honoring a great,

01:51:09.810 --> 01:51:13.510
great human being,
Omar Ibn Said.

