with her graciousness and
tact were absolutely vital

02:00:29.640 --> 02:00:30.940
to pull this one off.

02:00:30.940 --> 02:00:32.970
So thank you, Colina.

02:00:32.970 --> 02:00:35.270
Now on with our show.

02:00:40.510 --> 02:00:48.690
[ Music ]

02:00:48.690 --> 02:00:51.880
&gt;&gt; You asked me to
write my life.

02:00:51.880 --> 02:00:57.580
I cannot write my life, for I
have forgotten much of my talk

02:00:57.580 --> 02:00:59.070
as well as the talk
of the Arabs.

02:00:59.070 --> 02:01:04.870
Oh, brother, in the name
of Allah, I ask you not

02:01:04.870 --> 02:01:10.740
to blame me, for my eye is
weak as well as my body.

02:01:10.740 --> 02:01:13.220
&gt;&gt; Omar Ibn Said was a famous

02:01:13.220 --> 02:01:17.370
and scholarly African
American Muslim

02:01:17.370 --> 02:01:19.820
who came here in
the early 1800s.

02:01:19.820 --> 02:01:24.650
Omar Ibn Said's manuscript
shows that he was a scholar,

02:01:24.650 --> 02:01:28.080
he was a world's traveler
before he was even captured

02:01:28.080 --> 02:01:29.380
and enslaved.

02:01:29.380 --> 02:01:32.110
&gt;&gt; It is the only known,
existing manuscript

02:01:32.110 --> 02:01:34.250
in Arabic written by a slave.

02:01:34.250 --> 02:01:37.490
And it's written by a
man who is still a slave.

02:01:37.490 --> 02:01:42.470
He arrived when he was 37.

02:01:42.470 --> 02:01:45.170
He died when he was over 80.

02:01:45.170 --> 02:01:48.360
Over a period of 40
years, he knew English.

02:01:48.360 --> 02:01:52.510
In Arabic he knew that nobody
could understand what he said,

02:01:52.510 --> 02:01:55.060
and therefore he
could be more truthful

02:01:55.060 --> 02:01:57.370
if he wanted, less fearful.

02:01:57.370 --> 02:01:59.400
&gt;&gt; That fact that these
materials are written

02:01:59.400 --> 02:02:03.060
in Arabic sort of changes
what we believe we know

02:02:03.060 --> 02:02:06.640
about American slavery and
about those individuals

02:02:06.640 --> 02:02:08.500
who were enslaved in America.

02:02:08.500 --> 02:02:11.340
In a typical classroom,
when students are introduced

02:02:11.340 --> 02:02:14.850
to American slavery, there is
a section in their textbook.

02:02:14.850 --> 02:02:17.060
And that section in
their textbook may

02:02:17.060 --> 02:02:19.570
or may not introduce
many details

02:02:19.570 --> 02:02:22.140
about specific individuals.

02:02:22.140 --> 02:02:26.640
So I think part of what this
collection does is it lends an

02:02:26.640 --> 02:02:30.940
original voice that we've
never heard before to a story

02:02:30.940 --> 02:02:32.720
that we thought we knew.

02:02:32.720 --> 02:02:37.060
&gt;&gt; It opens a window
into 200 years ago.

02:02:37.060 --> 02:02:38.560
What was West Africa like?

02:02:38.560 --> 02:02:42.270
Who were the people who
were on that continent?

02:02:42.270 --> 02:02:45.870
So we begin asking
new questions.

02:02:45.870 --> 02:02:48.020
The questions about the lives

02:02:48.020 --> 02:02:53.010
of those slaves before
they became slaves.

02:02:53.010 --> 02:02:54.310
[ Music ]

02:02:54.310 --> 02:03:01.040
&gt;&gt; My name is Omar Ibn
Said, my birthplace Futa

02:03:01.040 --> 02:03:04.140
between the two rivers.

02:03:04.140 --> 02:03:09.000
&gt;&gt; He was born in an area
which was between two rivers,

02:03:09.000 --> 02:03:13.580
probably what is Senegal today.

02:03:13.580 --> 02:03:17.080
And there he grows
up and he studies.

02:03:17.080 --> 02:03:19.820
So he says, "I spent
26 years studying."

02:03:19.820 --> 02:03:21.610
And you say, "Okay,
what was he studying?"

02:03:21.610 --> 02:03:24.580
He doesn't elaborate.

02:03:24.580 --> 02:03:27.780
One has to assume that
he went beyond reading

02:03:27.780 --> 02:03:30.130
and writing to doing much more.

02:03:30.130 --> 02:03:36.130
&gt;&gt; Then there came to
our country a big army.

02:03:36.130 --> 02:03:38.210
It killed many people.

02:03:38.210 --> 02:03:42.620
It took me and brought me
to the big sea and sold me

02:03:42.620 --> 02:03:45.430
in the hand of a Christian man.

02:03:45.430 --> 02:03:48.600
&gt;&gt; There was tribal
warfare in the region.

02:03:48.600 --> 02:03:50.210
And he is caught.

02:03:50.210 --> 02:03:53.400
And then he is sold
into slavery.

02:03:53.400 --> 02:04:00.320
He is sold to merchants
who were buying slaves.

02:04:00.320 --> 02:04:07.380
And he is then put on a ship
and he sails for six weeks.

02:04:08.510 --> 02:04:11.040
[ Music ]

02:04:11.040 --> 02:04:14.190
&gt;&gt; He also talked
about his experience

02:04:14.190 --> 02:04:17.360
when he was riding to, making it

02:04:17.360 --> 02:04:22.530
into a place he called
Charles-Town, and being badgered

02:04:22.530 --> 02:04:24.830
and misused and abused.

02:04:24.830 --> 02:04:27.650
To the point that
he had to escape.

02:04:27.650 --> 02:04:29.540
&gt;&gt; So they captured him
and they put him in jail.

02:04:29.540 --> 02:04:34.850
And so he stays there and
he is alone and in a room

02:04:34.850 --> 02:04:36.510
and he begins writing
on the wall.

02:04:36.510 --> 02:04:37.930
He begins writing.

02:04:37.930 --> 02:04:41.120
And he writes in Arabic because
that's the language he knew.

02:04:41.120 --> 02:04:43.740
He could not understand what
people were saying around him.

02:04:43.740 --> 02:04:45.560
&gt;&gt; And they were
curious about this guy

02:04:45.560 --> 02:04:48.000
that wrote this writing.

02:04:48.000 --> 02:04:52.390
They thought that Africans
had no culture nor history,

02:04:52.390 --> 02:04:53.690
couldn't read and write.

02:04:53.690 --> 02:04:56.490
Omar Ibn Said dispels that.

02:04:56.490 --> 02:05:00.770
He could read, he could write
and he was very scholarly.

02:05:00.770 --> 02:05:06.520
&gt;&gt; One Friday, a man
came and opened the door

02:05:06.520 --> 02:05:09.420
of the jail and I saw many men.

02:05:09.420 --> 02:05:10.830
The language was Christian.

02:05:10.830 --> 02:05:12.130
They called to me.

02:05:12.130 --> 02:05:14.950
"Is your name not Omar?

02:05:14.950 --> 02:05:16.270
Is it not Said?"

02:05:16.270 --> 02:05:23.530
I did not understand
the Christian language.

02:05:23.530 --> 02:05:28.410
&gt;&gt; He refers to them as
the Owens, and they are --

02:05:28.410 --> 02:05:33.440
one of them turns out to be
the governor of North Carolina.

02:05:33.440 --> 02:05:38.710
And he takes him in and then
he says that they were good men

02:05:38.710 --> 02:05:42.700
who believed in God,
who had a Bible

02:05:42.700 --> 02:05:45.560
and who read to him the Bible.

02:05:45.560 --> 02:05:49.100
&gt;&gt; Anywhere from
25-28% of the population

02:05:49.100 --> 02:05:51.140
that was brought
here were Muslims.

02:05:51.140 --> 02:05:53.430
The same prophets that we find

02:05:53.430 --> 02:05:55.610
in the Koran we find
in the Bible.

02:05:55.610 --> 02:05:59.320
So they were able to intertwine,
interrelate those experiences.

02:05:59.320 --> 02:06:02.770
&gt;&gt; But when he writes
his biography,

02:06:02.770 --> 02:06:07.610
he begins with a
verse from the Koran.

02:06:07.610 --> 02:06:12.180
And the verse from the Koran is
again a very interesting choice.

02:06:12.180 --> 02:06:17.190
It is the verse which
refers to domination,

02:06:17.190 --> 02:06:19.890
which refers to ownership.

02:06:19.890 --> 02:06:23.490
And in Islam, all
ownership belongs to God.

02:06:23.490 --> 02:06:25.310
God is the only owner.

02:06:25.310 --> 02:06:28.240
It can be understood
as a criticism

02:06:28.240 --> 02:06:30.290
of the whole institution
of slavery.

02:06:30.290 --> 02:06:32.890
He does this in a
subtle way of saying,

02:06:32.890 --> 02:06:35.980
"You really have no right
to own another human being."

02:06:35.980 --> 02:06:37.480
&gt;&gt; They robbed the culture.

02:06:37.480 --> 02:06:39.260
They robbed the identity.

02:06:39.260 --> 02:06:42.420
They disconnected
them from family.

02:06:42.420 --> 02:06:45.020
There was no connection.

02:06:45.020 --> 02:06:50.100
&gt;&gt; I reside in a country
because of the great harm.

02:06:50.100 --> 02:06:55.100
The infidels took me
unjustly and sold me.

02:06:55.100 --> 02:07:00.180
&gt;&gt; It's one of those stories
that will always be relevant.

02:07:00.180 --> 02:07:04.180
Today around the world
there are tens of millions

02:07:04.180 --> 02:07:06.360
of people who are enslaved.

02:07:06.360 --> 02:07:10.430
So Omar Ibn Said
humanizes the experience

02:07:10.430 --> 02:07:12.820
of a person in his own words.

02:07:14.030 --> 02:07:16.040
[ Music ]

02:07:16.040 --> 02:07:17.340
&gt;&gt; This is a voice we
had never heard before.

02:07:17.340 --> 02:07:19.540
And these materials
have been out there.

02:07:19.540 --> 02:07:22.080
What other materials exist?

02:07:22.080 --> 02:07:25.030
What other stories
can we help uncover?

02:07:25.030 --> 02:07:27.820
And how can those stories
together help us better

02:07:27.820 --> 02:07:31.050
understand an episode
of our nation's past

02:07:31.050 --> 02:07:34.110
that maybe we don't understand
as thoroughly as we ought to?

02:07:34.110 --> 02:07:37.890
&gt;&gt; There's a lot of insight
that can be pulled out of it

02:07:37.890 --> 02:07:41.100
if people take it not with
bigotry in their heart

02:07:41.100 --> 02:07:44.590
or arrogance in their heart,
but to look for the insight.

02:07:44.590 --> 02:07:47.670
You see concrete, grass
come up out of concrete

02:07:47.670 --> 02:07:49.870
or trees grow by the concrete.

02:07:49.870 --> 02:07:51.170
So out of the concrete

02:07:51.170 --> 02:07:55.710
of enslavement we found positive
Muslim personalities rising up.

02:07:55.710 --> 02:07:57.680
Things will get better,
things will be better.

02:07:57.680 --> 02:08:00.040
And that's what he
represents: hope,

02:08:00.040 --> 02:08:03.510
that things will get better.

02:08:03.510 --> 02:08:16.040
[ Music ]

02:08:16.040 --> 02:08:18.980
&gt;&gt; The manuscript of Omar
Ibn Said signifies the spread

02:08:18.980 --> 02:08:22.480
of knowledge about the African
Muslim community, specifically

02:08:22.480 --> 02:08:24.710
as it relates to the
American slave trade,

02:08:24.710 --> 02:08:26.200
religion and race relations.

02:08:26.200 --> 02:08:27.500
The other aspect

02:08:27.500 --> 02:08:30.560
of the library's collection is
the African Islamic Manuscript

02:08:30.560 --> 02:08:33.110
Collection, a series
containing such documents

02:08:33.110 --> 02:08:35.610
as the visionary
religious Arabic manuscripts

02:08:35.610 --> 02:08:38.780
of Sheik Son-Asi, a mystical
account of the creation

02:08:38.780 --> 02:08:41.850
of the world and of
mankind by Mohammed Dakar.

02:08:41.850 --> 02:08:45.970
And various translations of
the Omar Ibn Said narrative.

02:08:45.970 --> 02:08:49.420
The attainment and dissemination
of all of these required years

02:08:49.420 --> 02:08:52.050
of correspondence between
significant missionaries,

02:08:52.050 --> 02:08:57.050
ethnographers, historians
and scholarly specialists.

02:08:57.050 --> 02:09:00.570
At the core of this company was
Theodore Dwight, a New Yorker,

02:09:00.570 --> 02:09:02.200
abolitionist and founding member

02:09:02.200 --> 02:09:04.930
of the American Ethnological
Society who campaigned

02:09:04.930 --> 02:09:07.740
for a better understanding
and appreciation

02:09:07.740 --> 02:09:09.190
of African Islamic culture.

02:09:09.190 --> 02:09:14.980
&gt;&gt; He was interested in
introducing African culture

02:09:14.980 --> 02:09:21.540
to this country so people will
understand better you know,

02:09:21.540 --> 02:09:24.860
the backgrounds of
the African people

02:09:24.860 --> 02:09:28.720
and not just seeing
them as slaves.

02:09:28.720 --> 02:09:33.650
So he collected a number of
important manuscripts written

02:09:33.650 --> 02:09:37.330
by the slaves of his time.

02:09:37.330 --> 02:09:42.560
And through the help of various
people including two presidents

02:09:42.560 --> 02:09:44.010
of Liberia.

02:09:44.010 --> 02:09:50.700
So you know, therefore we have
now a collection of 42 items.

02:09:50.700 --> 02:09:55.760
And each one is unique
in its own way.

02:09:55.760 --> 02:09:58.650
&gt;&gt; Long before each of Dwight's
pieces could find a permanent

02:09:58.650 --> 02:10:01.130
place in the archives, the
individual documents passed

02:10:01.130 --> 02:10:02.820
through dozens of hands.

02:10:02.820 --> 02:10:04.730
An extensive and
interconnected chain

02:10:04.730 --> 02:10:08.630
of acquisition brought the
collection to its current home.

02:10:08.630 --> 02:10:11.380
Beginning with Theodore Dwight,
the manuscripts first went

02:10:11.380 --> 02:10:13.470
to David Bliss, a
noted missionary,

02:10:13.470 --> 02:10:17.060
founder of the prestigious
American University of Beirut

02:10:17.060 --> 02:10:19.040
and fellow founding
member of AES.

02:10:19.040 --> 02:10:21.600
Shortly after the documents
were returned to Dwight,

02:10:21.600 --> 02:10:23.450
they passed through the
offices of the first

02:10:23.450 --> 02:10:26.850
and second presidents of
Liberia, Joseph Jenkins Roberts

02:10:26.850 --> 02:10:29.020
and Stephen Allen
Benson, respectively.

02:10:29.020 --> 02:10:32.170
After the documents were
given back once again,

02:10:32.170 --> 02:10:34.650
they were studied by
numismatist Helen Wood,

02:10:34.650 --> 02:10:37.040
likely from his home
state of Massachusetts.

02:10:37.040 --> 02:10:41.350
The collection was then given
to Dr. F. M. Musa and Isaac Byrd

02:10:41.350 --> 02:10:45.230
in order to be translated
from Arabic into English.

02:10:45.230 --> 02:10:47.550
After quite a number of years
with them, the papers went

02:10:47.550 --> 02:10:50.180
to accomplished historian
John Franklin Jameson

02:10:50.180 --> 02:10:51.480
in Washington, DC.

02:10:51.480 --> 02:10:53.450
The last known individual

02:10:53.450 --> 02:10:56.440
to have the Omar Ibn Said
manuscript was Derrick Beard,

02:10:56.440 --> 02:11:00.040
a philanthropist and art
collector based in California.

02:11:00.040 --> 02:11:02.880
This process of analyzing,
translating

02:11:02.880 --> 02:11:05.290
and simply appreciating
the collection created a

02:11:05.290 --> 02:11:09.490
comprehensive web of people all
dedicated to scholarly integrity

02:11:09.490 --> 02:11:11.460
and sharing knowledge.

02:11:11.460 --> 02:11:17.220
Finally, in 2002 the full
collection began its journey

02:11:17.220 --> 02:11:18.520
to the library.

02:11:18.520 --> 02:11:25.560
&gt;&gt; The original owner Derrick
Beard was an art collector.

02:11:25.560 --> 02:11:33.950
And he first displayed the
Omar Ibn Said manuscript here

02:11:33.950 --> 02:11:38.330
at the library in
2002 at a symposium.

02:11:38.330 --> 02:11:42.660
So when the materials were
made available at Sotheby's,

02:11:42.660 --> 02:11:47.380
the library decided to acquire
them and use library funding

02:11:47.380 --> 02:11:52.040
to acquire those
manuscripts in 2017.

02:11:52.040 --> 02:11:54.070
[ Music ]

02:11:54.070 --> 02:11:55.370
&gt;&gt; When broken down,

02:11:55.370 --> 02:11:58.250
the library's basic acquisition
process is really only

02:11:58.250 --> 02:11:59.550
five steps.

02:11:59.550 --> 02:12:02.350
Identification, approval
and funding,

02:12:02.350 --> 02:12:06.200
exchange in partnerships,
copyright deposit and purchase.

02:12:06.200 --> 02:12:08.780
But it's not actually
so straightforward.

02:12:08.780 --> 02:12:11.270
&gt;&gt; It sounds like a very
simple thing to say,

02:12:11.270 --> 02:12:14.920
but this is actually a very,

02:12:14.920 --> 02:12:17.780
pretty big project
involving a lot

02:12:17.780 --> 02:12:21.230
of different offices
collaborating together

02:12:21.230 --> 02:12:25.220
over a period of time in
order to achieve that goal

02:12:25.220 --> 02:12:28.830
of eventually presenting
the collection online

02:12:28.830 --> 02:12:30.740
to the general public, to anyone

02:12:30.740 --> 02:12:33.500
who is interested
in looking at it.

02:12:33.500 --> 02:12:37.750
&gt;&gt; While, the mechanism
and infrastructure

02:12:37.750 --> 02:12:41.860
for how we make it
happen may have changed,

02:12:41.860 --> 02:12:45.670
the purpose behind
it is the same.

02:12:45.670 --> 02:12:49.350
Building the collection,
building up a relationship,

02:12:49.350 --> 02:12:51.720
and you do that through
communication.

02:12:51.720 --> 02:12:55.760
And that communication
improves with each generation

02:12:55.760 --> 02:12:58.520
and technology improvements.

02:12:58.520 --> 02:13:02.920
&gt;&gt; The library is a
research institution,

02:13:02.920 --> 02:13:06.220
meaning like we have you
know, millions and millions

02:13:06.220 --> 02:13:08.940
of materials that are
available for scholars.

02:13:08.940 --> 02:13:14.020
But we also have these materials
for education purposes.

02:13:14.020 --> 02:13:16.010
So teachers will
be able to come in

02:13:16.010 --> 02:13:19.550
and use the Omar Ibn Said
collection for their classroom.

02:13:19.550 --> 02:13:23.970
They can use this collection,
design a history class.

02:13:23.970 --> 02:13:29.340
Scholars can come in,
look at these materials

02:13:29.340 --> 02:13:30.640
from a different perspective

02:13:30.640 --> 02:13:33.080
and write their scholarly
papers or publications.

02:13:33.080 --> 02:13:38.330
And the general public can come
and just look at the collection

02:13:38.330 --> 02:13:41.260
and just simply learn
more about the history

02:13:41.260 --> 02:13:44.630
of this country, about slavery.

02:13:44.630 --> 02:13:52.160
Yeah, so you know, definitely
the collection is of great value

02:13:52.160 --> 02:13:56.670
to our people, not just now.

02:13:56.670 --> 02:13:59.920
It's also important for
generations to come.

02:13:59.920 --> 02:14:03.300
&gt;&gt; So what has happened
is this is just one set

02:14:03.300 --> 02:14:04.910
of documents that's added

02:14:04.910 --> 02:14:09.790
to that rich research
field we wanted to explore.

02:14:09.790 --> 02:14:15.890
And it also helps establish
boundaries, or it helps break

02:14:15.890 --> 02:14:19.350
down boundaries among
those disciplines to say

02:14:19.350 --> 02:14:21.520
that they really are
not that separate.

02:14:21.520 --> 02:14:23.130
They all begin to meld.

02:14:23.130 --> 02:14:29.210
And the beauty of having access
to a broad array of content is

02:14:29.210 --> 02:14:32.610
that it allows the research
of a scholar, the student,

02:14:32.610 --> 02:14:35.560
to be able to pull these pieces
together, see how they do

02:14:35.560 --> 02:14:38.560
over them, how they
intertwine, how they meld

02:14:38.560 --> 02:14:45.700
and how there is likely no real
strong demarcation among all

02:14:45.700 --> 02:14:47.000
of these disciplines.

02:14:47.000 --> 02:14:50.160
&gt;&gt; You have to think about it.

02:14:50.160 --> 02:14:57.740
Theodore Dwight did not put an
emphasis on this manuscript.

02:14:57.740 --> 02:15:00.410
If he did not correspond
with others,

02:15:00.410 --> 02:15:04.570
this manuscript may
not have survived.

02:15:04.570 --> 02:15:10.130
It was his effort to retain,
to keep this manuscript,

02:15:10.130 --> 02:15:14.050
to bring in other scholars
to write about, to translate,

02:15:14.050 --> 02:15:18.380
to communicate and to
retain this collection.

02:15:18.380 --> 02:15:23.030
That made it possible for the
manuscript in a way to survive.

02:15:23.030 --> 02:15:27.000
And so as you see
there are the creators,

02:15:27.000 --> 02:15:30.980
the one who has actually written
the manuscript, Omar Ibn Said.

02:15:30.980 --> 02:15:33.250
And then there are the enablers

02:15:33.250 --> 02:15:37.090
who enable those
materials to be made public.

02:15:37.090 --> 02:15:41.220
And the Library of Congress
is doing the same thing

02:15:41.220 --> 02:15:45.060
by creating a website making
these materials available.

02:15:45.060 --> 02:15:49.190
We enable the learning process

02:15:49.190 --> 02:15:55.510
about the society,
about Omar Ibn Said.

02:15:55.510 --> 02:16:02.060
[ Music ]

02:16:02.060 --> 02:16:03.970
&gt;&gt; Before an artifact
can go on display,

02:16:03.970 --> 02:16:06.400
it must go through a
lengthy conservation process

02:16:06.400 --> 02:16:08.310
that ensures the
artifacts can be enjoyed

02:16:08.310 --> 02:16:10.100
for generations to come.

02:16:10.100 --> 02:16:12.580
Before anything can happen,
the departments involved

02:16:12.580 --> 02:16:15.870
in preservation and presentation
get together and decide

02:16:15.870 --> 02:16:18.320
which artifacts are the
top of their priorities

02:16:18.320 --> 02:16:20.310
and how feasible
each project is.

02:16:20.310 --> 02:16:23.030
After an artifact is
given the green light,

02:16:23.030 --> 02:16:24.360
it heads to conservation

02:16:24.360 --> 02:16:27.340
where it undergoes intense
inspection and repair.

02:16:27.340 --> 02:16:30.000
Shelly Smith, head of book
conservation at the Library

02:16:30.000 --> 02:16:33.510
of Congress, and Sylvia Albro,
senior paper conservator,

02:16:33.510 --> 02:16:36.330
talk to us about the
conservation process.

02:16:36.330 --> 02:16:41.520
&gt;&gt; Broadly, we treat
the collections

02:16:41.520 --> 02:16:42.880
of the Library of Congress.

02:16:42.880 --> 02:16:49.060
We make sure that they are well
cared for, that they are stored

02:16:49.060 --> 02:16:54.830
and housed properly, that
they can be accessed and used

02:16:54.830 --> 02:16:58.500
by researchers and
scholars and visitors.

02:16:58.500 --> 02:17:00.980
&gt;&gt; The conservators told us
about how they get to interact

02:17:00.980 --> 02:17:03.490
with artifacts in unique
ways in order to learn more

02:17:03.490 --> 02:17:06.360
about the historical
context of the documents.

02:17:06.360 --> 02:17:11.750
&gt;&gt; Well, I think that items
have layers and stories to tell.

02:17:11.750 --> 02:17:14.640
And there's their
immediate appearance,

02:17:14.640 --> 02:17:16.260
there's what's written
in the text

02:17:16.260 --> 02:17:17.900
in the case of a manuscript.

02:17:17.900 --> 02:17:21.390
But there's also what
it's composed of,

02:17:21.390 --> 02:17:25.170
how it was designed,
how it was put together.

02:17:25.170 --> 02:17:26.700
It all means something.

02:17:26.700 --> 02:17:29.480
And so you can tell
a different story

02:17:29.480 --> 02:17:31.540
with the technical information

02:17:31.540 --> 02:17:34.400
than necessarily what's
written in the text.

02:17:34.400 --> 02:17:36.900
&gt;&gt; Looking at the Omar
Ibn Said documents,

02:17:36.900 --> 02:17:39.210
the conservators were
able to analyze the paper

02:17:39.210 --> 02:17:40.620
that allowed them
to make predictions

02:17:40.620 --> 02:17:42.990
about the origins
of the document.

02:17:42.990 --> 02:17:45.980
The original autobiography was
written with iron gall ink.

02:17:45.980 --> 02:17:49.610
This ink is known for its
rich color and durability.

02:17:49.610 --> 02:17:51.250
It's created by a
chemical reaction

02:17:51.250 --> 02:17:54.000
between tanic acid
and iron sulfate.

02:17:54.000 --> 02:17:56.580
This causes the tanic acid
to produce a dark color

02:17:56.580 --> 02:17:57.950
when exposed to oxygen.

02:17:57.950 --> 02:18:01.770
Tanic acid is found in galls
which are growths on an oak tree

02:18:01.770 --> 02:18:03.070
in response to parasites.

02:18:03.070 --> 02:18:06.200
To extract the acid,
the galls are crushed,

02:18:06.200 --> 02:18:09.010
boiled or chemically
fermented using mold.

02:18:09.010 --> 02:18:11.780
The fermentation method will
result in the blackest ink

02:18:11.780 --> 02:18:13.080
but takes the longest.

02:18:13.080 --> 02:18:15.820
Because of the acidic
nature, the ink is known

02:18:15.820 --> 02:18:19.160
to be fairly corrosive over
time and prone to color changes.

02:18:19.160 --> 02:18:21.810
The conservators found the
ink had not corroded much

02:18:21.810 --> 02:18:25.540
of the paper so it was likely
of a very high quality.

02:18:25.540 --> 02:18:29.680
&gt;&gt; We try as much as possible
in conservation to be sure

02:18:29.680 --> 02:18:33.740
that what we do doesn't
unalterably change something.

02:18:33.740 --> 02:18:40.820
But sometimes it is necessary
to attempt a treatment procedure

02:18:40.820 --> 02:18:42.150
that has the potential --

02:18:42.150 --> 02:18:43.450
there's always a chance

02:18:43.450 --> 02:18:45.660
that something unexpected
could happen.

02:18:45.660 --> 02:18:50.210
And it involves affair amount
of guts to be able to go through

02:18:50.210 --> 02:18:54.080
and say test and test and
test but then put a piece

02:18:54.080 --> 02:18:55.780
of paper in a bath of water.

02:18:55.780 --> 02:18:58.280
You just have to jump in.

02:18:58.280 --> 02:19:00.050
&gt;&gt; The conservators
have to be very careful

02:19:00.050 --> 02:19:02.050
when interacting
with the documents.

02:19:02.050 --> 02:19:04.560
They made it clear that their
purpose is to make the documents

02:19:04.560 --> 02:19:08.100
as accessible as possible while
maintaining its integrity.

02:19:08.100 --> 02:19:10.870
After conservation has finished
their work on the artifacts,

02:19:10.870 --> 02:19:12.660
they are sent to
the digitization lab

02:19:12.660 --> 02:19:15.440
where they are photographed
and prepared to be put online.

02:19:15.440 --> 02:19:19.380
&gt;&gt; We are responsible
for digitizing items

02:19:19.380 --> 02:19:22.500
from the Cultural
Heritage Collections

02:19:22.500 --> 02:19:26.990
to make them available
online so that people

02:19:26.990 --> 02:19:30.290
around the world can see them.

02:19:30.290 --> 02:19:32.340
&gt;&gt; The lab has a variety
of equipment in order

02:19:32.340 --> 02:19:34.290
to present the artifacts
with the best lighting

02:19:34.290 --> 02:19:36.830
and most accurate
quality available.

02:19:36.830 --> 02:19:39.670
Their equipment ensures that
the files accessible online are

02:19:39.670 --> 02:19:43.280
accurate in replicating what the
documents may be like in person.

02:19:43.280 --> 02:19:48.190
&gt;&gt; New color checker, because
our job is to capture items

02:19:48.190 --> 02:19:51.110
at true to color form.

02:19:51.110 --> 02:19:53.990
Color accuracy is
very important.

02:19:53.990 --> 02:19:57.510
So each color swatch
here has an end point

02:19:57.510 --> 02:20:02.810
which is a number value that we
try to set up the camera toward.

02:20:02.810 --> 02:20:05.750
&gt;&gt; Similar to conservation, the
lab has to be very careful not

02:20:05.750 --> 02:20:08.370
to damage any documents, so
they use special machinery

02:20:08.370 --> 02:20:11.120
to handle them and get
the best picture possible.

02:20:11.120 --> 02:20:14.070
This is the rare book
modulator that has a scanner

02:20:14.070 --> 02:20:16.380
which holds pages flat,
pressed against the glass.

02:20:16.380 --> 02:20:18.470
But the table underneath
the glass moves

02:20:18.470 --> 02:20:20.950
in such a precise manner
that the glass is able

02:20:20.950 --> 02:20:22.290
to apply little to no pressure

02:20:22.290 --> 02:20:24.820
on the book itself,
reducing any damage.

02:20:24.820 --> 02:20:27.340
&gt;&gt; The Omar Ibn Said
documents were so old

02:20:27.340 --> 02:20:28.940
that the digitization
process had

02:20:28.940 --> 02:20:30.960
to take place inside
the conservation lab

02:20:30.960 --> 02:20:32.260
to avoid any damage.

02:20:32.260 --> 02:20:35.840
The library works to ensure
that all artifacts remain intact

02:20:35.840 --> 02:20:38.550
so that they're accessible to
scholars and the general public.

02:20:38.550 --> 02:20:41.320
&gt;&gt; A lot of scholars
and researchers,

02:20:41.320 --> 02:20:44.230
a lot can't come
here to the library.

02:20:44.230 --> 02:20:47.820
And we have a lot of things
here, one of a kind things

02:20:47.820 --> 02:20:53.120
that given -- sometimes
the fragility

02:20:53.120 --> 02:20:56.360
of an item determines
whether it can be served

02:20:56.360 --> 02:20:57.660
to the public or not.

02:20:57.660 --> 02:21:01.070
&gt;&gt; After digitization, the
artifacts are posted online

02:21:01.070 --> 02:21:03.470
for scholars and the
general public to view.

02:21:03.470 --> 02:21:05.900
The library uses a
technique called metadata

02:21:05.900 --> 02:21:08.100
to attach keywords
to various artifacts

02:21:08.100 --> 02:21:10.890
so that anyone can search for a
topic on the library's website.

02:21:10.890 --> 02:21:13.080
&gt;&gt; Some of the things
that we've handled

02:21:13.080 --> 02:21:18.160
in the past are top treasure
items here at the library,

02:21:18.160 --> 02:21:21.930
such as documents like
in the US, for example.

02:21:21.930 --> 02:21:25.420
Which would entail the rough
draft of the Declaration

02:21:25.420 --> 02:21:30.610
of Independence,
Gettysburg address and so on.

02:21:30.610 --> 02:21:33.990
&gt;&gt; To bring out something
that's so iconic

02:21:33.990 --> 02:21:36.300
and see people's reaction to it

02:21:36.300 --> 02:21:40.020
and see them interact
with history.

02:21:40.020 --> 02:21:45.540
And there's something that's
so immediate and intimate

02:21:45.540 --> 02:21:51.450
about a person seeing
a document that is

02:21:51.450 --> 02:21:54.570
so much a part of
our American life.

02:21:54.570 --> 02:21:57.220
&gt;&gt; No matter whether it's the
Declaration of Independence

02:21:57.220 --> 02:21:59.740
or the Omar Ibn Said
manuscripts,

02:21:59.740 --> 02:22:02.100
the Library of Congress
is filled with artifacts

02:22:02.100 --> 02:22:03.910
which are each a
piece in the puzzle

02:22:03.910 --> 02:22:05.700
of America's rich history.

02:22:05.700 --> 02:22:07.890
Today you saw an inside
look at the process

02:22:07.890 --> 02:22:10.810
through which these artifacts
are preserved for scholars,

02:22:10.810 --> 02:22:15.510
researchers and the general
public for generations to come.

02:22:15.510 --> 02:23:34.500
[ Music ]

02:23:40.510 --> 02:23:51.040
[ Music ]

02:23:51.040 --> 02:23:54.960
&gt;&gt; Omar Ibn Said was a wealthy
Islamic scholar who was born

02:23:54.960 --> 02:23:58.760
and educated in an African
region then called Utatolo.

02:23:58.760 --> 02:24:02.540
He was born in the late
1700's and received 25 years

02:24:02.540 --> 02:24:04.250
of schooling in Africa.

02:24:04.250 --> 02:24:08.310
He studied in Bundu under his
brother Sheik Mohammed Said.

02:24:08.310 --> 02:24:11.000
Said was mostly known for
his Arabic autobiography.

02:24:11.000 --> 02:24:13.930
Despite his inability
to speak English,

02:24:13.930 --> 02:24:18.190
his autobiography describes how
he was captured by a great army

02:24:18.190 --> 02:24:19.780
and placed on a great
ship headed

02:24:19.780 --> 02:24:21.080
to Charleston, South Carolina.

02:24:21.080 --> 02:24:24.330
Almost half of all enslaved
Africans were brought

02:24:24.330 --> 02:24:25.720
to Charleston before being sold.

02:24:25.720 --> 02:24:30.880
Said managed to escape his cruel
master and fled to Fayetteville,

02:24:30.880 --> 02:24:33.060
North Carolina where
he was recaptured

02:24:33.060 --> 02:24:34.750
and sent to a prison camp.

02:24:34.750 --> 02:24:37.190
Omar Ibn Said was discovered
and eventually taken

02:24:37.190 --> 02:24:40.150
into the household of
Jim Owen and John Owen

02:24:40.150 --> 02:24:43.370
who was the governor of
North Carolina at that time.

02:24:43.370 --> 02:24:47.110
He remained with the Owens
until his death in 1854.

02:24:47.110 --> 02:24:48.520
He became the first known slave

02:24:48.520 --> 02:24:51.480
to write an autobiography
in Arabic in the US.

02:24:51.480 --> 02:24:55.830
His manuscripts show a long
tradition of written culture

02:24:55.830 --> 02:24:58.140
in Africa at that time.

02:24:58.140 --> 02:25:01.400
They also provide a tremendous
tool for research on Africa

02:25:01.400 --> 02:25:05.350
in the 18th and 19th century.

02:25:05.350 --> 02:25:09.670
&gt;&gt; We wanted to know what
the process was coming

02:25:09.670 --> 02:25:11.870
from Muslim countries
to America.

02:25:11.870 --> 02:25:13.480
When did it start?

02:25:13.480 --> 02:25:17.950
And the earliest we could trace
it back to was from Africa.

02:25:17.950 --> 02:25:20.660
It was Muslims from
Africa who came

02:25:20.660 --> 02:25:25.840
who were the first
Muslims in America.

02:25:25.840 --> 02:25:30.820
And so we invited
different professors

02:25:30.820 --> 02:25:36.210
to cover this conference
on Muslims in America.

02:25:36.210 --> 02:25:41.230
And so we had Sylviane
Diuof from Senegal who came.

02:25:41.230 --> 02:25:45.120
She's actually one of
the writers in this book.

02:25:45.120 --> 02:25:49.170
We had Derrick Beard who came

02:25:49.170 --> 02:25:52.030
and say a few words,
and I love him.

02:25:52.030 --> 02:25:55.310
And then we had professors
from Asia, Pakistan,

02:25:55.310 --> 02:25:57.260
who talked about
the Asian migration.

02:25:57.260 --> 02:25:59.340
We had professors
from the Middle East.

02:25:59.340 --> 02:26:03.020
We spoke about Muslims from
the Middle East coming.

02:26:03.020 --> 02:26:07.490
But the earliest
were from Africa

02:26:07.490 --> 02:26:09.720
and Derrick Beard
was a collector.

02:26:09.720 --> 02:26:12.680
He was not a scholar,
but a collector.

02:26:12.680 --> 02:26:18.960
And he owned the
manuscript of Omar Ibn Said.

02:26:18.960 --> 02:26:21.110
He was the owner.

02:26:21.110 --> 02:26:25.430
And he said he had found it,
he had purchased it and it was

02:26:25.430 --> 02:26:27.760
in his collection, his
family's collection.

02:26:27.760 --> 02:26:31.560
And that was 2002.

02:26:31.560 --> 02:26:34.920
And when he talked about
it and he displayed it

02:26:34.920 --> 02:26:38.700
for all the people who had come
to the conference, he said,

02:26:38.700 --> 02:26:41.210
"It should be here at
the Library of Congress.

02:26:41.210 --> 02:26:43.610
It should be part of the
library's collections."

02:26:43.610 --> 02:26:45.720
And we all said, "Yes,
of course it should be."

02:26:45.720 --> 02:26:50.330
But at that point he was not
selling and we were not buying.

02:26:50.330 --> 02:26:54.760
But that's how we
found out it existed.

02:26:54.760 --> 02:26:58.820
&gt;&gt; It provided historical
information

02:26:58.820 --> 02:27:05.040
and cultural information about
the existence of Africans

02:27:05.040 --> 02:27:07.520
who came here enslaved.

02:27:07.520 --> 02:27:10.890
And they were Muslims.

02:27:10.890 --> 02:27:16.040
You don't really hear
much, at least I didn't

02:27:16.040 --> 02:27:26.440
when I was growing up, about
the Muslim contributions

02:27:26.440 --> 02:27:27.840
in the United States.

02:27:27.840 --> 02:27:33.760
We're still learning
more about Omar Ibn Said

02:27:33.760 --> 02:27:37.810
because he wrote his
own autobiography.

02:27:37.810 --> 02:27:43.930
And when we talk about
enslaved Africans here

02:27:43.930 --> 02:27:47.200
and what they contributed
to the United States,

02:27:47.200 --> 02:27:56.020
you don't really realize
who individuals were.

02:27:56.020 --> 02:28:03.620
And we learned a lot just from
this one man, and a little bit

02:28:03.620 --> 02:28:08.360
about his life in the past.

02:28:08.360 --> 02:28:16.400
But we have other histories that
are being researched and found

02:28:16.400 --> 02:28:21.810
and we get more information.

02:28:21.810 --> 02:28:24.660
And I thought that
was very important.

02:28:24.660 --> 02:28:28.830
&gt;&gt; In 2017, Derrick
Beard, the previous owner

02:28:28.830 --> 02:28:31.290
of the manuscripts, reached
out to the Library of Congress

02:28:31.290 --> 02:28:33.570
to inform them of
his declining health.

02:28:33.570 --> 02:28:36.040
He also informed them
of his willingness

02:28:36.040 --> 02:28:38.340
to sell his Oma Ibn Collection

02:28:38.340 --> 02:28:41.600
to the well-known auction
house Sotheby's located

02:28:41.600 --> 02:28:43.290
in London, England.

02:28:43.290 --> 02:28:48.250
&gt;&gt; All these materials
were in fact in England.

02:28:48.250 --> 02:28:54.100
And so they were then shipped
to us here in a big, big crate.

02:28:54.100 --> 02:28:58.310
I mean, it was a huge crate of
wood with metal all wrapped up.

02:28:58.310 --> 02:29:03.650
And we had screws on the box.

02:29:03.650 --> 02:29:09.980
And it arrived to great fanfare
to Washington and we took one

02:29:09.980 --> 02:29:14.130
of the major rooms here
next to us in Rare Books

02:29:14.130 --> 02:29:15.470
which is a beautiful room.

02:29:15.470 --> 02:29:19.300
And everybody gathered,
25 chiefs, directors,

02:29:19.300 --> 02:29:23.320
important people from
around the library.

02:29:23.320 --> 02:29:28.690
Everybody came and we
started unscrewing the box.

02:29:28.690 --> 02:29:30.560
And people were taking turns

02:29:30.560 --> 02:29:33.910
and they were taking
photographs and so on.

02:29:33.910 --> 02:29:37.230
And this is how it arrived.

02:29:37.230 --> 02:29:39.850
&gt;&gt; Before the library
acquired these manuscripts,

02:29:39.850 --> 02:29:43.480
Derrick Beard traveled to many
places granting various academic

02:29:43.480 --> 02:29:45.910
institutions, art
galleries, museums

02:29:45.910 --> 02:29:48.180
and even historians
an opportunity

02:29:48.180 --> 02:29:49.800
to examine the documents.

02:29:49.800 --> 02:29:51.490
&gt;&gt; We are called the
Library of Congress

02:29:51.490 --> 02:29:53.330
and of course this
is how it started.

02:29:53.330 --> 02:29:57.330
But we are also the National
Library of the United States.

02:29:57.330 --> 02:30:04.030
So to have this here means
that A, it was purchased

02:30:04.030 --> 02:30:06.300
with taxpayers' dollars.

02:30:06.300 --> 02:30:09.980
It was purchased by Americans.

02:30:09.980 --> 02:30:11.280
It is America money.

02:30:11.280 --> 02:30:13.440
It is not a private
collector's money.

02:30:13.440 --> 02:30:16.580
It is the money coming
from our tax dollars

02:30:16.580 --> 02:30:18.940
that purchased this manuscript.

02:30:18.940 --> 02:30:21.740
And it is available for every
American to come and see

02:30:21.740 --> 02:30:25.000
and to use and to do research.

02:30:25.000 --> 02:30:28.180
&gt;&gt; Mr. Beard granted a Yale
professor the permission

02:30:28.180 --> 02:30:30.740
to make copies of
the autobiography

02:30:30.740 --> 02:30:34.060
and publish a book titled,
A Muslim American Slave,

02:30:34.060 --> 02:30:36.470
the Life of Omar Ibn Said.

02:30:36.470 --> 02:30:39.960
&gt;&gt; In Islam, all
ownership belongs to God.

02:30:39.960 --> 02:30:43.070
Only God is an owner.

02:30:43.070 --> 02:30:45.140
No one owns anything.

02:30:45.140 --> 02:30:48.450
We come, we live
and then we die.

02:30:48.450 --> 02:30:51.140
We really are not owners.

02:30:51.140 --> 02:30:54.210
But why does he start his
biography with [inaudible]?

02:30:54.210 --> 02:31:00.210
Really, he is telling the
people that ownership is God's.

02:31:00.210 --> 02:31:01.510
It's not yours.

02:31:01.510 --> 02:31:04.790
You have no right to
own and certainly not

02:31:04.790 --> 02:31:07.450
to own another human being.

02:31:07.450 --> 02:31:10.160
So what I am simply
saying here is

02:31:10.160 --> 02:31:14.430
that Omar Ibn Said's
autobiography opens up a world.

02:31:14.430 --> 02:31:17.850
A world we are looking at,

02:31:17.850 --> 02:31:21.910
a history which has really
not been written yet.

02:31:21.910 --> 02:31:26.550
There is so much that
can be discovered

02:31:26.550 --> 02:31:30.250
from existing manuscripts
in Africa, okay?

02:31:30.250 --> 02:31:31.840
This one was written here.

02:31:31.840 --> 02:31:34.530
However, he comes from a
long tradition of those

02:31:34.530 --> 02:31:36.630
who wrote manuscripts there.

02:31:36.630 --> 02:31:41.820
See? So Senegal has a large
collection of manuscripts.

02:31:41.820 --> 02:31:44.260
Mali has a wonderful
collection of manuscripts.

02:31:44.260 --> 02:31:50.050
Nigeria is enormously
rich with manuscripts.

02:31:50.050 --> 02:31:53.820
And those manuscripts are
about everything from medicine

02:31:53.820 --> 02:31:59.700
to the stars, astronomy
and cosmology, to culture,

02:31:59.700 --> 02:32:06.500
traditions, food,
anything you want.

02:32:06.500 --> 02:32:09.200
They need to be preserved.

02:32:09.200 --> 02:32:13.540
So in a way Omar Ibn
Said is leading the way

02:32:13.540 --> 02:32:17.780
and taking us back to
West Africa and saying,

02:32:17.780 --> 02:32:23.660
"I'm bringing you this, but
look at what my ancestors did

02:32:23.660 --> 02:32:26.770
and what they wrote and
what they contributed."

02:32:26.770 --> 02:32:29.560
And those things need
to be preserved as well.

02:32:29.560 --> 02:32:33.560
We need to go back and we need
to go to Nigeria, we need to go

02:32:33.560 --> 02:32:35.780
to Mali, we need
to go everywhere.

02:32:35.780 --> 02:32:38.300
And we need to digitize
these manuscripts.

02:32:38.300 --> 02:32:44.590
&gt;&gt; You know, it reveals a lot
about, like we said earlier,

02:32:44.590 --> 02:32:48.740
the history and the culture of
the two continents which are

02:32:48.740 --> 02:32:52.630
so far apart and yet they
are being brought together

02:32:52.630 --> 02:32:53.930
by this man.

02:32:53.930 --> 02:32:58.410
And so when we're looking at
history, studying history,

02:32:58.410 --> 02:33:01.340
American history, we actually
also have to look at the rest

02:33:01.340 --> 02:33:03.590
of the world because
we're all connected.

02:33:03.590 --> 02:33:07.920
So to me that's the
importance of this collection.

02:33:07.920 --> 02:33:11.770
And so I'm very excited to be
able to work with all the items

02:33:11.770 --> 02:33:13.870
and make sure they
are properly digitized

02:33:13.870 --> 02:33:18.080
and make sure they are
presented on our website

02:33:18.080 --> 02:33:21.680
so more people will be
able to access them.

02:33:21.680 --> 02:33:25.190
&gt;&gt; In July of 2018, Derrick
Beard sadly passed away.

02:33:25.190 --> 02:33:27.990
But with the help of the Library
of Congress, they've continued

02:33:27.990 --> 02:33:31.160
to preserve the story of
Omar Ibn Said with the help

02:33:31.160 --> 02:33:33.120
of their conservation team.

02:33:33.120 --> 02:33:35.550
Since the acquisition
of these manuscripts,

02:33:35.550 --> 02:33:37.610
they've made a replica
of these documents

02:33:37.610 --> 02:33:41.140
which maintains its authentic
texture and appearance.

02:33:41.140 --> 02:33:42.900
&gt;&gt; So we use a device
similar to these,

02:33:42.900 --> 02:33:45.860
but we hand carry a camera
to the conservation division

02:33:45.860 --> 02:33:49.380
and that's what we have done
to do the Omar Said papers.

02:33:49.380 --> 02:33:51.470
They were done on-site
in conservation

02:33:51.470 --> 02:33:52.790
because they couldn't travel

02:33:52.790 --> 02:33:55.010
to this building
given their fragility

02:33:55.010 --> 02:33:56.790
and conditions that
they were in.

02:33:56.790 --> 02:33:59.420
So as conservation
was treating those,

02:33:59.420 --> 02:34:01.920
they would quickly call us and
say, "Hey, we have 10 ready."

02:34:01.920 --> 02:34:04.560
We'd go over and shoot
them and create the files.

02:34:04.560 --> 02:34:08.730
The handling was done by
them on-site and we would set

02:34:08.730 --> 02:34:11.980
up our camera and shoot
right there on the premises.

02:34:11.980 --> 02:34:15.900
So as we had ten documents
or maybe 20 ready to go,

02:34:15.900 --> 02:34:19.140
I'd say within an hour
to two hours we were able

02:34:19.140 --> 02:34:23.430
to capture all of them
from front to back.

02:34:23.430 --> 02:34:25.900
And so you have the
digitization side,

02:34:25.900 --> 02:34:27.460
because it's all
instant capture,

02:34:27.460 --> 02:34:30.800
our newest technology
is very, very fast now.

02:34:30.800 --> 02:34:33.530
So the handling of the item
could take a lot longer

02:34:33.530 --> 02:34:37.030
than the actual capturing
process.

02:34:37.030 --> 02:34:39.040
[ Inaudible ]

02:34:39.040 --> 02:34:40.340
And it does in this case.

02:34:40.340 --> 02:34:42.170
What we tried to
do is salvage it

02:34:42.170 --> 02:34:49.140
by getting really good digital
files, and later historians

02:34:49.140 --> 02:34:52.250
or whoever can take those
images and work with them

02:34:52.250 --> 02:34:55.010
on their end using Photoshop

02:34:55.010 --> 02:34:57.620
to reestablish what the
colors might have been.

02:34:57.620 --> 02:35:00.690
So there's a lot of that that
goes on outside of our realm.

02:35:00.690 --> 02:35:02.310
This is why it's very
important to send them

02:35:02.310 --> 02:35:04.470
up to a color checker
like I showed you.

02:35:04.470 --> 02:35:07.770
Because that ensures that you're
getting the color accuracy

02:35:07.770 --> 02:35:09.310
in today's color.

02:35:09.310 --> 02:35:12.000
But it can be recreated
based on those numbers

02:35:12.000 --> 02:35:13.580
that we achieve on
those targets.

02:35:13.580 --> 02:35:17.770
The life cycle of our
technology runs about ten years.

02:35:17.770 --> 02:35:21.140
So up until ten years ago
we were using old limier

02:35:21.140 --> 02:35:23.360
technology, which
doing a newspaper

02:35:23.360 --> 02:35:25.440
like you just saw
would be a pass

02:35:25.440 --> 02:35:28.930
of about 5-7 minutes per sheet.

02:35:28.930 --> 02:35:30.230
Today it's two seconds.

02:35:30.230 --> 02:35:31.530
&gt;&gt; Right.

02:35:31.530 --> 02:35:35.040
&gt;&gt; With no compromising quality
or anything of that nature.

02:35:35.040 --> 02:35:39.340
&gt;&gt; It can cause endless
discussion amongst researchers

02:35:39.340 --> 02:35:42.640
when someone says, "I think
this is in this person's hand."

02:35:42.640 --> 02:35:44.430
And someone may disagree
and think

02:35:44.430 --> 02:35:46.390
that it looks more
like another person.

02:35:46.390 --> 02:35:50.620
But when you've got a manuscript
like this that has the main body

02:35:50.620 --> 02:35:53.520
of the manuscript but then
it clearly has marginality

02:35:53.520 --> 02:35:55.890
that has been written by
someone else, it has pagination

02:35:55.890 --> 02:35:57.290
that may have been
written by someone else,

02:35:57.290 --> 02:35:58.950
it has a cover that's
been added that has

02:35:58.950 --> 02:36:02.920
yet another style of hand on it.

02:36:02.920 --> 02:36:06.520
It's educated guesses
based on evidence.

02:36:06.520 --> 02:36:09.350
And the more data points
you have, the better.

02:36:09.350 --> 02:36:11.890
So the more examples that
you have, the better.

02:36:11.890 --> 02:36:19.330
But mostly it is just
a good -- absolutely.

02:36:19.330 --> 02:36:21.600
&gt;&gt; In addition to
-- you see a lot

02:36:21.600 --> 02:36:24.240
of microscope difference
between inks.

02:36:24.240 --> 02:36:25.540
&gt;&gt; Right.

02:36:25.540 --> 02:36:29.080
&gt;&gt; And you can see a lot of UV.

02:36:29.080 --> 02:36:33.350
And we also have infrared
photography that we can apply,

02:36:33.350 --> 02:36:35.940
and that's very useful
if somebody's tried

02:36:35.940 --> 02:36:38.990
to make a correction
in the script.

02:36:38.990 --> 02:36:40.290
&gt;&gt; Right.

02:36:40.290 --> 02:36:43.280
&gt;&gt; You can usually see a
difference in one of those kinds

02:36:43.280 --> 02:36:47.040
of lighting conditions.

02:36:47.040 --> 02:36:49.060
[ Music ]

02:36:49.060 --> 02:36:53.620
&gt;&gt; Abolitionist people, they
were studying these cultures

02:36:53.620 --> 02:36:57.310
in West Africa because
they became convinced

02:36:57.310 --> 02:37:02.870
that the only way of stopping
the slave trade was having the

02:37:02.870 --> 02:37:06.970
Muslim cultures intervene.

02:37:06.970 --> 02:37:12.720
So this book is his writing
of his meeting of a lot

02:37:12.720 --> 02:37:16.100
of different people's
journeys into West Africa.

02:37:16.100 --> 02:37:18.960
Think how large that could be.

02:37:18.960 --> 02:37:20.850
So all these different
people's journeys

02:37:20.850 --> 02:37:22.400
and what they discovered.

02:37:22.400 --> 02:37:25.250
And he comes to a conclusion
at the end of his book:

02:37:25.250 --> 02:37:28.290
the only way that
we're going to be able

02:37:28.290 --> 02:37:30.980
to really say something
meaningful

02:37:30.980 --> 02:37:36.420
about these cultures is
if we learn the language

02:37:36.420 --> 02:37:42.100
and live there for a
substantial period of time.

02:37:42.100 --> 02:37:46.520
&gt;&gt; So my background is in
literature and language.

02:37:46.520 --> 02:37:50.510
So I was very interested
in the African story

02:37:50.510 --> 02:37:57.010
about how this is the only known
slave narrative that was written

02:37:57.010 --> 02:38:01.180
by a slave who was in
captivity in Arabic.

02:38:01.180 --> 02:38:06.170
So I was very interested
in that aspect and the kind

02:38:06.170 --> 02:38:14.450
of authenticity that went to the
manuscript and also the kinds

02:38:14.450 --> 02:38:16.910
of questions that that
raised about others like him,

02:38:16.910 --> 02:38:21.660
about Arabic speakers who
were slave sand their stories.

02:38:21.660 --> 02:38:24.910
So that was one of
my access points.

02:38:24.910 --> 02:38:31.560
And I think also just
the nuance that it added

02:38:31.560 --> 02:38:36.030
to my understanding or my
learning about American slavery,

02:38:36.030 --> 02:38:38.230
I think that was
also interesting.

02:38:38.230 --> 02:38:40.720
Because I had not
heard about him.

02:38:40.720 --> 02:38:44.710
I didn't know a lot
about the history

02:38:44.710 --> 02:38:47.760
of Muslim slaves in America.

02:38:47.760 --> 02:38:53.080
So I think you know, for me
it was good to be exposed

02:38:53.080 --> 02:38:55.030
to something that I
didn't know anything about.

02:38:55.030 --> 02:38:58.860
And frankly now I really feel
like I should learn more.

02:38:58.860 --> 02:39:02.500
And like I said, I'm going
back to kind of being proud

02:39:02.500 --> 02:39:06.260
of the institution,
being proud to work here.

02:39:06.260 --> 02:39:09.580
Because I think that
it's wonderful

02:39:09.580 --> 02:39:16.400
to present another voice
and present another example.

02:39:16.400 --> 02:39:23.550
And to really show diverse
voices, even diversity

02:39:23.550 --> 02:39:25.910
within diversity, so to speak.

02:39:25.910 --> 02:39:33.690
So my hope is that bringing
this collection forward,

02:39:33.690 --> 02:39:40.920
that many people who perhaps
had never heard of the Library

02:39:40.920 --> 02:39:43.580
of Congress or had never been
to the Library of Congress

02:39:43.580 --> 02:39:47.080
or had never used it for
research will be able

02:39:47.080 --> 02:39:52.840
to in some ways see themselves
here and be able to see

02:39:52.840 --> 02:39:56.780
that there is a value in
history, in their history.

02:39:56.780 --> 02:40:01.460
And will be encouraged
to come here or go online

02:40:01.460 --> 02:40:04.670
and further their own research,
whether that's, like I said,

02:40:04.670 --> 02:40:06.670
for their academic
projects or even

02:40:06.670 --> 02:40:09.720
for their personal research.

02:40:09.720 --> 02:40:14.670
So I really hope that they
can also see the value

02:40:14.670 --> 02:40:15.970
in their own stories.

02:40:15.970 --> 02:40:18.980
&gt;&gt; Throughout the process of
creating this film, my peers

02:40:18.980 --> 02:40:20.280
and I gained a wealth

02:40:20.280 --> 02:40:21.870
of knowledge concerning
the Islamic background

02:40:21.870 --> 02:40:24.280
of many Africans
enslaved in America.

02:40:24.280 --> 02:40:26.330
These were human beings who
were treated as animals.

02:40:26.330 --> 02:40:29.370
Human beings with their own
rich culture, set of beliefs,

02:40:29.370 --> 02:40:31.220
way of life and families.

02:40:31.220 --> 02:40:32.520
It is our hope that
the publishing

02:40:32.520 --> 02:40:34.090
of this document will
help change the perception

02:40:34.090 --> 02:40:37.510
of Islam's history in America.

