02:56:46.040 --> 02:56:51.220
&gt;&gt; Because it speaks of
a specific individual.

02:56:51.220 --> 02:56:54.240
His thoughts, his
feelings, his story.

02:56:54.240 --> 02:57:00.280
Omar Ibn Said is a scholar
in what is today Senegal.

02:57:00.280 --> 02:57:03.120
And he was sold into slavery.

02:57:03.120 --> 02:57:09.920
He ran away and was
caught as a runaway slave.

02:57:09.920 --> 02:57:14.370
And in jail he began
writing on the walls.

02:57:14.370 --> 02:57:16.930
And that's when people
began wondering

02:57:16.930 --> 02:57:20.100
who he was, what he was writing.

02:57:20.100 --> 02:57:26.190
This autobiography is the only
known autobiography as a slave

02:57:26.190 --> 02:57:29.560
in Arabic in the United States.

02:57:29.560 --> 02:57:32.780
When he was writing, he knew

02:57:32.780 --> 02:57:36.390
that his owners could
not read it.

02:57:36.390 --> 02:57:40.310
So Arabic is in a way a language

02:57:40.310 --> 02:57:42.000
in which he could
be more truthful,

02:57:42.000 --> 02:57:44.580
more candid about
his real feelings.

02:57:46.470 --> 02:57:52.750
Using the original of course
is what every researcher would

02:57:52.750 --> 02:57:54.050
like to do.

02:57:54.050 --> 02:57:57.260
However, the paper is very
brittle, very delicate.

02:57:57.260 --> 02:58:01.130
So it was important
to make facsimiles

02:58:01.130 --> 02:58:04.750
so that people would get
a sense of the item and

02:58:04.750 --> 02:58:07.890
yet not damage it
by looking at it.

02:58:07.890 --> 02:58:11.930
And preservation did a fantastic
job trying to preserve it

02:58:11.930 --> 02:58:14.400
and to maintain it so that
it can continue existing

02:58:14.400 --> 02:58:16.700
for generations to come.

02:58:17.730 --> 02:58:22.860
&gt;&gt; So what we're really hoping
to achieve with this documentary

02:58:22.860 --> 02:58:26.920
that we're doing, Richard
Wright, we hope to really appeal

02:58:26.920 --> 02:58:28.220
to the younger audience.

02:58:28.220 --> 02:58:30.440
Because we want them to know
more about their black history.

02:58:30.440 --> 02:58:33.120
For me it's amazing
because I had never heard

02:58:33.120 --> 02:58:34.760
of Omar Ibn Said at all.

02:58:34.760 --> 02:58:38.610
So to me it's just like
an amazing experience.

02:58:38.610 --> 02:58:43.060
&gt;&gt; A collection such as this
one questions the very principle

02:58:43.060 --> 02:58:45.680
of enslaving another
human being.

02:58:45.680 --> 02:58:50.070
Hopefully it will be a tool
of education, of learning,

02:58:50.070 --> 02:58:51.910
of better understanding others,

02:58:51.910 --> 02:58:55.550
of understanding the
history of Africa as well.

02:58:55.550 --> 02:58:59.380
It is this very personal
way of writing

02:58:59.380 --> 02:59:02.430
and of talking that reaches us.

02:59:02.430 --> 02:59:05.890
It reaches everyone
across the 200 years.

02:59:05.890 --> 02:59:08.510
And speaks to people today.

