to share with us as you talk.

03:00:53.960 --> 03:00:55.260
&gt;&gt; Shelly Smith: We do.

03:00:55.260 --> 03:00:59.000
Conservation is pretty visual,
so we included some photographs

03:00:59.000 --> 03:01:01.110
to kind of illustrate
some of our processes.

03:01:01.110 --> 03:01:04.180
So first of all, I would like
to say that this really was just

03:01:04.180 --> 03:01:06.430
such a big team effort.

03:01:06.430 --> 03:01:09.750
This fabulous team up here
and many other team members

03:01:09.750 --> 03:01:11.380
that are here in the audience.

03:01:11.380 --> 03:01:12.680
Way to go team.

03:01:12.680 --> 03:01:19.220
Good job. So I am the head of
the Book Conservation Section

03:01:19.220 --> 03:01:22.370
and I was asked to oversee and
coordinate the preservation

03:01:22.370 --> 03:01:24.670
and conservation activities
that would be required

03:01:24.670 --> 03:01:27.630
to make the Omar Ibn
Said collection available

03:01:27.630 --> 03:01:30.480
for whatever use,
whether that be research

03:01:30.480 --> 03:01:32.550
or exhibition or other.

03:01:32.550 --> 03:01:36.360
Now luckily, before the
collection even arrived,

03:01:36.360 --> 03:01:41.020
we were able to see a few
images of several items

03:01:41.020 --> 03:01:43.390
in the collection that were
from the auction catalog

03:01:43.390 --> 03:01:45.380
that was produced by Southaby's,
and that's what you see

03:01:45.380 --> 03:01:48.440
on the screen right now,
are these couple of images

03:01:48.440 --> 03:01:49.890
that were from Southaby's.

03:01:49.890 --> 03:01:54.250
This was really helpful to
get a very basic understanding

03:01:54.250 --> 03:01:56.450
of what the scope
of this project was.

03:01:56.450 --> 03:02:01.750
We knew it was 42 items, but
not having seen any of them,

03:02:01.750 --> 03:02:04.720
we didn't know what that
would really entail.

03:02:04.720 --> 03:02:09.200
And that's because conservation
can take quite some time

03:02:09.200 --> 03:02:10.500
from start to finish.

03:02:10.500 --> 03:02:13.650
Especially so many
of the activities

03:02:13.650 --> 03:02:16.630
that we do ideally
should happen in sequence

03:02:16.630 --> 03:02:19.510
and can't really
happen concurrently.

03:02:19.510 --> 03:02:23.800
So to be able to know up front
if this was a six-month project

03:02:23.800 --> 03:02:28.050
or a multi-year project,
which is not inconceivable,

03:02:28.050 --> 03:02:30.000
was of course very helpful.

03:02:30.000 --> 03:02:35.650
So this initial brief
view of the collection

03:02:35.650 --> 03:02:38.690
at least gave us the
confidence that the schedule

03:02:38.690 --> 03:02:41.070
that the library was
hoping for, to get this done

03:02:41.070 --> 03:02:44.260
in approximately 18
months, was possible.

03:02:44.260 --> 03:02:49.540
And if 18 months seems like a
long time, just the conservation

03:02:49.540 --> 03:02:54.670
and preservation parts of this
included detailed assessment,

03:02:54.670 --> 03:02:56.830
documentation, and
that includes written

03:02:56.830 --> 03:02:59.490
and photographic documentation
which is a very important part

03:02:59.490 --> 03:03:01.820
of the conservation process.

03:03:01.820 --> 03:03:06.220
Treatment of course and
housing, making the facsimiles,

03:03:06.220 --> 03:03:10.670
assisting with digitization and
being a part of the multiplicity

03:03:10.670 --> 03:03:15.650
that would all be happening
around this project as well.

03:03:15.650 --> 03:03:19.520
So as I mentioned,
in an ideal world,

03:03:19.520 --> 03:03:22.450
a lot of these activities
would happen in sequence.

03:03:22.450 --> 03:03:23.920
But because of the timeline,

03:03:23.920 --> 03:03:27.780
because the library wanted
these materials to be available

03:03:27.780 --> 03:03:31.390
as soon as possible, it
meant that a lot of this had

03:03:31.390 --> 03:03:32.710
to happen concurrently.

03:03:32.710 --> 03:03:36.850
There were a lot of things
happening all at the same time.

03:03:36.850 --> 03:03:41.220
So by far I think the most
meaningful thing that I did

03:03:41.220 --> 03:03:43.960
to contribute to the
success of this project was

03:03:43.960 --> 03:03:48.260
that I asked Sylvia
Albro, this really talented

03:03:48.260 --> 03:03:54.170
and qualified conservator, to
take care of the assessment

03:03:54.170 --> 03:03:56.330
and the treatment and
the documentation.

03:03:56.330 --> 03:03:57.630
So I'm going to hand
it over to Sylvia

03:03:57.630 --> 03:03:58.930
to talk about those things.

