03:04:09.880 --> 03:04:13.140
and for really the joy
of participating in it.

03:04:13.140 --> 03:04:17.860
Because we know that his voice,
the voice of Omar Ibn Said,

03:04:17.860 --> 03:04:19.390
spoke for a lot of people.

03:04:19.390 --> 03:04:22.830
And we all felt very
privileged to be part of trying

03:04:22.830 --> 03:04:25.970
to get that voice out.

03:04:25.970 --> 03:04:30.140
Now I cannot see the
screens as well as you can.

03:04:30.140 --> 03:04:37.950
But I will just point out that
-- I will talk to this screen

03:04:37.950 --> 03:04:40.970
but I'll try to say left
and right so that people

03:04:40.970 --> 03:04:43.160
who are watching that
screen will know what I'm

03:04:43.160 --> 03:04:44.460
talking about.

03:04:44.460 --> 03:04:47.430
If we go back to the slide
that was right before Shelly,

03:04:47.430 --> 03:04:50.750
that one, we can see
on the right-hand side

03:04:50.750 --> 03:04:54.620
that was the condition of
the manuscript when it came

03:04:54.620 --> 03:04:56.070
to the conservation lab.

03:04:56.070 --> 03:04:58.400
And after it arrived,
of course the African

03:04:58.400 --> 03:05:01.280
and Middle Eastern
Division made sure that all

03:05:01.280 --> 03:05:04.540
of the objects arrived from
