03:05:11.200 --> 03:05:17.160
And I also had the opportunity
to read the translation

03:05:17.160 --> 03:05:20.630
and it was so wonderful
to meet the author today

03:05:20.630 --> 03:05:21.930
of the translation.

03:05:21.930 --> 03:05:25.600
And so because before
attempting work on any object

03:05:25.600 --> 03:05:28.820
at the Library of this value,
you want to know what you have

03:05:28.820 --> 03:05:30.680
and what you're working with.

03:05:30.680 --> 03:05:32.440
And it was important
to know what was said.

03:05:32.440 --> 03:05:33.990
I don't read Arabic.

03:05:33.990 --> 03:05:36.890
But the materials of
this project also speak

03:05:36.890 --> 03:05:38.190
their language.

03:05:38.190 --> 03:05:41.800
And a conservator has to become
kind of very familiar with them,

03:05:41.800 --> 03:05:43.290
sort of intimate
with the materials.

03:05:43.290 --> 03:05:45.120
So at the beginning, you can see

03:05:45.120 --> 03:05:48.160
that there were some
damages visible.

03:05:48.160 --> 03:05:51.100
The way that the cover
which was put on 20 years

03:05:51.100 --> 03:05:54.430
after Omar had written
the script --

03:05:54.430 --> 03:06:00.110
20 years later it was
stab-sewn on the side.

03:06:00.110 --> 03:06:04.770
And all of the original
paper was breaking

03:06:04.770 --> 03:06:08.310
where those stitches were.

03:06:08.310 --> 03:06:11.610
And so together with
the curators,

03:06:11.610 --> 03:06:14.560
we looked at the item
and we made a plan.

03:06:14.560 --> 03:06:18.930
It was a joint decision
that we would take it apart

03:06:18.930 --> 03:06:22.280
so that it would
eventually open fully.

03:06:22.280 --> 03:06:25.740
With the stitching on the
side added later like that,

03:06:25.740 --> 03:06:27.850
the manuscript did
not open safely

03:06:27.850 --> 03:06:30.570
and it cracked all
along that fold.

03:06:30.570 --> 03:06:35.690
So Shelly, the book conservator,
we moved the stitching.

03:06:35.690 --> 03:06:40.200
And one of the things
that we found

03:06:40.200 --> 03:06:41.730
when we removed the stitching is

03:06:41.730 --> 03:06:45.420
that actually there was
another layer of stitching

03:06:45.420 --> 03:06:47.690
that held the manuscript
through the fold

03:06:47.690 --> 03:06:48.990
that had been invisible.

03:06:48.990 --> 03:06:53.620
And that was much closer to the
execution of the manuscript.

03:06:53.620 --> 03:06:56.210
So we had to take
both threads out.

03:06:56.210 --> 03:06:59.420
They both were made of cotton,
but they were very different.

03:06:59.420 --> 03:07:01.160
And we saved them of course.

03:07:01.160 --> 03:07:05.910
And later in the project
we found that this thread

03:07:05.910 --> 03:07:10.450
that had been used
to sew the cover

03:07:10.450 --> 03:07:13.140
to the manuscript was the
same thread that was found

03:07:13.140 --> 03:07:16.370
on the translations
by Isaac Byrd.

03:07:16.370 --> 03:07:19.950
So it was important to save
that and make that connection.

03:07:19.950 --> 03:07:23.090
Whereas the thread that was
used to sew through the fold

03:07:23.090 --> 03:07:26.500
of the manuscript was the
same as one that was found

03:07:26.500 --> 03:07:29.340
on the manuscripts that
had been commissioned

03:07:29.340 --> 03:07:31.650
from Arabic scribes
in West Africa.

03:07:31.650 --> 03:07:33.870
So there was a connection
with that thread

03:07:33.870 --> 03:07:36.120
and those manuscripts.

03:07:36.120 --> 03:07:38.710
So let's go to the next slide.

03:07:38.710 --> 03:07:41.790
And you can see on
one of the pages part

03:07:41.790 --> 03:07:43.470
of the page was missing.

03:07:43.470 --> 03:07:47.100
So we were looking at
the ink and the paper.

03:07:47.100 --> 03:07:49.090
We have actually
done a lot of work

03:07:49.090 --> 03:07:52.250
on iron gall ink preservation
here at the Library of Congress.

03:07:52.250 --> 03:07:54.820
Some of my colleagues
are very expert in this.

03:07:54.820 --> 03:07:57.590
We were beneficiaries
of their research.

03:07:57.590 --> 03:08:02.150
And so we looked at the
document using ultraviolet light

03:08:02.150 --> 03:08:03.860
which is a tool.

03:08:03.860 --> 03:08:06.720
You can see what the manuscript
looked like on the right

03:08:06.720 --> 03:08:08.020
under ultraviolet light.

03:08:08.020 --> 03:08:11.690
And that shows us what
the deterioration process

03:08:11.690 --> 03:08:12.990
of the ink is.

03:08:12.990 --> 03:08:15.400
This ink was actually
in very good condition.

03:08:15.400 --> 03:08:19.020
And as the students so
amply talked about --

03:08:19.020 --> 03:08:20.840
I won't go into iron
gall ink again,

03:08:20.840 --> 03:08:23.640
because they gave a
very good explanation.

03:08:23.640 --> 03:08:27.470
It turned out to be in really
reasonably good condition.

03:08:27.470 --> 03:08:30.610
And the paper was
of good quality.

03:08:30.610 --> 03:08:33.940
It's made of rag which is
a cotton-linen mixture.

03:08:33.940 --> 03:08:36.680
It's a wove paper
without a watermark.

03:08:36.680 --> 03:08:39.390
And it's a machine-made paper.

03:08:39.390 --> 03:08:42.130
We think that it was made in
America but we can't prove

03:08:42.130 --> 03:08:48.040
that because there's no
watermark or blind stamp on it.

03:08:48.040 --> 03:08:51.450
So it did not require any
kind of chemical treatment.

03:08:51.450 --> 03:08:54.760
It simply required
repair of the pages.

03:08:54.760 --> 03:08:56.720
We did take extensive
photographs

03:08:56.720 --> 03:08:58.020
so that we can use them

03:08:58.020 --> 03:09:00.550
to monitor whether the
ink deteriorates further

03:09:00.550 --> 03:09:01.850
in the future.

03:09:01.850 --> 03:09:07.480
There were a few areas in the
script that were heavily applied

03:09:07.480 --> 03:09:10.580
and there it was breaking
through the paper.

03:09:13.600 --> 03:09:18.490
So here you see the different
steps, the different tools

03:09:18.490 --> 03:09:21.070
and the different papers
used to mend the manuscript.

03:09:21.070 --> 03:09:23.500
There were at least
six different kinds.

03:09:23.500 --> 03:09:27.480
I primarily used lightweight
Japanese papers that were toned

03:09:27.480 --> 03:09:30.970
to match the different
colors of the paper.

03:09:30.970 --> 03:09:33.680
And two different adhesives.

03:09:33.680 --> 03:09:36.620
Reed starch paste which is
a traditional conservation

03:09:36.620 --> 03:09:39.840
adhesive was used in
areas with no ink.

03:09:39.840 --> 03:09:43.670
But where there was mending that
was required in inked areas,

03:09:43.670 --> 03:09:46.830
we used a non-aqueous
adhesive applied

03:09:46.830 --> 03:09:49.830
that all mends are
reversible in the future.

03:09:49.830 --> 03:09:54.480
But that will not cause any
kind of reaction with the ink.

03:09:54.480 --> 03:09:59.780
And here I'd like to make
a comment about a couple

03:09:59.780 --> 03:10:03.210
of graduate students that
helped me on this project.

03:10:03.210 --> 03:10:06.940
They worked on some of
the other items that were

03:10:06.940 --> 03:10:09.630
in the collection in
addition to the Omar Ibn Said.

03:10:09.630 --> 03:10:15.140
And here we see Marie Keita
Mora who's repairing some

03:10:15.140 --> 03:10:18.380
of the publisher's
scripts that were part

03:10:18.380 --> 03:10:20.590
of the 41 other items
in the collection.

03:10:20.590 --> 03:10:24.030
We also had Mary
Elizabeth Watson who's here,

03:10:24.030 --> 03:10:27.520
and Grace Walters
who also assisted.

03:10:33.060 --> 03:10:37.590
The cover did require
a chemical treatment.

03:10:37.590 --> 03:10:40.150
The paper was very
different than the text paper.

03:10:40.150 --> 03:10:42.500
It actually had a lot
of straw threads in it.

03:10:42.500 --> 03:10:46.380
It was kind of the equivalent
of sort of a paper bag quality

03:10:46.380 --> 03:10:49.730
and it actually had
discolored Omar's text

03:10:49.730 --> 03:10:52.240
at the front and back pages.

03:10:52.240 --> 03:10:56.400
And it had a very
low pH, under four.

03:10:56.400 --> 03:10:59.260
We tried to aim for a
neutral pH with paper

03:10:59.260 --> 03:11:01.410
to be stable for the future.

03:11:01.410 --> 03:11:04.980
The ink was tested
thoroughly and it was able

03:11:04.980 --> 03:11:07.440
to undergo aqueous treatment.

03:11:07.440 --> 03:11:13.250
And we did that with an alkaline
water bath, mixed with alcohol.

03:11:13.250 --> 03:11:15.830
And you can see there
it's being immersed.

03:11:15.830 --> 03:11:20.570
And after it came out and
it was dried, it was resized

03:11:20.570 --> 03:11:25.500
with gelatin to help with
the future handling stability

03:11:25.500 --> 03:11:29.580
of this paper.

03:11:32.310 --> 03:11:33.720
Let's see.

03:11:33.720 --> 03:11:37.380
Oh. Okay, here you can see a
picture of before treatment

03:11:37.380 --> 03:11:39.460
on the left where
you can see that some

03:11:39.460 --> 03:11:42.660
of the pages had
separated, and you can see

03:11:42.660 --> 03:11:44.590
where mending was required.

03:11:44.590 --> 03:11:47.400
And then after treatment
on the right.

03:11:47.400 --> 03:11:51.630
And I thought I would show
page one of Omar's script

03:11:51.630 --> 03:11:53.390
because of course
the cover is put

03:11:53.390 --> 03:11:57.520
on in the English
orientation, but the text opens

03:11:57.520 --> 03:11:59.610
in the opposite direction.

03:11:59.610 --> 03:12:03.800
So that is actually
the first page.

03:12:11.120 --> 03:12:14.670
The cover required a little
bit of mending on the spine

03:12:14.670 --> 03:12:17.320
and on the corners
and that was also done

03:12:17.320 --> 03:12:19.620
with a tinted Japanese paper.

03:12:19.620 --> 03:12:21.950
And as I said, we
try to do repairs

03:12:21.950 --> 03:12:25.220
that don't look like
they're repairs.

03:12:25.220 --> 03:12:28.620
We try to keep the
manuscript looking as authentic

03:12:28.620 --> 03:12:30.020
and original as possible.

03:12:30.020 --> 03:12:33.480
We don't want our
thumbprint to be on there.

03:12:33.480 --> 03:12:37.510
So we hope that it
just enables handling

03:12:37.510 --> 03:12:42.700
without making any
alterations to the authenticity.

03:12:45.180 --> 03:12:53.100
And one last thing, imaging
can tell you material things

03:12:53.100 --> 03:12:55.760
about the manuscript that
you don't immediately see

03:12:55.760 --> 03:12:57.330
in visible light.

03:12:57.330 --> 03:13:00.100
And some of the other
manuscripts

03:13:00.100 --> 03:13:02.520
in this collection are
very interesting in terms

03:13:02.520 --> 03:13:04.750
of what their paper has to say.

03:13:04.750 --> 03:13:08.430
For instance, on the right you
can see a blind stamp in one

03:13:08.430 --> 03:13:11.480
of the papers that was used

03:13:11.480 --> 03:13:15.320
by the commissioned
West African scribes

03:13:15.320 --> 03:13:18.660
to write their documents, that
Theodore Dwight collected.

03:13:18.660 --> 03:13:20.420
And it shows that the paper

03:13:20.420 --> 03:13:24.550
that he used actually
came from Massachusetts.

03:13:24.550 --> 03:13:28.120
So it's a whole collection of
very interesting blind stamps

03:13:28.120 --> 03:13:30.140
in these 41 documents
that are going

03:13:30.140 --> 03:13:33.380
to make an excellent
research project for someone.

03:13:33.380 --> 03:13:36.550
And then what you see on the
lower left is another one

03:13:36.550 --> 03:13:38.650
of the 41 documents
in the collection.

03:13:38.650 --> 03:13:43.520
It's a travel payer, a
very beautiful document

03:13:43.520 --> 03:13:47.410
with Arabic writing in a
circle that is a talisman

03:13:47.410 --> 03:13:48.710
that a traveler would take.

03:13:48.710 --> 03:13:52.250
And that paper happened to have
an Italian watermark in it,

03:13:52.250 --> 03:13:53.550
which is very interesting.

03:13:53.550 --> 03:13:58.430
It's known that the paper trade
was wide from Europe to Africa.

03:13:58.430 --> 03:14:02.980
But here's an example of the
watermark that proves that.

