03:15:02.020 --> 03:15:03.450
Now as far as the facsimile,

03:15:03.450 --> 03:15:06.240
this isn't something
that we normally do.

03:15:06.240 --> 03:15:10.240
We just in talking
with our colleagues

03:15:10.240 --> 03:15:13.980
in the custodial divisions, we
knew that there would be a lot

03:15:13.980 --> 03:15:17.030
of interest and that
people would really want

03:15:17.030 --> 03:15:18.500
to handle the original
manuscript.

03:15:18.500 --> 03:15:21.710
And that it was fragile.

03:15:21.710 --> 03:15:24.840
It had been well handled over
its lifetime and we wanted

03:15:24.840 --> 03:15:27.100
to try to minimize that
as much as possible.

03:15:27.100 --> 03:15:30.760
But to make a facsimile
to allow researchers

03:15:30.760 --> 03:15:35.520
to really get the sense
of the artifact itself,

03:15:35.520 --> 03:15:37.140
we thought would be
really important.

03:15:37.140 --> 03:15:44.530
And so I had never
done this before,

03:15:44.530 --> 03:15:50.000
but I was optimistic
that I could do this.

03:15:50.000 --> 03:15:53.130
And in finding different
kinds of handmade paper

03:15:53.130 --> 03:15:57.910
that were very similar to the
original and experimenting

03:15:57.910 --> 03:16:02.880
with printing methods, I was
able to make several copies

03:16:02.880 --> 03:16:06.300
that will be available
both for use in the Africa

03:16:06.300 --> 03:16:09.500
and Middle Eastern Division
and in the Rare Books

03:16:09.500 --> 03:16:11.120
and Special Collections
Division.

03:16:11.120 --> 03:16:14.150
And then finally we
house the items and most

03:16:14.150 --> 03:16:16.630
of those were in
-- oh sorry, yes.

03:16:16.630 --> 03:16:18.250
Oh, so before and afters, right?

03:16:18.250 --> 03:16:22.640
So on the left is the original

03:16:22.640 --> 03:16:25.290
and on the right
is the facsimile.

03:16:25.290 --> 03:16:28.460
And on the next one
is an opening.

03:16:28.460 --> 03:16:30.590
And then again on the
left is the original

03:16:30.590 --> 03:16:32.410
and on the right
is the facsimile.

03:16:32.410 --> 03:16:34.800
Trying to keep the
sense of the original

03:16:34.800 --> 03:16:38.220
with the facsimile
as much as possible.

03:16:38.220 --> 03:16:41.040
We housed all 42 of the items.

03:16:41.040 --> 03:16:43.420
Most of them were in
acid-free paper folders

03:16:43.420 --> 03:16:48.650
that our conservation staff
member Mary Elizabeth Watson

03:16:48.650 --> 03:16:52.860
constructed two fantastic
custom-made cloth-covered

03:16:52.860 --> 03:16:55.500
clamshell boxes for
both the main manuscript

03:16:55.500 --> 03:16:58.260
and for one of the facsimiles.

03:16:58.260 --> 03:17:00.150
There, finally.

03:17:00.150 --> 03:17:02.280
[ Laughter ]

03:17:02.280 --> 03:17:03.580
&gt;&gt; Beacher Wiggins: All right.

03:17:03.580 --> 03:17:06.380
You may have covered some of
this, but as all of us know,

03:17:06.380 --> 03:17:10.360
the reason that we collect any
of this content is to share it

03:17:10.360 --> 03:17:12.550
and have researchers
have access to it.

03:17:12.550 --> 03:17:15.510
So a couple of questions,
and you hit on some of this.

03:17:15.510 --> 03:17:19.870
The first one is, are there
any observations that either

03:17:19.870 --> 03:17:25.270
of you have in terms of how
what you did affect a researcher

03:17:25.270 --> 03:17:28.410
in looking at and
accessing this?

03:17:28.410 --> 03:17:30.870
I picked up some of that
as you were talking.

03:17:30.870 --> 03:17:34.100
But in case you wanted
to highlight any of that?

03:17:34.100 --> 03:17:37.640
&gt;&gt; Sylvia Albro: Well, as I
said, there is material evidence

03:17:37.640 --> 03:17:40.260
that can contribute
to the story.

03:17:40.260 --> 03:17:44.750
And if we in any way can
document that and include

03:17:44.750 --> 03:17:48.680
that with the collection so
that when scholars come to look

03:17:48.680 --> 03:17:50.940
at it, they have
also that evidence,

03:17:50.940 --> 03:17:54.790
I think it can contribute
to their appreciation

03:17:54.790 --> 03:17:56.760
or to their investigations.

03:17:56.760 --> 03:18:00.040
And some of that includes
information about the paper,

03:18:00.040 --> 03:18:05.240
information about these sewing
threads and sewing construction.

03:18:06.270 --> 03:18:11.510
Origins of some of the paper
when we know and any kind

03:18:11.510 --> 03:18:13.870
of alterations that
have been made.

03:18:13.870 --> 03:18:17.190
We save everything, we
document everything.

03:18:17.190 --> 03:18:19.340
And we're always
available for consultation.

03:18:19.340 --> 03:18:20.640
&gt;&gt; Beacher Wiggins: And
where do you store this?

03:18:20.640 --> 03:18:21.940
How will anyone know?

03:18:21.940 --> 03:18:24.200
Has this been passed on?

03:18:24.200 --> 03:18:27.430
&gt;&gt; Sylvia Albro: Well, we write
an extensive treatment report

03:18:27.430 --> 03:18:29.800
and that will accompany
the item.

03:18:29.800 --> 03:18:33.340
In some cases it's
also kept in our files.

03:18:33.340 --> 03:18:35.400
We have a lot of
digital photographs

03:18:35.400 --> 03:18:37.280
of before and after treatment.

03:18:37.280 --> 03:18:39.840
Those are also available
if necessary.

03:18:39.840 --> 03:18:43.360
And we printed out a lot of
our information and included it

03:18:43.360 --> 03:18:47.710
in the files with the
conserved documents when it went

03:18:47.710 --> 03:18:49.670
to the Rare Book Division.

03:18:49.670 --> 03:18:53.710
&gt;&gt; Beacher Wiggins: And is
there a methodology that you use

03:18:53.710 --> 03:18:59.670
when you get something like
the Omar Ibn Said documents

03:18:59.670 --> 03:19:02.950
to determine how you want
to do your conservation?

03:19:02.950 --> 03:19:06.730
Do you get a team to
pull that together?

03:19:06.730 --> 03:19:08.440
&gt;&gt; Shelly Smith:
Usually it's a balance.

03:19:08.440 --> 03:19:10.040
You did the treatment.

03:19:10.040 --> 03:19:13.440
&gt;&gt; Sylvia Albro: We
definitely consult

03:19:13.440 --> 03:19:17.190
with the curatorial department
that's associated with the item.

03:19:17.190 --> 03:19:19.390
In this case it was
the AMA team.

03:19:19.390 --> 03:19:22.280
And we write a proposal.

03:19:22.280 --> 03:19:23.650
We look at it together.

03:19:23.650 --> 03:19:26.300
We think of three
things in particular:

03:19:26.300 --> 03:19:31.330
the value of the item of
course, the condition the item

03:19:31.330 --> 03:19:34.380
and how the item is
going to be used.

03:19:34.380 --> 03:19:37.870
So those are three factors
that we discuss and we look

03:19:37.870 --> 03:19:40.500
at the item together, and
we come up with a plan.

03:19:40.500 --> 03:19:43.370
And we write up our proposal.

03:19:43.370 --> 03:19:46.190
It gets signed off
on if it's approved.

03:19:46.190 --> 03:19:47.890
And as we're going
through the treatment,

03:19:47.890 --> 03:19:51.350
we often have questions
and we regularly consult.

03:19:51.350 --> 03:19:54.820
It's the richness of the library
that we have so many specialists

03:19:54.820 --> 03:20:00.030
in so many areas that can
really inform what we do.

03:20:00.030 --> 03:20:01.330
&gt;&gt; Beacher Wiggins: Great.

03:20:01.330 --> 03:20:02.630
Thank you.

03:20:02.630 --> 03:20:03.930
Now we'll move on.

03:20:03.930 --> 03:20:08.160
Those of us at the
library know that one

03:20:08.160 --> 03:20:14.450
of Dr. Hayden's goals is to have
the library's content digitized

03:20:14.450 --> 03:20:16.220
and made accessible
to the world.

03:20:16.220 --> 03:20:18.290
She doesn't want it just
to be here on Capital Hill.

03:20:18.290 --> 03:20:23.310
So now we turn to the
digitization aspect of it.

03:20:23.310 --> 03:20:29.820
And we'll ask Domenic to
give us a background run

03:20:29.820 --> 03:20:32.140
through what happened to get us

03:20:32.140 --> 03:20:34.400
to this point for
the digitization.

03:20:34.400 --> 03:20:35.700
Domenic?

03:20:35.700 --> 03:20:37.160
&gt;&gt; Domenico Sergi: Okay,
thank you, Beacher.

03:20:37.160 --> 03:20:39.310
My name is Domenic and I am head

03:20:39.310 --> 03:20:41.730
of the digital scan
center here at the library.

03:20:41.730 --> 03:20:47.640
And this project came up
rather suddenly, I think.

03:20:47.640 --> 03:20:49.550
I certainly wasn't
prepared for it.

03:20:49.550 --> 03:20:52.250
But working with
conservation and Sam here

03:20:52.250 --> 03:20:55.370
with the digital
conversion team.

03:20:55.370 --> 03:20:57.040
Yes. I'm sorry, is that better?

03:20:57.040 --> 03:21:01.050
Should I start over?

03:21:01.050 --> 03:21:04.410
So we were working closely
with the conservation staff

03:21:04.410 --> 03:21:08.200
and Sam here to my right

03:21:08.200 --> 03:21:10.890
who coordinated all the
digital ID's for the items.

03:21:10.890 --> 03:21:14.340
So that way we keep all
the pagination correctly

03:21:14.340 --> 03:21:16.370
because some of the
items were backwards

03:21:16.370 --> 03:21:18.180
in how they were paginated.

03:21:18.180 --> 03:21:20.220
The orientation being
a foreign language,

03:21:20.220 --> 03:21:22.940
it has to be presented
correctly.

03:21:22.940 --> 03:21:25.040
So with their guidance
we were able

03:21:25.040 --> 03:21:29.200
to do all of that in one sweep.

03:21:30.270 --> 03:21:33.410
Shelly and company made
our end really easy.

03:21:33.410 --> 03:21:37.050
So we showed up at their
lab with our equipment set

03:21:37.050 --> 03:21:40.440
up on site and they
did all of the handling

03:21:40.440 --> 03:21:42.890
as these items were treated.

03:21:42.890 --> 03:21:46.560
They'd call us over, we'd
come over, image them,

03:21:46.560 --> 03:21:48.930
and take the images
and then put them

03:21:48.930 --> 03:21:51.420
into our post-processing effort.

03:21:51.420 --> 03:21:55.120
Which entails the cropping,
rotating and pagination.

03:21:55.120 --> 03:22:00.900
And the setting up of the
camera is unique in that we have

03:22:00.900 --> 03:22:04.300
to shoot color checkers
for color accuracy.

03:22:04.300 --> 03:22:08.550
It's important when you're doing
facsimiles or if these are used

03:22:08.550 --> 03:22:12.540
in publications that
the colors are correct.

03:22:12.540 --> 03:22:17.530
We shoot -- in this particular
case we did these at 600 PPI

03:22:17.530 --> 03:22:21.270
so that we could get down
to the grain of the paper.

03:22:21.270 --> 03:22:24.840
It's also for scholars to have
the ability of studying them

03:22:24.840 --> 03:22:28.150
for the inks that
were used or have had.

03:22:28.150 --> 03:22:31.650
Our goal is always to
keep the images true

03:22:31.650 --> 03:22:34.840
to the authenticity
of the object.

03:22:34.840 --> 03:22:38.680
So we show all edges,
gathers, how they're sewn,

03:22:38.680 --> 03:22:40.680
it's all in the image.

03:22:40.680 --> 03:22:43.510
And that's it.

03:22:43.510 --> 03:22:46.860
&gt;&gt; Beacher Wiggins:
Did a particular set

03:22:46.860 --> 03:22:51.250
of documents present any
particular challenges you

03:22:51.250 --> 03:22:55.000
thought about, the
digitization process?

03:22:55.000 --> 03:22:58.380
&gt;&gt; Domenico Sergi: Well, some
of the challenges were you have

03:22:58.380 --> 03:23:01.130
to make sure the lighting was
set up correctly for contrast,

03:23:01.130 --> 03:23:03.760
for example, so that
there are minimal shadows.

03:23:03.760 --> 03:23:06.790
Some of the items may have
had a little bit of lifting

03:23:06.790 --> 03:23:11.420
or they were dog-eared in one
corner which may cause a shadow.

03:23:11.420 --> 03:23:13.600
So we correct for all of that.

03:23:13.600 --> 03:23:15.930
The images online
look really nice.

03:23:15.930 --> 03:23:20.290
The website is beautiful and
we've really enjoyed working

03:23:20.290 --> 03:23:23.340
on this whole effort
with everybody involved.

03:23:23.340 --> 03:23:25.110
&gt;&gt; Beacher Wiggins:
No new equipment

03:23:25.110 --> 03:23:27.490
or machinery was
needed to pull this off?

03:23:27.490 --> 03:23:29.410
&gt;&gt; Domenico Sergi: No, no new.

03:23:29.410 --> 03:23:33.830
In 2009 we did a pretty big
acquisition of new equipment.

03:23:33.830 --> 03:23:38.160
We've moved to new technology
which is instant capture now.

03:23:38.160 --> 03:23:42.860
And we're using cameras that
range from 70 megapixels,

03:23:42.860 --> 03:23:45.570
80 on up to 100 megapixels.

03:23:45.570 --> 03:23:48.590
For this particular project
we used the 80 megapixel

03:23:48.590 --> 03:23:50.290
and shot these items at a 1-to-1

03:23:50.290 --> 03:23:55.020
of their original
size at 600 PPI.

03:23:55.020 --> 03:23:56.470
&gt;&gt; Beacher Wiggins: Thank you.

