03:53:26.540 --> 03:53:29.340
Just a quick question to Sylvia.

03:53:29.340 --> 03:53:32.690
I'm sorry to ask you to repeat
yourself, but your story

03:53:32.690 --> 03:53:36.020
about the threads was
absolutely fascinating.

03:53:36.020 --> 03:53:40.270
And you mentioned that the cover
stitching is the same thread

03:53:40.270 --> 03:53:43.710
as that used in other
Isaac Bird translations.

03:53:43.710 --> 03:53:47.680
But I didn't catch what you
said about the earlier threading

03:53:47.680 --> 03:53:50.190
that you had found
underneath that and what

03:53:50.190 --> 03:53:53.220
that connected to
in your research.

03:53:53.220 --> 03:53:56.150
&gt;&gt; Sylvia Albro:
Okay, thank you.

03:53:56.150 --> 03:54:00.980
The earlier thread which is very
different from the thread used

03:54:00.980 --> 03:54:06.200
to attach the cover, was
used to sew through the fold

03:54:06.200 --> 03:54:09.630
of Omar Ibn Said's manuscript.

03:54:09.630 --> 03:54:14.720
But we noticed since we were
working on all 42 objects

03:54:14.720 --> 03:54:20.450
in the same spate of time, that
the same thread had been used

03:54:20.450 --> 03:54:26.170
to sew the solicited manuscripts
that were from West Africa

03:54:26.170 --> 03:54:28.510
that were primarily --

03:54:28.510 --> 03:54:30.980
the calligraphy was

03:54:30.980 --> 03:54:37.960
by an individual identified
as Mohammed Decker.

03:54:37.960 --> 03:54:41.690
And so we'll have to have
the historians explain more

03:54:41.690 --> 03:54:43.390
about who he was.

03:54:43.390 --> 03:54:49.340
But Theodore Dwight wrote to
the president of Liberia asking

03:54:49.340 --> 03:54:53.200
if he could procure some
manuscripts from the part

03:54:53.200 --> 03:54:57.650
of West Africa that Omar Ibn
Said was from in an attempt

03:54:57.650 --> 03:55:00.990
to understand more about what
the culture of the people

03:55:00.990 --> 03:55:02.470
who lived in that area were.

03:55:02.470 --> 03:55:08.390
And so those manuscripts are
also multi-page manuscripts

03:55:08.390 --> 03:55:09.950
and they're in this collection

03:55:09.950 --> 03:55:13.250
and they also required
some conservation.

03:55:13.250 --> 03:55:16.260
Because pages were falling out.

03:55:16.260 --> 03:55:19.550
But they were sewn
with the same thread.

03:55:19.550 --> 03:55:23.410
So to me that means that the
person that collected these

03:55:23.410 --> 03:55:28.760
in the US probably
sewed all of those.

03:55:28.760 --> 03:55:33.220
But we have photographs
before the treatment

03:55:33.220 --> 03:55:37.320
and we've saved the threads,
and some that didn't have

03:55:37.320 --> 03:55:39.900
to be disbound were
not disbound.

03:55:39.900 --> 03:55:45.100
We only took out the thread if
it was preventing the manuscript

03:55:45.100 --> 03:55:50.020
from opening or if pages
were falling out and broken.

03:55:50.020 --> 03:55:54.200
So we would not typically
remove a thread unless it has

03:55:54.200 --> 03:55:59.510
to in order to facilitate
the use of the manuscript.

03:56:01.170 --> 03:56:02.770
&gt;&gt; Beacher Wiggins: It just
